1
00:00:31,009 --> 00:00:33,445
So our Undercover Chef,

2
00:00:33,445 --> 00:00:35,514
we're rolling into day two now.

3
00:00:35,514 --> 00:00:38,383
Out of five days, this is day two.

4
00:00:38,383 --> 00:00:40,986
Truth is, we're really running out of time.

5
00:00:40,986 --> 00:00:41,954
- Right?
- Yep, exactly.

6
00:00:41,954 --> 00:00:43,455
- Burned a whole day already.
- For real.

7
00:00:43,455 --> 00:00:48,093
After getting through
that first day in a total blur,

8
00:00:48,093 --> 00:00:50,508
bet your head was spinning
before you fell asleep.

9
00:00:50,508 --> 00:00:51,730
Probably couldn't even sleep, huh?

10
00:00:51,730 --> 00:00:53,098
[Heading into day two]
How was it for you?

11
00:00:53,098 --> 00:00:55,534
First off, a harsh reality check.

12
00:00:55,534 --> 00:00:56,535
A major reality check.

13
00:00:56,535 --> 00:00:58,170
It's harder than I thought
to reach the next level.

14
00:00:58,170 --> 00:01:00,138
- That's the thought that hit me.
- Right.

15
00:01:00,138 --> 00:01:03,475
- That part was tough.
- You've got Lu above you,

16
00:01:03,475 --> 00:01:05,277
- and then Sorem suddenly shows up too.
- Right.

17
00:01:05,277 --> 00:01:06,879
So now

18
00:01:06,879 --> 00:01:10,449
[Too many levels to climb]
there are so many steps you've got to climb.

19
00:01:10,449 --> 00:01:14,386
That thought kept creeping in,
like, can I really break through all this?

20
00:01:14,386 --> 00:01:16,555
- Right, can I get through it?
- Yeah.

21
00:01:16,555 --> 00:01:18,790
- How was it for you, Ji Sun?
- I've got some experience,

22
00:01:18,790 --> 00:01:20,859
[24 years of know-how I built up]
so naturally

23
00:01:20,859 --> 00:01:22,761
- I figured I could show plenty of it off.
- Yeah.

24
00:01:22,761 --> 00:01:24,029
But it turns out,

25
00:01:24,029 --> 00:01:26,832
no matter how much experience the rookie has,

26
00:01:26,832 --> 00:01:29,301
[Settling into someone else's kitchen is rough]
it was hard to adjust to that life.

27
00:01:29,301 --> 00:01:31,336
To communal living, that kind of life.

28
00:01:31,336 --> 00:01:34,139
And me...
I went in expecting a tiny little place.

29
00:01:34,139 --> 00:01:35,140
[Grand]
It was even more so for her.

30
00:01:35,140 --> 00:01:37,476
- Because it's huge.
- Right. You'd pictured something modest,

31
00:01:37,476 --> 00:01:39,611
- like an old mom-and-pop spot.
- Yeah, that's what I thought.

32
00:01:39,611 --> 00:01:40,946
How was it for you, Sung Jun?

33
00:01:40,946 --> 00:01:42,414
For me,

34
00:01:42,414 --> 00:01:44,683
[Once day two rolled around]
the warm-up's over.

35
00:01:44,683 --> 00:01:46,852
- The warm-up's over now.
- Now it begins.

36
00:01:46,852 --> 00:01:49,087
- All according to plan.
- Right on track, just as planned.

37
00:01:49,087 --> 00:01:50,155
- Right on track.
- Right.

38
00:01:50,155 --> 00:01:53,258
- You probably slept great too.
- I was out the second I lay down.

39
00:01:53,258 --> 00:01:55,961
I usually have terrible insomnia!

40
00:01:55,961 --> 00:01:58,196
Turns out it was
because I wasn't working enough.

41
00:01:58,196 --> 00:01:59,498
- Now that I'm working again.
- Right.

42
00:01:59,498 --> 00:02:01,967
You have to be physically exhausted to sleep.

43
00:02:01,967 --> 00:02:03,869
- I only recently stopped being the rookie.
- In a sense.

44
00:02:03,869 --> 00:02:05,737
So that gave me an edge, I'd say.

45
00:02:05,737 --> 00:02:08,774
More than the two of you, honestly,
it was a more familiar place.

46
00:02:08,774 --> 00:02:10,642
I worked in Naples,

47
00:02:10,642 --> 00:02:14,313
and I head to Naples once or twice every year,

48
00:02:14,313 --> 00:02:16,615
so...

49
00:02:16,615 --> 00:02:17,716
it felt like coming home.

50
00:02:17,716 --> 00:02:19,384
It was easier for me to adjust.

51
00:02:19,384 --> 00:02:21,520
The setup for the Italian persona
just clicked perfectly.

52
00:02:21,520 --> 00:02:23,188
[An Italian's challenge, more or less]

53
00:02:23,188 --> 00:02:25,257
But he wasn't there that long, was he?

54
00:02:25,257 --> 00:02:27,492
- Long for what?
- The truth is...

55
00:02:27,492 --> 00:02:29,528
[Kim Pung, Sung Jun's Ultimate Counter]
you were in Naples for what, nine months?

56
00:02:29,528 --> 00:02:31,797
- No, I mean...
- Right? Nine months total.

57
00:02:31,797 --> 00:02:32,664
- Fact.
- A whole year.

58
00:02:32,664 --> 00:02:33,999
The fact is it was nine months,

59
00:02:33,999 --> 00:02:36,034
- and you never made it to a full year.
- I don't really remember.

60
00:02:36,034 --> 00:02:37,135
- Exactly.
- It's like this.

61
00:02:37,135 --> 00:02:39,504
It's like this. I lived in LA for 12 years.

62
00:02:39,504 --> 00:02:43,075
The guy who took one trip to LA
has more to say about it.

63
00:02:43,075 --> 00:02:46,144
[The one bursting with love for Naples!]
- Right. - After living there.

64
00:02:46,144 --> 00:02:48,292
Always brimming with confidence,

65
00:02:48,292 --> 00:02:50,048
our man Chef Kwon Sung Jun,

66
00:02:50,048 --> 00:02:53,418
one Italian phrase from Chef Sam Kim.

67
00:02:53,418 --> 00:02:55,587
- One phrase in Italian.
- Sure.

68
00:02:55,587 --> 00:02:58,290
It's actually the opposite of his motto.

69
00:02:58,290 --> 00:02:59,691
[Sung Jun's motto]
Instead of "Mai paura,"

70
00:02:59,691 --> 00:03:02,861
maybe it's time for some real "paura."

71
00:03:02,861 --> 00:03:06,198
My motto is "Mai paura,"
which means "Don't be afraid."

72
00:03:06,198 --> 00:03:07,399
But now it's time to be afraid.

73
00:03:07,399 --> 00:03:08,567
Get a little scared.

74
00:03:08,567 --> 00:03:10,936
- You should be sweating a bit.
- Paura-hae.

75
00:03:10,936 --> 00:03:14,006
[Want to see the rookie shaking just once]
Strangely, that scene never happens.

76
00:03:14,006 --> 00:03:17,442
[Hmm...]
I want something big to happen once.

77
00:03:17,442 --> 00:03:18,810
Same here.

78
00:03:18,810 --> 00:03:21,313
- Just once, I want him to really get it.
- Right.

79
00:03:21,313 --> 00:03:23,048
That won't happen easily.

80
00:03:23,048 --> 00:03:25,550
- It won't be easy.
- It should though.

81
00:03:26,418 --> 00:03:28,065
[Undercover rookie day 1.5,
Sam Kwon, not Sung Jun]

82
00:03:28,065 --> 00:03:29,588
[Naples, Italy]

83
00:03:29,588 --> 00:03:31,957
[Current time, 10:00 PM]
[30 minutes before closing]

84
00:03:31,957 --> 00:03:33,892
- It's ten?
- Day one's done.

85
00:03:33,892 --> 00:03:36,342
[The dining room empties out]

86
00:03:37,529 --> 00:03:40,399
[Only the last table remains]

87
00:03:40,399 --> 00:03:41,967
What order came in?

88
00:03:41,967 --> 00:03:44,836
Pasta's still going.

89
00:03:44,836 --> 00:03:47,305
[Just pasta orders left in the kitchen]
The pasta never ends.

90
00:03:47,305 --> 00:03:51,043
Tonight feels like dinner service
didn't even start.

91
00:03:51,043 --> 00:03:52,778
Seriously, it was so slow.

92
00:03:52,778 --> 00:03:53,979
It was pretty busy though.

93
00:03:53,979 --> 00:03:55,514
[Among the relaxed seniors]
You thought it was slow?

94
00:03:55,514 --> 00:03:58,350
Today was pretty slow.

95
00:03:58,350 --> 00:03:59,618
[Burned out alone on day one]

96
00:03:59,618 --> 00:04:00,852
Sung Jun looks really tired.

97
00:04:00,852 --> 00:04:02,132
Of course I'm tired on day one.

98
00:04:02,132 --> 00:04:03,822
- I wasn't over my jet lag yet back then.
- Day one was brutal.

99
00:04:03,822 --> 00:04:06,124
[Glance]

100
00:04:06,124 --> 00:04:09,061
[Glance again]
Why is she looking at him?

101
00:04:09,061 --> 00:04:11,596
[Luisa thinking as she watches him]

102
00:04:11,596 --> 00:04:13,951
Kwon.

103
00:04:14,733 --> 00:04:18,236
Want to try finishing the pasta?

104
00:04:18,236 --> 00:04:20,305
[Finish the pasta?]

105
00:04:20,305 --> 00:04:23,775
- Want to try finishing the pasta?
- Finish the pasta?

106
00:04:23,775 --> 00:04:25,243
What does finishing the pasta mean?

107
00:04:25,243 --> 00:04:30,115
I watched Kwon throughout dinner service.

108
00:04:30,115 --> 00:04:34,953
[Ears perked!]
He has quick reflexes, he's proactive,

109
00:04:34,953 --> 00:04:38,156
sharp, and he's clearly eager to learn.

110
00:04:38,156 --> 00:04:39,991
[Bashful...]
[The boss who watched him closely]

111
00:04:39,991 --> 00:04:44,129
That's exactly what separates
the amateurs from the pros.

112
00:04:44,129 --> 00:04:46,364
- It's whether you have wasted movements.
- Yeah.

113
00:04:46,364 --> 00:04:49,367
When I cook,
I have way too many extra movements,

114
00:04:49,367 --> 00:04:51,236
[Relatable]
and you can tell it looks clumsy.

115
00:04:51,236 --> 00:04:53,004
[A pro's experience]
When you're clean about it,

116
00:04:53,004 --> 00:04:55,073
the higher-ups think,
"Should I let him try this too?"

117
00:04:55,073 --> 00:04:56,141
- That kind of thinking.
- Right.

118
00:04:56,141 --> 00:04:59,077
[Sam Kwon / Pro Rookie]
You have to nail what they give you first.

119
00:04:59,077 --> 00:05:00,812
That's how the next mission comes.

120
00:05:00,812 --> 00:05:02,581
That's what I focused on.

121
00:05:02,581 --> 00:05:04,483
[Sung Jun's big picture for promotion]
Right, exactly.

122
00:05:04,483 --> 00:05:06,418
[He'll be finishing pasta with Luisa]

123
00:05:06,418 --> 00:05:12,303
Have you ever tried potato pasta?

124
00:05:12,303 --> 00:05:14,226
[Plays dumb]
Never had it.

125
00:05:14,226 --> 00:05:17,896
- He's saying he's never done this before.
- Okay, I'll show you.

126
00:05:17,896 --> 00:05:19,164
Potatoes, okay?

127
00:05:19,164 --> 00:05:21,266
[Though he played dumb,
what does potato pasta mean to Chef Kwon?]

128
00:05:21,266 --> 00:05:24,136
[The dish Napoli Matfia called
his life dish in his book]

129
00:05:24,136 --> 00:05:27,606
[Potato pasta]

130
00:05:27,606 --> 00:05:31,176
It's a really iconic Naples pasta.

131
00:05:31,176 --> 00:05:32,377
I make this all the time.

132
00:05:32,377 --> 00:05:34,946
[The actual potato pasta Kwon makes]

133
00:05:34,946 --> 00:05:38,884
[A chance to finish potato pasta for him]

134
00:05:38,884 --> 00:05:42,420
- Stir the pasta slowly first...
- Okay.

135
00:05:42,420 --> 00:05:45,519
to let the moisture cook off.

136
00:05:46,458 --> 00:05:48,326
Give it a try.

137
00:05:48,326 --> 00:05:50,695
[Interested]
An instant promotion?

138
00:05:50,695 --> 00:05:53,265
[Grabs it]
Give it a try.

139
00:05:53,265 --> 00:05:55,233
- When you stir,
- Yes.

140
00:05:55,233 --> 00:05:58,303
[He confidently takes the pan]
stir like...

141
00:05:58,303 --> 00:06:02,073
When making this pasta,
breaking down the potato matters.

142
00:06:02,073 --> 00:06:05,243
- Okay.
- You still want some potato texture left.

143
00:06:05,243 --> 00:06:08,747
It feels like home cooking.

144
00:06:08,747 --> 00:06:10,515
Wild that it's done in a pot, right?

145
00:06:10,515 --> 00:06:11,616
[Nice]
Right.

146
00:06:11,616 --> 00:06:13,451
- It's old school.
- It is.

147
00:06:13,451 --> 00:06:15,453
- You're doing great, Kwon.
- Aluminum pot.

148
00:06:15,453 --> 00:06:17,388
[This is nothing]

149
00:06:18,123 --> 00:06:20,826
[Swoop]

150
00:06:20,826 --> 00:06:22,861
[He grabs a tasting spoon on his own]

151
00:06:22,861 --> 00:06:26,164
[Checking the pasta seasoning]
Taste both the sauce and the pasta.

152
00:06:26,164 --> 00:06:28,500
Is it a little bland?

153
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:30,435
- What do you think?
- It's fine with me.

154
00:06:30,435 --> 00:06:31,903
Then it's fine with me too.

155
00:06:31,903 --> 00:06:34,072
[His palate knows!]
Okay.

156
00:06:34,072 --> 00:06:36,842
- Pasta's coming out soon, right?
- Yes, going out now.

157
00:06:36,842 --> 00:06:38,243
Okay, now toss it.

158
00:06:38,243 --> 00:06:40,679
[He starts tossing it like it's nothing]

159
00:06:40,679 --> 00:06:41,947
[Side glance]

160
00:06:41,947 --> 00:06:44,549
Good! Did the provola cheese melt well?

161
00:06:44,549 --> 00:06:47,285
[Of course, I'm doing the mantecare]
Good.

162
00:06:47,285 --> 00:06:48,653
Right now...

163
00:06:48,653 --> 00:06:51,092
he just busted out that move out of nowhere!

164
00:06:51,092 --> 00:06:52,257
I have to show off a little.

165
00:06:52,257 --> 00:06:55,727
She didn't even teach you that.
You weren't taught, so why are you doing it?

166
00:06:55,727 --> 00:06:57,329
- I was...
- Trying to show off again!

167
00:06:57,329 --> 00:06:58,396
No, no.

168
00:06:58,396 --> 00:07:00,131
- What?
- I have to do well to get the next task.

169
00:07:00,131 --> 00:07:02,200
[Kim Pung, Undercover Guardian]
But this is undercover!

170
00:07:02,200 --> 00:07:03,869
- But I...
- You said you'd never done it.

171
00:07:03,869 --> 00:07:05,937
- You said you'd never done it.
- I haven't done potato pasta.

172
00:07:05,937 --> 00:07:07,239
But I have done pasta.

173
00:07:07,239 --> 00:07:09,708
[The pro rookie's standing shrinks]
I make pasta and risotto all the time.

174
00:07:09,708 --> 00:07:11,610
[Kim Pung, Undercover Enforcement]
Stick to your role,

175
00:07:11,610 --> 00:07:12,878
- please.
- Well...

176
00:07:12,878 --> 00:07:14,012
I worked hard.

177
00:07:14,012 --> 00:07:15,046
Is working hard a crime?

178
00:07:15,046 --> 00:07:17,782
- You're still undercover.
- Right.

179
00:07:17,782 --> 00:07:18,783
Good.

180
00:07:18,783 --> 00:07:22,187
[He's the mantecare god
the whole world has witnessed]

181
00:07:22,187 --> 00:07:24,489
[Swish]

182
00:07:24,489 --> 00:07:26,825
It's tricky, but give it a try.

183
00:07:26,825 --> 00:07:27,959
[Watching closely]

184
00:07:27,959 --> 00:07:29,227
Okay.

185
00:07:29,227 --> 00:07:32,530
[Luisa gives him hints
and he adds his own touch]

186
00:07:32,530 --> 00:07:34,666
[Finishing the pasta diligently]

187
00:07:34,666 --> 00:07:36,601
Okay, bravo.

188
00:07:36,601 --> 00:07:39,170
[A clean finish too]

189
00:07:39,170 --> 00:07:41,373
[Sung Jun's killing it]
Looks good, plate it up.

190
00:07:41,373 --> 00:07:43,141
He adapts so fast.

191
00:07:43,141 --> 00:07:44,876
- I have to give him that.
- Okay.

192
00:07:44,876 --> 00:07:46,978
For day one, this was excellent!

193
00:07:46,978 --> 00:07:48,280
Could I have done any better?

194
00:07:48,280 --> 00:07:49,547
[Smug]

195
00:07:49,547 --> 00:07:51,649
[Self-praise]
I think I was perfect.

196
00:07:54,152 --> 00:07:56,688
- Are you okay?
- What's with me?

197
00:07:58,390 --> 00:08:00,158
I even cleaned the inside.

198
00:08:00,158 --> 00:08:01,860
He's cleaning thoroughly.

199
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:03,928
I have to do it thoroughly.

200
00:08:05,664 --> 00:08:08,366
[Wiping every corner]

201
00:08:08,366 --> 00:08:10,368
[Like nothing happened, spotless]

202
00:08:10,368 --> 00:08:12,904
- We're done.
- Okay.

203
00:08:12,904 --> 00:08:14,940
Get some rest and see you tomorrow.

204
00:08:14,940 --> 00:08:16,732
[The brightest smile of the day]
- Got it. - Thank you.

205
00:08:16,732 --> 00:08:18,576
[Happy]
Thank you.

206
00:08:18,576 --> 00:08:20,345
It's midnight.

207
00:08:20,345 --> 00:08:22,981
[Day 1 service over, 12:00 AM]
Restaurants in Italy close around that time.

208
00:08:22,981 --> 00:08:24,783
[Past midnight]

209
00:08:24,783 --> 00:08:26,251
[Arriving at the lodging]

210
00:08:26,251 --> 00:08:28,185
[Water rushing]

211
00:08:29,821 --> 00:08:31,690
[Humming]

212
00:08:31,690 --> 00:08:35,226
[Late but washing off the long day]

213
00:08:35,226 --> 00:08:36,428
What is that? What song is that?

214
00:08:36,428 --> 00:08:38,997
[Discovering a new side of himself]
He's singing?

215
00:08:38,997 --> 00:08:40,898
What was I singing?

216
00:08:42,467 --> 00:08:46,405
[Going straight to sleep for tomorrow]

217
00:08:47,339 --> 00:08:49,074
[Alarm set too]

218
00:08:49,074 --> 00:08:50,663
He's out cold already.

219
00:08:50,663 --> 00:08:52,911
[Day 1 officially ends, 1:00 AM]
I was so exhausted, seriously.

220
00:08:52,911 --> 00:08:54,679
You must be tired.

221
00:08:58,750 --> 00:09:00,518
[Morning breaks]

222
00:09:00,518 --> 00:09:02,187
Day two.

223
00:09:02,187 --> 00:09:03,946
The vibe is completely different.

224
00:09:03,946 --> 00:09:04,989
[Kwon's day 2 as an undercover rookie begins]

225
00:09:04,989 --> 00:09:07,359
- Totally different from Parma, right?
- Completely.

226
00:09:07,359 --> 00:09:09,787
[Snoring]

227
00:09:10,996 --> 00:09:14,666
[The alarm wakes him up]

228
00:09:14,666 --> 00:09:16,234
[Protecting our cast]
[Blink]

229
00:09:16,234 --> 00:09:17,369
[Sudden awake]
What's this?

230
00:09:17,369 --> 00:09:19,104
What?

231
00:09:19,104 --> 00:09:21,506
[Traces of deep sleep]
It was too hot so I slept without clothes.

232
00:09:21,506 --> 00:09:22,907
I usually sleep without clothes on.

233
00:09:22,907 --> 00:09:25,577
[What time is it?]

234
00:09:25,577 --> 00:09:27,812
[8:00 AM]

235
00:09:27,812 --> 00:09:31,883
[Time to get up]
[One hour before work]

236
00:09:31,883 --> 00:09:33,985
[Protecting our cast]

237
00:09:33,985 --> 00:09:35,886
Too much exposure.

238
00:09:36,621 --> 00:09:39,157
[Springs up]

239
00:09:39,157 --> 00:09:41,026
[Spreading the blanket]

240
00:09:41,026 --> 00:09:43,828
[Blanket made in record time]

241
00:09:43,828 --> 00:09:46,264
[No hesitation]

242
00:09:46,264 --> 00:09:48,133
[Same outer layer as yesterday]

243
00:09:48,133 --> 00:09:50,368
[Same hat]
I wore the same clothes the whole time.

244
00:09:50,368 --> 00:09:52,463
[Three-second Sam Kwon disguise complete]
Three seconds flat.

245
00:09:53,304 --> 00:09:54,506
Did you wash your face?

246
00:09:54,506 --> 00:09:56,875
Just brushed my teeth, no face wash.

247
00:09:56,875 --> 00:09:58,576
You only wash every other day?

248
00:09:58,576 --> 00:10:00,278
I washed last night.

249
00:10:00,278 --> 00:10:02,914
I have to hurry.

250
00:10:02,914 --> 00:10:04,983
[Rushing]

251
00:10:04,983 --> 00:10:08,319
[Why he's in such a rush today...]

252
00:10:08,319 --> 00:10:09,387
It's a holiday.

253
00:10:09,387 --> 00:10:11,189
There'll probably be a lot of guests.

254
00:10:11,189 --> 00:10:12,724
It's a holiday today?

255
00:10:12,724 --> 00:10:14,125
[Today is a busy holiday?]

256
00:10:14,125 --> 00:10:16,194
[The day before]

257
00:10:16,194 --> 00:10:19,654
[Yesterday morning during prep time]

258
00:10:19,654 --> 00:10:20,665
[Side glance]

259
00:10:20,665 --> 00:10:24,269
- Paolo, are you making zeppole right now?
- Yes, that's right.

260
00:10:24,269 --> 00:10:28,273
- The dessert Paolo's making is zeppole.
- Dessert? Okay.

261
00:10:28,273 --> 00:10:30,115
- Dessert? Okay.
- Zeppole?

262
00:10:30,115 --> 00:10:31,443
[Wait, why zeppole all of a sudden?]

263
00:10:31,443 --> 00:10:35,847
It's a dessert eaten only on Father's Day,
which is tomorrow.

264
00:10:35,847 --> 00:10:37,348
- Okay.
- Which is tomorrow.

265
00:10:37,348 --> 00:10:39,751
- Tomorrow?
- Tomorrow's Father's Day.

266
00:10:39,751 --> 00:10:43,521
It's also one of the biggest
celebrations in Italy.

267
00:10:43,521 --> 00:10:45,890
- On Father's Day.
- On Father's Day.

268
00:10:45,890 --> 00:10:47,792
So Father's Day is a separate thing here.

269
00:10:47,792 --> 00:10:50,928
In Europe and the West,
Father's Day and Mother's Day are separate.

270
00:10:50,928 --> 00:10:51,930
- Really?
- The US is like that too.

271
00:10:51,930 --> 00:10:53,965
In Asia, we lump it into Parents' Day.

272
00:10:53,965 --> 00:10:55,400
The West splits them up.

273
00:10:55,400 --> 00:10:57,868
- I like that.
- Right?

274
00:10:58,470 --> 00:11:02,781
[Naples invented zeppole
and all of Italy tasted it]

275
00:11:03,741 --> 00:11:05,009
That stuff's delicious.

276
00:11:05,009 --> 00:11:08,279
So there's a traditional dessert
they share together.

277
00:11:08,279 --> 00:11:09,814
[Which means]

278
00:11:09,814 --> 00:11:13,585
[Family dining day]

279
00:11:13,585 --> 00:11:16,187
[Every table booked]
That day had a ton of guests.

280
00:11:16,187 --> 00:11:17,355
[The kitchen's on high alert too]

281
00:11:17,355 --> 00:11:19,924
It's a real crisis.

282
00:11:19,924 --> 00:11:22,481
[Paolo on mains is going to be the busiest]

283
00:11:23,528 --> 00:11:24,863
[8:35 AM, first one in today]

284
00:11:24,863 --> 00:11:27,599
I'm here early today, what's the deal?

285
00:11:27,599 --> 00:11:30,869
[Catch up with Kwon after he changes]

286
00:11:30,869 --> 00:11:33,371
[Same time]

287
00:11:33,371 --> 00:11:36,274
[Whoosh]

288
00:11:36,274 --> 00:11:38,543
- Who's that?
- Paolo.

289
00:11:38,543 --> 00:11:40,744
He's so cute.

290
00:11:41,880 --> 00:11:45,963
[Senior Pa scooting in as always]

291
00:11:45,963 --> 00:11:47,051
Senior Pa.

292
00:11:47,051 --> 00:11:49,655
[Heading straight to the counter]

293
00:11:50,755 --> 00:11:53,024
[Flutter]

294
00:11:53,024 --> 00:11:55,727
Two, six, ten...

295
00:11:55,727 --> 00:11:59,297
- Reservation book.
- Checking reservations.

296
00:11:59,297 --> 00:12:01,633
[Reservations packed in scribbled writing]
How do I figure out what it says?

297
00:12:01,633 --> 00:12:03,434
I can't make out a single word.

298
00:12:03,434 --> 00:12:05,537
[That's a lot of guests... Bummed]

299
00:12:05,537 --> 00:12:07,739
[Looks like a packed day ahead...]
- Bummed. - Bummed.

300
00:12:07,739 --> 00:12:09,440
When it's busy, you get annoyed!

301
00:12:09,440 --> 00:12:11,342
- Only the boss is happy.
- Yeah.

302
00:12:11,342 --> 00:12:12,426
'Morning.

303
00:12:12,426 --> 00:12:13,978
[Kitchen staff start trickling in one by one]

304
00:12:13,978 --> 00:12:17,253
[Everyone clocked in 20 minutes early]

305
00:12:18,016 --> 00:12:20,251
Paolo, how's the pork shank coming along?

306
00:12:20,251 --> 00:12:22,187
I need to start now.

307
00:12:22,854 --> 00:12:24,022
[Antonio's tasks, Paolo's tasks]

308
00:12:24,022 --> 00:12:25,156
Prep list.

309
00:12:25,156 --> 00:12:27,992
[Paolo has a lot piling up]
Paolo has a ton on his plate.

310
00:12:27,992 --> 00:12:29,961
He handles most of the desserts too.

311
00:12:29,961 --> 00:12:31,462
[Thinking]

312
00:12:31,462 --> 00:12:33,765
Well...

313
00:12:33,765 --> 00:12:35,400
You'll be with him today, right?

314
00:12:35,400 --> 00:12:36,935
I should work over there.

315
00:12:36,935 --> 00:12:39,770
I'll team up with Kwon.

316
00:12:40,371 --> 00:12:43,908
[What is Kwon up to?]

317
00:12:43,908 --> 00:12:45,510
[New bandana pulled down tight]

318
00:12:45,510 --> 00:12:48,179
- Found your bandana?
- Yes.

319
00:12:48,179 --> 00:12:49,814
The bandana keeps getting smaller.

320
00:12:49,814 --> 00:12:51,482
[Struggling]

321
00:12:51,482 --> 00:12:53,351
- Why's it so small?
- It got even smaller.

322
00:12:53,351 --> 00:12:55,420
- He keeps eating.
- The swelling went down a bit.

323
00:12:55,420 --> 00:12:58,423
At this rate it'll stick
straight up like a topknot.

324
00:12:58,423 --> 00:13:01,031
- No matter how you pull it down it rides up.
- That's why it keeps riding up.

325
00:13:01,031 --> 00:13:02,493
[Chef with a topknot]

326
00:13:02,493 --> 00:13:05,396
[Pulled the shrunken bandana on for now]

327
00:13:05,396 --> 00:13:09,133
I have to do the same things as yesterday

328
00:13:09,133 --> 00:13:12,537
but when it gets busy,
the kitchen always gets tangled up.

329
00:13:12,537 --> 00:13:16,441
Today I'm staying sharp every second.

330
00:13:16,441 --> 00:13:18,710
[Locked in!]

331
00:13:18,710 --> 00:13:21,512
[Ready to do this right on a busy day!]

332
00:13:21,512 --> 00:13:25,716
[So who's prepping with Kwon today?]
Let's start with the potato cake.

333
00:13:26,751 --> 00:13:30,555
[Trusted right hand of the sister owners]
- Paolo's handling the prep today. - Paolo.

334
00:13:30,555 --> 00:13:31,589
All right, starting now...

335
00:13:31,589 --> 00:13:34,459
Now I need that you...

336
00:13:34,459 --> 00:13:37,228
help me out like you did yesterday morning.

337
00:13:37,228 --> 00:13:39,304
[Sounds good]

338
00:13:39,304 --> 00:13:44,059
We're making the potato cake
for the antipasto platter.

339
00:13:44,059 --> 00:13:45,069
Okay.

340
00:13:45,069 --> 00:13:48,406
[On a busy day the first rookie task...]

341
00:13:48,406 --> 00:13:50,842
[A signature dish the antipasto platter]

342
00:13:50,842 --> 00:13:52,577
That one. Potato cake.

343
00:13:52,577 --> 00:13:54,078
[Prepping the potato cake]

344
00:13:54,078 --> 00:13:55,747
- Let's do it like this.
- Okay.

345
00:13:55,747 --> 00:13:57,082
[Starting prep with Senior Pa]

346
00:13:57,082 --> 00:14:01,252
First wet your hands really well.

347
00:14:01,252 --> 00:14:03,888
[Eyes locked in]

348
00:14:03,888 --> 00:14:07,225
[Senior An's eyes locked too?]

349
00:14:07,225 --> 00:14:08,226
Senior An, why?

350
00:14:08,226 --> 00:14:10,295
[Something missing from Senior An's side today]

351
00:14:10,295 --> 00:14:14,265
Try flattening one out.

352
00:14:14,265 --> 00:14:16,100
[Checking the method]

353
00:14:16,100 --> 00:14:18,469
[Slide]

354
00:14:18,469 --> 00:14:19,871
I think Senior An misses me.

355
00:14:19,871 --> 00:14:22,106
[Two seniors and one junior the vibe is...]

356
00:14:22,106 --> 00:14:24,876
[Undercover Chef spin-off Senior Exchange]

357
00:14:24,876 --> 00:14:26,811
[Ex, anxious senior Antonio]

358
00:14:26,811 --> 00:14:29,013
What's this now?

359
00:14:29,013 --> 00:14:31,482
Why do they keep making weird stuff?

360
00:14:31,482 --> 00:14:32,750
He hates this kind of thing.

361
00:14:32,750 --> 00:14:34,552
- I really hate it.
- He really can't stand it.

362
00:14:34,552 --> 00:14:37,655
[Secretly flustered]
[Look at him]

363
00:14:37,655 --> 00:14:40,291
[NEW chill senior Paolo]

364
00:14:40,291 --> 00:14:42,760
[Wavering junior Sam Kwon]
Why is this?

365
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:43,949
[Glance]

366
00:14:45,130 --> 00:14:48,199
- The layer's a bit thick, so press it thinner.
- Okay.

367
00:14:48,199 --> 00:14:50,401
Thinner.

368
00:14:50,401 --> 00:14:52,670
Think of it like playing with clay,
press it down.

369
00:14:52,670 --> 00:14:56,107
[Nod]
He is pretty different from Senior An.

370
00:14:56,107 --> 00:14:58,276
["Your ex senior is watching you!"]

371
00:14:58,276 --> 00:14:59,911
Why does he keep staring?

372
00:14:59,911 --> 00:15:01,045
I didn't realize that.

373
00:15:01,045 --> 00:15:03,147
[Senior An lost in thought watching Kwon]

374
00:15:03,147 --> 00:15:06,417
["Your ex senior has stepped away"]

375
00:15:06,417 --> 00:15:09,420
[Senior An is going somewhere]

376
00:15:09,420 --> 00:15:11,122
[Coming straight to Kwon]

377
00:15:11,122 --> 00:15:12,223
Hey.

378
00:15:12,223 --> 00:15:14,158
[Take these tongs]

379
00:15:14,158 --> 00:15:16,060
Thank you.

380
00:15:17,995 --> 00:15:20,838
[Gifting to block the rebound]
He lent me his since I didn't have any.

381
00:15:21,632 --> 00:15:25,036
[He'll like this, right?]

382
00:15:25,036 --> 00:15:27,438
[Truth is yesterday Senior An...]

383
00:15:27,438 --> 00:15:30,341
- Don't forget to drizzle the sauce.
- Okay.

384
00:15:30,341 --> 00:15:32,043
Is this right?

385
00:15:32,043 --> 00:15:34,545
You need to spread the plating wide.

386
00:15:34,545 --> 00:15:38,449
Meatballs and tomato sauce.
Thinking about how you plate...

387
00:15:38,449 --> 00:15:40,852
[Drilled him hard to keep him in line]
- You don't need it. - Okay.

388
00:15:40,852 --> 00:15:44,088
[Why does it feel sentimental today?]

389
00:15:44,088 --> 00:15:46,457
[Meanwhile...]

390
00:15:46,457 --> 00:15:49,627
How much milk should we add?

391
00:15:49,627 --> 00:15:50,561
[Calmly waiting for the answer?]

392
00:15:50,561 --> 00:15:51,863
So...

393
00:15:51,863 --> 00:15:54,031
- 400 grams?
- Good, very nicely done.

394
00:15:54,031 --> 00:15:56,467
Senior Paolo is kind of...

395
00:15:56,467 --> 00:15:58,503
- Kind of different.
- How do I put it? Next to you...

396
00:15:58,503 --> 00:16:00,438
He feels like a senior
who teaches you in a really calm way.

397
00:16:00,438 --> 00:16:03,441
Right. And he's really fun too.

398
00:16:03,441 --> 00:16:05,977
The start is always the hardest.

399
00:16:05,977 --> 00:16:09,546
- He's warm. Turns out he's a warm guy.
- He really is.

400
00:16:10,314 --> 00:16:12,449
He's singing?

401
00:16:13,751 --> 00:16:15,853
[Breaking into song out of nowhere]

402
00:16:15,853 --> 00:16:16,879
Out of nowhere?

403
00:16:16,879 --> 00:16:20,024
You've got a singer's blood today, Paolo.

404
00:16:20,024 --> 00:16:24,262
This morning my daughter
read me a poem and gave me a gift.

405
00:16:24,262 --> 00:16:28,065
- Right, today is Father's Day.
- She read her little poem to me.

406
00:16:28,065 --> 00:16:29,567
Do you like music?

407
00:16:29,567 --> 00:16:32,136
Of course. I love the song that's playing.

408
00:16:32,136 --> 00:16:33,938
[Ancora by Eduardo De Crescenzo,
an 80s Italian ballad full of soul]

409
00:16:33,938 --> 00:16:36,107
[Italy needs work songs too!]
In Italy you've got to sing while you work.

410
00:16:36,107 --> 00:16:38,843
I like working at a relaxed pace.

411
00:16:38,843 --> 00:16:41,460
That way the food turns out beautiful.

412
00:16:41,460 --> 00:16:43,246
[Glance]
Right.

413
00:16:45,216 --> 00:16:48,019
[Senior Pa's warmth melting the tension...]
- Because... - Fried it's like that.

414
00:16:48,019 --> 00:16:49,554
[Even a relaxed smile now]
You like it fried?

415
00:16:49,554 --> 00:16:51,756
- Paolo.
- To shorten it.

416
00:16:51,756 --> 00:16:53,424
[Unfamiliar]
He's even smiling now?

417
00:16:53,424 --> 00:16:54,926
- His face looks different.
- Starting day two,

418
00:16:54,926 --> 00:16:56,928
- I'm getting used to it.
- Right.

419
00:16:56,928 --> 00:17:00,465
[A smile blooming between them]
- It's more Italian. - Okay.

420
00:17:00,465 --> 00:17:02,392
[Hehe]
We don't eat cats.

421
00:17:02,392 --> 00:17:04,135
[One person's pout...]
Senior An looks lonely today.

422
00:17:04,135 --> 00:17:05,736
[A bit hurt]

423
00:17:05,736 --> 00:17:07,405
[Bop bop]

424
00:17:07,405 --> 00:17:10,308
[Paolo's work-song time continues]

425
00:17:10,308 --> 00:17:11,776
Paolo's basically

426
00:17:11,776 --> 00:17:16,047
- got a lot of energy and sets a fun vibe.
- The mood maker.

427
00:17:16,047 --> 00:17:18,149
[Bobbing head]
[Kwon starting to catch the rhythm too]

428
00:17:18,149 --> 00:17:19,483
[Glance]

429
00:17:19,483 --> 00:17:22,587
[Swaying along]

430
00:17:22,587 --> 00:17:25,108
[Quietly enjoying it]

431
00:17:25,108 --> 00:17:29,525
[And starting with Paolo...]

432
00:17:29,525 --> 00:17:32,430
[Everyone joins in singing]
Wait, the whole team's singing?

433
00:17:34,331 --> 00:17:37,085
[Joining the singalong]
This is Naples.

434
00:17:37,702 --> 00:17:40,271
[Smiling brightly]
Basically...

435
00:17:40,271 --> 00:17:44,408
I wanted Kwon to feel more at ease!

436
00:17:44,408 --> 00:17:46,377
- So it was a kind gesture.
- Kwon seemed to like music

437
00:17:46,377 --> 00:17:49,013
and he looked like he loosened up

438
00:17:49,013 --> 00:17:52,817
so it felt like the right call.

439
00:17:52,817 --> 00:17:54,519
[Touched]
So he thought you love music

440
00:17:54,519 --> 00:17:55,820
and sang on purpose.

441
00:17:55,820 --> 00:17:57,455
Sung Jun!

442
00:17:57,455 --> 00:17:59,190
That's a real senior.

443
00:17:59,190 --> 00:18:01,559
He's looking out for you. Got it?

444
00:18:01,559 --> 00:18:02,860
I get it, but...

445
00:18:02,860 --> 00:18:04,795
You just thought he liked music
and left it at that, right?

446
00:18:04,795 --> 00:18:07,531
But Senior An keeps coming to mind.

447
00:18:07,531 --> 00:18:08,566
Really?

448
00:18:08,566 --> 00:18:10,268
[So you're playing hot and cold?]
Right.

449
00:18:10,268 --> 00:18:12,336
- You prefer that?
- I'm not sure.

450
00:18:12,336 --> 00:18:14,438
- Oh, really?
- I need to think it over.

451
00:18:14,438 --> 00:18:17,675
- That was him caring just now.
- Right.

452
00:18:17,675 --> 00:18:18,676
Senior Pa.

453
00:18:18,676 --> 00:18:20,444
[Wavering]

454
00:18:20,444 --> 00:18:23,281
[Enjoying music thanks to Senior Pa]

455
00:18:23,281 --> 00:18:25,583
[Potato cake prep done!]

456
00:18:25,583 --> 00:18:29,180
[Kwon pausing to think]

457
00:18:30,187 --> 00:18:32,723
- A question.
- Fire away.

458
00:18:32,723 --> 00:18:35,993
[Sudden question]
Who's the most famous chef in Naples?

459
00:18:35,993 --> 00:18:37,795
[Asking in a relaxed mood]
The most famous.

460
00:18:37,795 --> 00:18:39,363
- Why is he asking that?
- Who is it?

461
00:18:39,363 --> 00:18:41,832
[Curious]

462
00:18:41,832 --> 00:18:44,902
Who's the most famous chef?

463
00:18:44,902 --> 00:18:49,607
There's one, his name is Mellino...

464
00:18:49,607 --> 00:18:52,143
- Oh, the three-star Michelin one?
- Right.

465
00:18:52,143 --> 00:18:54,211
Quattro Passi.

466
00:18:54,211 --> 00:18:57,281
- Is he starting to be suspicious of you?
- I think so.

467
00:18:57,281 --> 00:19:00,118
[Second question]
Do you know the Michelin spot on Ischia?

468
00:19:00,985 --> 00:19:03,087
- Michelin.
- Yes.

469
00:19:03,087 --> 00:19:04,522
[Gulp]
Daní Maison, that's the name.

470
00:19:04,522 --> 00:19:06,023
Yes.

471
00:19:06,023 --> 00:19:08,526
[Now that they're friendly
testing if Paolo knows his mentor...]

472
00:19:08,526 --> 00:19:13,164
- You mean Daní, run by chef Nino di Costanzo?
- Yes.

473
00:19:13,164 --> 00:19:15,766
- Where I worked.
- Oh, where you worked?

474
00:19:15,766 --> 00:19:18,169
- Is that place famous?
- Yes.

475
00:19:18,169 --> 00:19:20,371
Of course, Campania's got to have
some famous chefs.

476
00:19:20,371 --> 00:19:21,484
He's a famous one?

477
00:19:21,484 --> 00:19:23,140
[Smirk]
He's the most famous in Naples.

478
00:19:23,140 --> 00:19:24,775
[Kwon's mentor is the No.1 chef in Naples]
Really?

479
00:19:24,775 --> 00:19:26,944
Are there Michelin restaurants in Korea?

480
00:19:26,944 --> 00:19:28,346
Of course we have them.

481
00:19:28,346 --> 00:19:30,848
- In Seoul?
- Yes, Seoul!

482
00:19:30,848 --> 00:19:32,083
Seoul.

483
00:19:32,083 --> 00:19:34,951
- Right, in Korean we pronounce it "Seoul."
- Right.

484
00:19:36,020 --> 00:19:37,288
I asked on purpose.

485
00:19:37,288 --> 00:19:40,257
And he actually knew
the restaurant I worked at.

486
00:19:40,257 --> 00:19:42,059
[Smug]

487
00:19:42,059 --> 00:19:44,293
Why are you the one acting smug? Hold on.

488
00:19:44,293 --> 00:19:46,059
[Dying of laughter]
It's not that you're famous,

489
00:19:46,059 --> 00:19:48,866
- it's that the head chef there is good.
- No, that's not it.

490
00:19:48,866 --> 00:19:50,968
- That's not what I meant.
- Because he worked there.

491
00:19:50,968 --> 00:19:52,860
- I'm painting the big picture.
- You're painting it?

492
00:19:52,860 --> 00:19:55,106
- Really?
- Later, when I reveal myself,

493
00:19:55,106 --> 00:19:56,641
- "I worked here."
- "I used to work here."

494
00:19:56,641 --> 00:19:58,209
"I'm someone who actually worked in Naples."

495
00:19:58,209 --> 00:20:00,578
I get that,
but you suddenly got all cocky there.

496
00:20:00,578 --> 00:20:03,748
- I wasn't being cocky. I'm always like this.
- It just looked really bad.

497
00:20:03,748 --> 00:20:05,883
- So that's just how you are.
- That's how I am.

498
00:20:05,883 --> 00:20:08,753
[Can't accept this] [Still hilarious]
I just can't wrap my head around this.

499
00:20:08,753 --> 00:20:11,188
[Matfia, Chef, painter, and writer]
The Mat-writer is laying it all out.

500
00:20:11,188 --> 00:20:12,723
- He's planting seeds.
- I'm planting seeds.

501
00:20:12,723 --> 00:20:14,225
- Is that what it is? Got it.
- Yes.

502
00:20:14,225 --> 00:20:15,672
Later when this airs,

503
00:20:15,672 --> 00:20:17,761
- you're going for the surprise.
- Yes, it'll be fun.

504
00:20:18,996 --> 00:20:22,667
Wouldn't it be fun to say later
that I worked there?

505
00:20:22,667 --> 00:20:23,768
[Smirk]

506
00:20:23,768 --> 00:20:24,802
[PM 12:35]

507
00:20:24,802 --> 00:20:26,604
[25 minutes till lunch service]
It's lunchtime.

508
00:20:26,604 --> 00:20:30,702
All right, let's start
prepping for lunch service.

509
00:20:31,375 --> 00:20:33,022
- Okay.
- Okay.

510
00:20:33,022 --> 00:20:35,939
[Back beside Senior An for lunch service]
First, we make antipasti.

511
00:20:43,339 --> 00:20:45,241
- The deserts are the last.
- Okay.

512
00:20:45,241 --> 00:20:48,411
- Start prepping the beef rolls.
- Okay.

513
00:20:48,411 --> 00:20:49,846
[Right to work]

514
00:20:49,846 --> 00:20:51,848
Those two are so different.

515
00:20:51,848 --> 00:20:53,583
How many lunch reservations do we have today?

516
00:20:53,583 --> 00:20:55,415
[How many?]

517
00:20:56,652 --> 00:20:58,921
How many lunch reservations today?

518
00:20:58,921 --> 00:21:03,513
[Flipping through the book]
Including the bank guests, it's 25.

519
00:21:04,360 --> 00:21:06,329
[25 reservations means...]

520
00:21:06,329 --> 00:21:08,264
25 people.

521
00:21:08,264 --> 00:21:09,766
We have walk-ins too.

522
00:21:09,766 --> 00:21:12,201
- Walk-ins too.
- Yes.

523
00:21:12,201 --> 00:21:16,605
[99% chance of a full house]

524
00:21:16,605 --> 00:21:20,712
25 is basically one table for Chef Jung Ji Sun.

525
00:21:20,712 --> 00:21:21,736
Right?

526
00:21:21,736 --> 00:21:26,315
But the youngest should know the reservations
and the headcount before service.

527
00:21:26,315 --> 00:21:28,818
Really? Sung Jun would know then.

528
00:21:28,818 --> 00:21:30,553
I actually didn't know.

529
00:21:30,553 --> 00:21:32,822
[Sassy]
You're surprisingly proud of that.

530
00:21:32,822 --> 00:21:34,490
- Of course you should know.
- Everyone should know.

531
00:21:34,490 --> 00:21:36,692
Everyone needs to know.

532
00:21:36,692 --> 00:21:39,028
We have 25 reservations,

533
00:21:39,028 --> 00:21:41,877
so let's prep for 30 to 35 just in case.

534
00:21:42,765 --> 00:21:43,800
Let's do 30.

535
00:21:43,800 --> 00:21:47,370
[Sam Kwon's task: Pre-roll 30 beef rolls]
- Okay. - I already got you the salad.

536
00:21:47,370 --> 00:21:50,139
[More prep as more guests are coming]
You have to prep for around 35 servings.

537
00:21:50,139 --> 00:21:51,841
Make some extra.

538
00:21:51,841 --> 00:21:53,476
30 is nothing.

539
00:21:53,476 --> 00:21:55,478
[Both appetizer guys focused more than usual]

540
00:21:55,478 --> 00:22:00,027
[Senior An drops the nagging
to brace for the rush]

541
00:22:02,552 --> 00:22:06,422
About those bank reservations coming in.

542
00:22:06,422 --> 00:22:07,623
[Why the bank guests?]
Bank guests?

543
00:22:07,623 --> 00:22:10,839
Eight were supposed to come,
but two more are joining.

544
00:22:10,839 --> 00:22:12,895
I told them okay.

545
00:22:12,895 --> 00:22:13,896
So it's ten now.

546
00:22:13,896 --> 00:22:15,631
They already pre-ordered. Antipasto platter,

547
00:22:15,631 --> 00:22:18,401
then five potato pastas,
one pork fat pasta, and two Genovese.

548
00:22:18,401 --> 00:22:21,304
[This out of nowhere?]

549
00:22:21,304 --> 00:22:23,706
[Which means]

550
00:22:23,706 --> 00:22:26,642
We have a 10-person reservation,

551
00:22:26,642 --> 00:22:29,478
and they're in a rush so they pre-ordered.

552
00:22:29,478 --> 00:22:32,048
- Okay.
- They want to eat antipasti.

553
00:22:32,048 --> 00:22:35,551
[Party of ten, plus, quick turnaround needed]
I already made them.

554
00:22:35,551 --> 00:22:39,055
[Stacking up]

555
00:22:39,055 --> 00:22:43,559
[Ten portions of antipasto packed and ready]

556
00:22:43,559 --> 00:22:47,203
[Ten minutes till lunch service]

557
00:22:47,977 --> 00:22:50,499
[Roll as many beef rolls as possible]
This is so different from yesterday.

558
00:22:50,499 --> 00:22:52,268
I think we were pretty slammed that day.

559
00:22:52,268 --> 00:22:54,103
[Jaw clenched, locked in]

560
00:22:54,103 --> 00:22:55,404
[Watching closely]

561
00:22:55,404 --> 00:22:56,806
He's watching from the front again.

562
00:22:56,806 --> 00:22:59,175
[Came to cheer him on, charmed by the rookie]

563
00:22:59,175 --> 00:23:03,146
We're battle-ready, got our combat gear on.

564
00:23:03,946 --> 00:23:06,549
[Pleased]

565
00:23:06,549 --> 00:23:08,718
[I feel solid with you guys]

566
00:23:08,718 --> 00:23:11,153
- That tight battle helmet.
- Why do they keep highlighting my hat?

567
00:23:11,153 --> 00:23:13,489
[Sam Kwon in his tight battle helmet
doubles down]

568
00:23:13,489 --> 00:23:16,058
[Quick and precise hands]
He's frowning again.

569
00:23:16,058 --> 00:23:17,100
When I'm focused.

570
00:23:17,100 --> 00:23:18,761
[Beef rolls in two neat columns]

571
00:23:18,761 --> 00:23:21,464
[Next]

572
00:23:21,464 --> 00:23:24,033
[Prepping bean soup on his own]

573
00:23:24,033 --> 00:23:27,356
[Even the dessert piping bag]

574
00:23:27,356 --> 00:23:28,362
[Grating cheese ahead of time]

575
00:23:28,362 --> 00:23:30,659
I'm like I've worked here forever.

576
00:23:30,659 --> 00:23:33,142
- Is this enough?
- Good!

577
00:23:33,142 --> 00:23:34,810
Okay.

578
00:23:34,810 --> 00:23:39,294
The previous rookie was really bad at cooking.

579
00:23:40,016 --> 00:23:42,485
- But Kwon's nailing it right off the bat!
- Right.

580
00:23:42,485 --> 00:23:44,553
I'll show him.

581
00:23:44,553 --> 00:23:48,027
So today I just handed everything over to Kwon.

582
00:23:48,027 --> 00:23:50,226
[Honey dripping]
He gave him the reins here too?

583
00:23:50,226 --> 00:23:54,063
[Kwon's become the restaurant's sweetheart]
- So Senior Antonio likes him too. - Right.

584
00:23:54,063 --> 00:23:56,465
What matters is how well
you handle the busy times.

585
00:23:56,465 --> 00:23:59,635
You earn your voice by doing the work.

586
00:23:59,635 --> 00:24:02,104
- Right.
- That's true.

587
00:24:02,104 --> 00:24:04,856
You have to do everything flawlessly
to get the next mission.

588
00:24:04,856 --> 00:24:05,861
Right.

589
00:24:05,861 --> 00:24:09,712
[The pasta station he sampled yesterday]

590
00:24:09,712 --> 00:24:12,882
[Hoping to earn his way back at lunch!]
You just empty your head

591
00:24:12,882 --> 00:24:14,916
and let your hands move.

592
00:24:16,652 --> 00:24:20,391
[Father's Day]

593
00:24:21,424 --> 00:24:24,961
[Streets full of kids today]

594
00:24:24,961 --> 00:24:26,449
[Peeking]

595
00:24:29,265 --> 00:24:31,100
[First lunch guests arrive]
Customers are coming in.

596
00:24:31,100 --> 00:24:33,936
Hi, hello.

597
00:24:33,936 --> 00:24:35,871
[A father and son arriving on Father's Day]

598
00:24:35,871 --> 00:24:38,741
It's Father's Day today, right?

599
00:24:38,741 --> 00:24:40,810
[So sweet]
He talks to every single one of them.

600
00:24:40,810 --> 00:24:42,945
I love this neighborhood vibe so much.

601
00:24:42,945 --> 00:24:44,580
[Tables filling up with guests]
Right?

602
00:24:44,580 --> 00:24:46,515
What are they eating?

603
00:24:46,515 --> 00:24:49,458
[First order ticket is in]

604
00:24:51,120 --> 00:24:54,190
- Table 8 order.
- Everyone hold on.

605
00:24:54,190 --> 00:24:56,459
Table 8 has to head back to work soon,
so they're in a real rush.

606
00:24:56,459 --> 00:25:02,064
- Them as well.
- Table 8, sausage and salad.

607
00:25:02,064 --> 00:25:04,333
[A table of office workers in a hurry]
- So this becomes a special case. - Right.

608
00:25:04,333 --> 00:25:07,536
- Have to move fast.
- Instead of following the regular order,

609
00:25:07,536 --> 00:25:10,239
- they need theirs first.
- You just go fast no matter what.

610
00:25:10,239 --> 00:25:12,375
[Quickly starting on bean soup
for the rushed guests]

611
00:25:12,375 --> 00:25:14,979
[More order tickets coming in]

612
00:25:14,979 --> 00:25:17,581
- Three antipasto platters in the oven.
- Yes.

613
00:25:18,481 --> 00:25:19,348
That's not it!

614
00:25:19,348 --> 00:25:22,551
[Sorry?]

615
00:25:22,551 --> 00:25:24,754
That's not it!

616
00:25:24,754 --> 00:25:27,089
Table 5, direct, 3 potato pasta.

617
00:25:27,089 --> 00:25:28,591
[Confused]

618
00:25:28,591 --> 00:25:32,293
[Party of three, potato pasta]
[No antipasto platter order]

619
00:25:32,293 --> 00:25:34,633
- Three antipasto platters in the oven.
- Yes.

620
00:25:34,633 --> 00:25:36,499
That's not it!

621
00:25:36,499 --> 00:25:38,134
You have to read the order first.

622
00:25:38,134 --> 00:25:40,236
[Dizzy from the surprise at service start]
So it was a joke. I just realized.

623
00:25:40,236 --> 00:25:43,172
You need to know how to read an order.

624
00:25:43,172 --> 00:25:45,107
Yes.

625
00:25:45,107 --> 00:25:46,442
[Reading the ticket like Senior An said]

626
00:25:46,442 --> 00:25:49,412
[Recentering himself]

627
00:25:49,412 --> 00:25:52,242
[No more mistakes]

628
00:25:54,583 --> 00:25:56,985
Anyone can do this when it's slow.

629
00:25:58,287 --> 00:25:59,588
The kitchen's really picking up now.

630
00:25:59,588 --> 00:26:01,724
[Today's goal: Prove I belong here]

631
00:26:01,724 --> 00:26:04,060
[Catching every little detail]

632
00:26:04,060 --> 00:26:05,127
Okay.

633
00:26:05,127 --> 00:26:07,463
[Doing well]

634
00:26:07,463 --> 00:26:11,700
[All in]

635
00:26:11,700 --> 00:26:17,040
[Kwon's in the groove, soup flying out]

636
00:26:17,907 --> 00:26:20,476
[The hurried office workers]

637
00:26:20,476 --> 00:26:22,244
[and others start their meal with bean soup]

638
00:26:22,244 --> 00:26:24,146
These guests are cool.

639
00:26:24,146 --> 00:26:25,846
Right.

640
00:26:28,417 --> 00:26:33,289
[Thinking he can handle soup solo...]

641
00:26:35,298 --> 00:26:40,029
The bank guests are arriving soon.

642
00:26:40,029 --> 00:26:41,097
[Peak time incoming]
In three minutes.

643
00:26:41,097 --> 00:26:42,898
The bank guests are coming in now.

644
00:26:42,898 --> 00:26:44,900
- A party.
- Ten people.

645
00:26:44,900 --> 00:26:47,870
[They have to eat fast]
So I told you to prep ahead.

646
00:26:47,870 --> 00:26:50,873
This is the bank guests' order ticket.

647
00:26:50,873 --> 00:26:53,008
[Rookie, let's prep]

648
00:26:53,008 --> 00:26:55,811
[Senior An starts with the antipasto]

649
00:26:55,811 --> 00:26:58,681
[Putting all ten portions
into the oven to bake]

650
00:26:58,681 --> 00:27:03,698
[Three minutes till the bank guests arrive]

651
00:27:04,687 --> 00:27:06,956
If you don't get everything prepped
in those three minutes,

652
00:27:06,956 --> 00:27:08,824
[Starts on bean soup]
it'll all unravel.

653
00:27:08,824 --> 00:27:10,059
- Hold on.
- Stop right there.

654
00:27:10,059 --> 00:27:11,772
You have to do the antipasto first
since it takes longer.

655
00:27:11,772 --> 00:27:13,229
- Okay.
- Start with the polenta fries.

656
00:27:13,229 --> 00:27:14,497
Kwon!

657
00:27:14,497 --> 00:27:16,465
The bean soup cools,
so plate it right before serving.

658
00:27:16,465 --> 00:27:18,234
[Notes raining down]
Yes.

659
00:27:18,234 --> 00:27:19,401
[More drained]
[Yes...]

660
00:27:19,401 --> 00:27:21,637
He was going to prep it before they arrived.

661
00:27:21,637 --> 00:27:23,005
Did you fry the polenta?

662
00:27:23,005 --> 00:27:24,773
[Scrambling]
I can do...

663
00:27:27,276 --> 00:27:31,947
[Quickly dropping it in]

664
00:27:31,947 --> 00:27:36,252
[Nerves kicking in, he gets flustered]

665
00:27:36,252 --> 00:27:40,789
[Bank guests arrive]

666
00:27:40,789 --> 00:27:42,724
There are so many.

667
00:27:43,658 --> 00:27:46,361
[Peak time and a tough party arriving]
Hello, good morning.

668
00:27:49,865 --> 00:27:51,534
[Bank guests seated]
The party arrived.

669
00:27:51,534 --> 00:27:53,401
"Hello."

670
00:27:55,137 --> 00:28:00,342
11 bank guests showed up.

671
00:28:00,342 --> 00:28:02,244
You said it went up to ten earlier.

672
00:28:02,244 --> 00:28:05,039
[Kitchen tensing up with the changes]
What? Now it's one more?

673
00:28:05,039 --> 00:28:06,415
[What do they do?]
Look at that...

674
00:28:06,415 --> 00:28:09,051
[Only ten antipasto platters in the oven]

675
00:28:09,051 --> 00:28:10,419
Only the people who have reserved should come.

676
00:28:10,419 --> 00:28:11,754
At least give us a heads-up.

677
00:28:11,754 --> 00:28:13,956
- You prepped accordingly.
- No heads-up. They booked for ten.

678
00:28:13,956 --> 00:28:16,276
Customers... That's customers for you.

679
00:28:16,276 --> 00:28:18,561
[Guest vs. chef conflict?]
It's almost opening time. Calm down.

680
00:28:18,561 --> 00:28:20,996
- This happens all the time.
- All the time.

681
00:28:20,996 --> 00:28:23,365
- It does. It happens constantly.
- You should always

682
00:28:23,365 --> 00:28:25,701
- have a buffer. There's no way around it.
- Right.

683
00:28:25,701 --> 00:28:28,704
Put one more antipasto platter in the oven.

684
00:28:28,704 --> 00:28:30,439
Yes.

685
00:28:30,439 --> 00:28:33,729
[Plus one more antipasto in the oven]

686
00:28:35,710 --> 00:28:37,346
[Is it baking right?]
- Kwon! - Yes.

687
00:28:37,346 --> 00:28:39,281
[Coming...]

688
00:28:39,281 --> 00:28:41,116
- Oil on the bean soup.
- Okay.

689
00:28:41,116 --> 00:28:44,253
- Hit the call bell, plate it, and send it out.
- Okay.

690
00:28:44,253 --> 00:28:46,021
Did you ring the call bell?

691
00:28:46,755 --> 00:28:49,058
It went from 8 to 10 to 11.

692
00:28:49,058 --> 00:28:50,192
[Kwon's too rattled to answer]

693
00:28:50,192 --> 00:28:52,027
Confusing.

694
00:28:53,729 --> 00:28:55,764
[Why isn't he ringing it?]

695
00:28:55,764 --> 00:28:58,100
[Locked into the bean soup]
Is the timer not working?

696
00:29:00,869 --> 00:29:03,372
[Senior An rings the bell himself]
It's not a timer, it's a call bell.

697
00:29:03,372 --> 00:29:05,480
I didn't know how to use it.

698
00:29:06,809 --> 00:29:10,279
[Setting off Senior An without knowing]
Senior An is getting a little annoyed.

699
00:29:10,279 --> 00:29:11,780
- Busy means edgy.
- Yeah.

700
00:29:11,780 --> 00:29:14,583
- Right.
- Things get tense when it's busy.

701
00:29:14,583 --> 00:29:16,685
[Bank guests' bean soup served]

702
00:29:16,685 --> 00:29:22,157
[No breather. Straight into antipasto prep]

703
00:29:22,157 --> 00:29:23,525
The antipasto.

704
00:29:23,525 --> 00:29:26,457
[Plates out for easy plating]

705
00:29:27,563 --> 00:29:28,866
[Lined up tight]

706
00:29:30,399 --> 00:29:33,068
[Starting with the beef roll plating]
- That's not how you do it, Kwon. - Sorry?

707
00:29:33,068 --> 00:29:34,803
- That's not the way.
- No?

708
00:29:34,803 --> 00:29:36,505
Let me show you.

709
00:29:36,505 --> 00:29:39,326
[Step aside...]

710
00:29:40,284 --> 00:29:42,678
[The stack-the-plates move!]

711
00:29:42,678 --> 00:29:44,947
- Tight space!
- Tight quarters.

712
00:29:44,947 --> 00:29:46,982
Max space efficiency.

713
00:29:46,982 --> 00:29:47,983
Now you put it aside.

714
00:29:47,983 --> 00:29:49,351
You need room in the middle.

715
00:29:49,351 --> 00:29:51,720
Okay.

716
00:29:51,720 --> 00:29:53,956
Right, you need space for the tray.

717
00:29:53,956 --> 00:29:55,958
[How to fit plates and tray together]

718
00:29:55,958 --> 00:29:57,760
[Beef roll]

719
00:29:57,760 --> 00:29:59,595
[Beef roll]

720
00:29:59,595 --> 00:30:01,697
[A much smoother plating flow]
Little things like this

721
00:30:01,697 --> 00:30:04,867
could be tips for people
in the restaurant business.

722
00:30:04,867 --> 00:30:07,202
[Senior An drizzles the sauce]

723
00:30:07,202 --> 00:30:08,651
[Kwon adds the cheese]

724
00:30:09,972 --> 00:30:12,641
[In sync]

725
00:30:12,641 --> 00:30:14,043
[Smooth]
I'm actually really good.

726
00:30:14,043 --> 00:30:15,444
He keeps saying he's good.

727
00:30:15,444 --> 00:30:17,413
[While Kwon does the sauce]

728
00:30:17,413 --> 00:30:20,376
[Senior An heads to the oven]

729
00:30:24,219 --> 00:30:26,021
- Attention.
- Okay.

730
00:30:26,855 --> 00:30:29,925
[Where Kwon piped the sauce]

731
00:30:29,925 --> 00:30:32,127
[Senior An tops with the roast in sync]
You're totally in sync.

732
00:30:32,127 --> 00:30:33,495
Of course.

733
00:30:33,495 --> 00:30:36,398
- Now pull out the polenta fries.
- Yes.

734
00:30:37,866 --> 00:30:39,292
[Golden]

735
00:30:40,235 --> 00:30:45,765
[Polenta fries on top, fast]

736
00:30:47,135 --> 00:30:49,999
Eleven antipasto platters for Table 2, done.

737
00:30:52,314 --> 00:30:55,284
[Finally]

738
00:30:55,284 --> 00:30:56,418
Enjoy your meal.

739
00:30:56,418 --> 00:30:59,413
[Eleven antipasto platters to the bank party]

740
00:31:01,890 --> 00:31:04,226
[Mm!]

741
00:31:04,226 --> 00:31:07,930
[The rushed bank guests finally start eating]

742
00:31:08,831 --> 00:31:11,868
On to the next order.

743
00:31:12,868 --> 00:31:16,572
[After that big rush]

744
00:31:16,572 --> 00:31:19,609
[the dark circles get even darker...]

745
00:31:20,676 --> 00:31:22,311
- You okay, Kwon?
- I'm okay.

746
00:31:22,311 --> 00:31:25,848
- Tired?
- No, I'm good.

747
00:31:25,848 --> 00:31:29,051
This is honestly pretty quiet.

748
00:31:29,051 --> 00:31:31,186
- Today?
- Today's calm.

749
00:31:31,186 --> 00:31:33,555
[Even Senior An gives off cocky energy]

750
00:31:33,555 --> 00:31:36,225
No way... Really?

751
00:31:36,225 --> 00:31:38,460
Look. I'm standing still right now.

752
00:31:38,460 --> 00:31:40,462
- We're all standing still.
- Me as well.

753
00:31:40,462 --> 00:31:42,564
[Just laughing]

754
00:31:42,564 --> 00:31:45,033
Hold on. Senior An is
kind of similar in personality?

755
00:31:45,033 --> 00:31:46,769
- Similar!
- A bit cocky too...

756
00:31:46,769 --> 00:31:48,237
[Kwon, the Naples defender?]
Everyone in Naples is like this.

757
00:31:48,237 --> 00:31:49,505
Naples people are all like that.

758
00:31:49,505 --> 00:31:51,240
[His personal opinion...]
Naples people? Come on!

759
00:31:51,240 --> 00:31:52,908
All people from Naples are cocky?

760
00:31:52,908 --> 00:31:54,909
Kwon doesn't seem to agree.

761
00:31:55,994 --> 00:31:59,114
[Meanwhile, every burner running full blast]
Pasta orders are flooding in now.

762
00:31:59,114 --> 00:32:02,885
The bank guests have to eat fast, right?

763
00:32:02,885 --> 00:32:05,287
Yes, but pretty much everyone
needs to leave quickly.

764
00:32:05,287 --> 00:32:10,008
I'll cut ten minutes off.

765
00:32:10,008 --> 00:32:13,295
[After antipasto, pasta gets the rush]
On to the pasta course.

766
00:32:13,295 --> 00:32:14,329
[Quick, quick...]

767
00:32:14,329 --> 00:32:18,326
Hold on while I plate the rest.

768
00:32:19,168 --> 00:32:22,137
[Main course station getting busy too]

769
00:32:22,137 --> 00:32:25,935
Get Table A's food out fast.

770
00:32:27,275 --> 00:32:30,679
[Rushed sauce splashes onto her chef coat]
No way...

771
00:32:30,679 --> 00:32:32,915
Even veterans make mistakes like this.

772
00:32:32,915 --> 00:32:35,117
- It's rushed and busy.
- Of course.

773
00:32:35,117 --> 00:32:37,218
[Watching closely...]
Take it easy, Laura.

774
00:32:37,820 --> 00:32:41,023
The rookie should run over and wipe it off.

775
00:32:41,023 --> 00:32:43,124
Wipe her coat?

776
00:32:43,124 --> 00:32:44,693
Isn't that a bit much?

777
00:32:44,693 --> 00:32:48,530
- Be glad your mentor isn't Jung Ji Sun!
- Run over and wipe it off like this.

778
00:32:48,530 --> 00:32:50,032
[Rookie 101 by Jung Sunny. Rule 1. Move fast!]
If your mentor were Ji Sun,

779
00:32:50,032 --> 00:32:51,400
- you'd be dead.
- He's not seeing the whole picture.

780
00:32:51,400 --> 00:32:52,568
That feels like too much.

781
00:32:52,568 --> 00:32:54,703
[Rookie... hard to keep up...]
Wiping her coat...

782
00:32:54,703 --> 00:32:57,439
[Pasta and main stations slammed]

783
00:32:57,439 --> 00:32:59,208
[Luisa arriving late to help]
Hi, come in.

784
00:32:59,208 --> 00:33:01,500
[Why are you here only now...]

785
00:33:03,212 --> 00:33:05,146
Laura, tell me what to do.

786
00:33:06,773 --> 00:33:09,044
Want me to help stir the potato pasta?

787
00:33:11,086 --> 00:33:15,491
[Everyone on the burners now]

788
00:33:15,491 --> 00:33:18,727
The appetizer station is a bit quiet now?

789
00:33:18,727 --> 00:33:20,629
For the moment.

790
00:33:20,629 --> 00:33:24,933
[Briefly empty appetizer station]

791
00:33:24,933 --> 00:33:27,721
[Kwon takes it]

792
00:33:30,639 --> 00:33:33,609
[Okay, antipasto]
[Two more to go...]

793
00:33:33,609 --> 00:33:35,277
This is great.

794
00:33:35,277 --> 00:33:37,546
[Senior An stepped away...]
I can do appetizers and dessert solo.

795
00:33:37,546 --> 00:33:39,448
[Chance to claim the appetizer station]

796
00:33:39,448 --> 00:33:42,951
[Sips water and locks in]

797
00:33:42,951 --> 00:33:45,821
[Don't make any mistakes]

798
00:33:45,821 --> 00:33:46,955
[And right on cue, another order]

799
00:33:46,955 --> 00:33:48,923
What's coming next?

800
00:33:50,626 --> 00:33:54,296
Prep six antipasti and six bean soups.

801
00:33:54,296 --> 00:33:56,098
- Six antipasti?
- Another six?

802
00:33:56,098 --> 00:33:58,667
[And so it begins]

803
00:33:58,667 --> 00:34:00,369
I'm working solo now.

804
00:34:00,369 --> 00:34:03,572
[Kwon's one-man show]
What? One-man show?

805
00:34:03,572 --> 00:34:04,840
[Starting with six antipasto platters]

806
00:34:04,840 --> 00:34:06,540
[Proud]
See?

807
00:34:07,809 --> 00:34:12,147
[A full tray of six antipasti, neatly packed]

808
00:34:12,147 --> 00:34:14,583
- Perfect.
- He's really good.

809
00:34:14,583 --> 00:34:16,685
- Kwon!
- Yes.

810
00:34:16,685 --> 00:34:18,987
What's wrong again?

811
00:34:19,721 --> 00:34:21,857
[Senior An, who'd been watching closely]

812
00:34:21,857 --> 00:34:23,959
- Kwon!
- Yes.

813
00:34:23,959 --> 00:34:26,087
[Come here]

814
00:34:26,087 --> 00:34:29,464
With this many antipasti,
you have to space them out.

815
00:34:29,464 --> 00:34:32,601
[Space them out...]
You need to space them out.

816
00:34:32,601 --> 00:34:35,904
- They won't heat up if they're touching.
- Okay.

817
00:34:35,904 --> 00:34:37,940
- Space them out.
- I should space them out.

818
00:34:37,940 --> 00:34:40,509
For the outside to be crispy.

819
00:34:40,509 --> 00:34:43,011
[Adjusting based on the feedback]
To get them crispy.

820
00:34:43,011 --> 00:34:46,278
[He wanted to handle it solo, but...]

821
00:34:47,849 --> 00:34:50,986
[From here on, no more mistakes]

822
00:34:50,986 --> 00:34:52,120
[Plating antipasto with fire]

823
00:34:52,120 --> 00:34:53,288
Good job.

824
00:34:53,288 --> 00:34:55,090
[Burning eyes]

825
00:34:55,090 --> 00:34:56,458
Look how locked in I am.

826
00:34:56,458 --> 00:35:01,537
[Carefully finishing the antipasto platters]

827
00:35:02,497 --> 00:35:04,935
Kwon! Did you fry the polenta?

828
00:35:04,935 --> 00:35:05,981
[Oops?]
What?

829
00:35:05,981 --> 00:35:07,302
- The polenta should've gone in earlier, right?
- Yeah.

830
00:35:07,302 --> 00:35:09,037
- For it to go out with everything.
- Exactly.

831
00:35:09,037 --> 00:35:10,839
- What?
- Not fried yet.

832
00:35:10,839 --> 00:35:12,374
I timed it precisely.

833
00:35:12,374 --> 00:35:14,543
Hold on, if it's like this now...

834
00:35:14,543 --> 00:35:15,711
It fries in one minute.

835
00:35:15,711 --> 00:35:17,212
The cook time has to line up.

836
00:35:17,212 --> 00:35:19,982
[Sung Jun, you should've fried it first]
Antipasto needs everything coming out together.

837
00:35:19,982 --> 00:35:21,617
[Okay]
Miss.

838
00:35:21,617 --> 00:35:25,020
- Seriously...
- No, just say it was a mistake.

839
00:35:25,020 --> 00:35:28,290
- Miss.
- Don't call it a miss. Mistake or not?

840
00:35:28,290 --> 00:35:29,993
Mistake.

841
00:35:29,993 --> 00:35:30,993
Small mistake.

842
00:35:30,993 --> 00:35:34,329
- Yes, anyone can make a mistake.
- Mistake.

843
00:35:35,063 --> 00:35:39,021
[Quickly starts frying the polenta]

844
00:35:40,268 --> 00:35:41,570
[Phew...]

845
00:35:42,404 --> 00:35:46,715
[Senior An has eyes in the back of his head]

846
00:35:47,709 --> 00:35:51,472
[Going solo is not easy]

847
00:35:52,681 --> 00:35:57,019
[Pushing through to make antipasto alone]

848
00:35:57,019 --> 00:35:58,387
[No escaping Senior An's watch]

849
00:35:58,387 --> 00:36:00,856
Senior An, please just do pasta.

850
00:36:00,856 --> 00:36:04,426
[Eyes constantly on Kwon]

851
00:36:04,426 --> 00:36:05,460
All table 2.

852
00:36:05,460 --> 00:36:08,563
[Sends the potato pasta out]

853
00:36:08,563 --> 00:36:09,965
Antipasti platter and fries.

854
00:36:09,965 --> 00:36:12,515
[Comes back with antipasto]
Behind you.

855
00:36:14,803 --> 00:36:16,071
[Edgy after Kwon's small slip,
anxious-type Senior An returns]

856
00:36:16,071 --> 00:36:17,272
[Mirrored expression]

857
00:36:17,272 --> 00:36:19,474
[Auto step-back]

858
00:36:19,474 --> 00:36:22,010
[Reading the room, helping with tomato sauce]

859
00:36:22,010 --> 00:36:23,710
Spray here too.

860
00:36:24,980 --> 00:36:27,604
[Zigzag]

861
00:36:29,451 --> 00:36:33,041
That's not how. Watch me.

862
00:36:33,689 --> 00:36:35,624
[Sweep, okay]
Squeeze in one spot to coat it in a circle.

863
00:36:35,624 --> 00:36:37,993
- Watch how the senior does it.
- So.

864
00:36:37,993 --> 00:36:39,728
A potato pie.

865
00:36:39,728 --> 00:36:42,798
[More orders during the sauce lesson]
- A potato pie? - Satisfaction.

866
00:36:42,798 --> 00:36:45,333
One potato mushroom flan
and one antipasto came in.

867
00:36:45,333 --> 00:36:47,002
You do this.

868
00:36:47,002 --> 00:36:49,542
[No more, truly no more mistakes]

869
00:36:51,540 --> 00:36:53,803
[Maybe his last chance to make up for lunch!]

870
00:36:55,577 --> 00:36:58,246
- Flan and antipasto both in the oven?
- Yes.

871
00:36:58,246 --> 00:37:00,449
That's not true. You only put the flan in.

872
00:37:00,449 --> 00:37:02,517
- I put the flan in.
- Not the antipasto?

873
00:37:02,517 --> 00:37:05,179
- One portion.
- One.

874
00:37:05,179 --> 00:37:07,689
[Another mistake]

875
00:37:07,689 --> 00:37:09,591
[Patience...]

876
00:37:09,591 --> 00:37:12,994
When you start in a kitchen,
there's a lot of understanding and patience.

877
00:37:12,994 --> 00:37:14,675
They forgive mistakes. There's tolerance.

878
00:37:14,675 --> 00:37:17,632
- Right, tolerance.
- We understand.

879
00:37:17,632 --> 00:37:21,369
But people get tired of those mistakes.

880
00:37:21,369 --> 00:37:25,188
[For example...]
"Pay attention, don't you remember?" Like that?

881
00:37:26,441 --> 00:37:29,177
[Rookie, the grace period is over]
The tone gets harsher.

882
00:37:29,177 --> 00:37:32,080
[Shrinking...]
But doing the tickets alone on day two

883
00:37:32,080 --> 00:37:34,216
- isn't easy.
- True.

884
00:37:34,216 --> 00:37:38,353
[The sauce piping he got called out on]

885
00:37:38,353 --> 00:37:39,988
[Eagle eye watch]

886
00:37:39,988 --> 00:37:42,591
- Here.
- Okay.

887
00:37:42,591 --> 00:37:44,493
[Senior An steps in to do it himself]
Look.

888
00:37:44,493 --> 00:37:46,695
He doesn't like it.

889
00:37:46,695 --> 00:37:47,929
That's the thing! Wrong direction!

890
00:37:47,929 --> 00:37:49,898
One smooth squeeze versus zigzag,
totally different.

891
00:37:49,898 --> 00:37:52,000
- Right, different.
- I do it in a more fine dining style.

892
00:37:52,000 --> 00:37:55,378
No, listen to the senior.

893
00:37:56,071 --> 00:37:57,873
[No communication]
There's a wall between us.

894
00:37:57,873 --> 00:37:59,574
Really.

895
00:37:59,574 --> 00:38:02,311
[And another senior failing to communicate]

896
00:38:03,293 --> 00:38:04,312
[Startled]

897
00:38:04,312 --> 00:38:07,215
[Worked up]
Table 8. Antipasti platter, meatballs

898
00:38:07,215 --> 00:38:09,217
and cotoletta with fries.

899
00:38:09,217 --> 00:38:13,822
[Maybe from trying too hard,
more mistakes than yesterday]

900
00:38:13,822 --> 00:38:16,191
But the thing is,

901
00:38:16,191 --> 00:38:19,895
I guess he feels comfortable around me now

902
00:38:19,895 --> 00:38:22,097
because he was speaking Italian
so much faster...

903
00:38:22,097 --> 00:38:24,266
It was harder to catch than yesterday.

904
00:38:24,266 --> 00:38:28,270
[I get it]
He talks like he's talking to a local,

905
00:38:28,270 --> 00:38:30,099
it wasn't easy.

906
00:38:30,739 --> 00:38:33,942
Kwon, leave what you're about
to take out in the oven.

907
00:38:33,942 --> 00:38:38,180
- You got it? Leave it in the oven longer.
- Okay.

908
00:38:38,180 --> 00:38:42,884
[The vibe gets tense
with every Kwon slip-up...]

909
00:38:42,884 --> 00:38:45,487
- Kwon, prep a zeppole for Table 6.
- Okay.

910
00:38:45,487 --> 00:38:47,992
A chocolate piece that says "Congratulations"

911
00:38:47,992 --> 00:38:50,125
- has to go on top.
- Yes.

912
00:38:50,125 --> 00:38:51,993
[This chocolate piece]
"Congratulations?"

913
00:38:51,993 --> 00:38:53,094
With chocolate?

914
00:38:53,094 --> 00:38:55,597
A chocolate piece that says "Congratulations"

915
00:38:55,597 --> 00:38:57,301
- has to go on top.
- Yes.

916
00:38:57,301 --> 00:38:58,457
Do you know what it is?

917
00:38:58,457 --> 00:38:59,601
[Did he really get it?]

918
00:38:59,601 --> 00:39:02,370
- He talks so fast...
- He really does.

919
00:39:02,370 --> 00:39:04,973
- Do you know what it is?
- Yes.

920
00:39:04,973 --> 00:39:09,344
If you didn't understand, it's totally fine.

921
00:39:09,344 --> 00:39:11,179
Yeah, just say you don't know.

922
00:39:11,179 --> 00:39:12,681
If it's a mistake, say it's a mistake.

923
00:39:12,681 --> 00:39:13,748
It's okay.

924
00:39:13,748 --> 00:39:15,250
Can I send the zeppole out like this?

925
00:39:15,250 --> 00:39:16,651
- Table 6.
- Table 6.

926
00:39:16,651 --> 00:39:18,887
But what did I just say? What else do you need?

927
00:39:18,887 --> 00:39:21,422
[He missed it again]
- Sorry? - What else do you need?

928
00:39:22,324 --> 00:39:26,161
[The instruction Kwon missed was...]
[Heart racing]

929
00:39:26,161 --> 00:39:28,463
- The call bell?
- No, the "Congratulations" chocolate piece.

930
00:39:28,463 --> 00:39:31,900
- You even said you got it just now.
- Yeah.

931
00:39:31,900 --> 00:39:33,835
Okay.

932
00:39:33,835 --> 00:39:38,673
- He's being a little harsh.
- It's a bit harsh.

933
00:39:39,307 --> 00:39:40,909
I can't follow. How could I?

934
00:39:40,909 --> 00:39:42,811
I'm pretending to understand.

935
00:39:42,811 --> 00:39:46,548
He asked a question
and didn't get a clear answer back,

936
00:39:46,548 --> 00:39:48,550
those moments must've happened.

937
00:39:48,550 --> 00:39:50,986
But you can't expect them

938
00:39:50,986 --> 00:39:55,423
to talk slowly during a busy service.

939
00:39:55,423 --> 00:39:56,524
Right.

940
00:39:56,524 --> 00:39:59,415
[Flushed from the string
of mistakes in the busy kitchen]

941
00:40:00,295 --> 00:40:02,891
Antonio might be even more frustrated...

942
00:40:04,065 --> 00:40:06,114
- Kwon!
- Yes.

943
00:40:07,202 --> 00:40:09,037
Outside?

944
00:40:09,037 --> 00:40:11,273
[Antonio suddenly takes Kwon outside]
I'm being dragged.

945
00:40:11,273 --> 00:40:13,341
I'm being dragged.

946
00:40:13,341 --> 00:40:15,944
Even getting yelled at is
something to be thankful for.

947
00:40:15,944 --> 00:40:17,411
I'm thankful.

948
00:40:17,411 --> 00:40:20,815
[Teary-eyed...]

949
00:40:20,815 --> 00:40:22,450
[One more time... don't get scared]
Mai paura.

950
00:40:22,450 --> 00:40:23,451
- Kwon!
- Yes.

951
00:40:23,451 --> 00:40:25,712
[Where is he being taken?]
I'm going outside for one second.

952
00:40:25,712 --> 00:40:27,923
- Follow me outside.
- Okay.

953
00:40:27,923 --> 00:40:29,190
He got called out?

954
00:40:29,190 --> 00:40:31,847
[Called to the backyard with no idea why...]

955
00:40:33,395 --> 00:40:35,221
[Kwon's face goes pale...]

956
00:40:35,221 --> 00:40:36,248
Sorry.

957
00:40:36,248 --> 00:40:41,350
[Where is he being taken...]

958
00:40:42,570 --> 00:40:46,241
[Parma, Italy] [Not Sam Kim, but Hee Tae]
[Day 2 of undercover]

959
00:40:46,241 --> 00:40:50,879
But right now, Chef Sam Kim's kitchen
is apparently a complete mess.

960
00:40:50,879 --> 00:40:54,549
- Some major incident supposedly went down.
- What? What did he do?

961
00:40:54,549 --> 00:40:56,584
What exactly happened?

962
00:40:56,584 --> 00:40:59,141
[So what happened to Hee Tae...?]
Let's roll the footage.

963
00:41:01,499 --> 00:41:04,626
[Day 2, D-4]
Day two.

964
00:41:04,626 --> 00:41:06,594
The scenery is so nice.

965
00:41:06,594 --> 00:41:10,165
Right. If only this were a vacation and not work.

966
00:41:10,165 --> 00:41:12,625
[Hee Tae looking really tired]

967
00:41:12,625 --> 00:41:14,669
[Different color from yesterday's confidence...]

968
00:41:14,669 --> 00:41:16,071
- Day one was...
- No...

969
00:41:16,071 --> 00:41:17,445
- Day one...
- That's a different person.

970
00:41:17,445 --> 00:41:18,974
The excitement and worry.

971
00:41:18,974 --> 00:41:20,709
- Different person.
- Day two looks like...

972
00:41:20,709 --> 00:41:22,811
he's on some cross-country trek.

973
00:41:22,811 --> 00:41:24,079
He's beat.

974
00:41:24,079 --> 00:41:25,780
It was really tough.

975
00:41:25,780 --> 00:41:29,398
[Looking back at Hee Tae the night before]

976
00:41:31,144 --> 00:41:33,545
[Oh...]

977
00:41:33,545 --> 00:41:36,825
[Ugh]

978
00:41:36,825 --> 00:41:40,636
[Why did he fall asleep in such agony?]

979
00:41:46,558 --> 00:41:49,327
[Aftermath of an ambitious Day 1]

980
00:41:49,327 --> 00:41:51,797
- Hee Tae, you try making the fresh pasta.
- Yes.

981
00:41:51,797 --> 00:41:53,865
He's thrown right into the deep end on day one.

982
00:41:53,865 --> 00:41:55,534
I said I was a farmer.

983
00:41:55,534 --> 00:41:58,537
Putting me on that on day one
doesn't make sense.

984
00:41:58,537 --> 00:41:59,604
- Hee Tae!
- Yes.

985
00:41:59,604 --> 00:42:02,474
Go with Lucrezia to serve gelato in the hall.

986
00:42:02,474 --> 00:42:04,609
Yeah, they pile it on early.

987
00:42:04,609 --> 00:42:07,679
[Sent to serve gelato face-to-face with guests]
Good evening everyone.

988
00:42:07,679 --> 00:42:09,314
Okay.

989
00:42:09,314 --> 00:42:13,552
[A lot of tasks for a rookie on day one]
Day one went well.

990
00:42:13,552 --> 00:42:15,464
[Groaning ending]

991
00:42:15,464 --> 00:42:17,689
- Did you sleep with the light on?
- He fell asleep the second he lay down.

992
00:42:17,689 --> 00:42:20,401
He really did sleep with the light on.

993
00:42:21,026 --> 00:42:22,727
He must have been exhausted.

994
00:42:22,727 --> 00:42:24,229
- He must've been really tired.
- Right.

995
00:42:24,229 --> 00:42:25,663
[Nodding]

996
00:42:26,698 --> 00:42:27,799
[But! AM 06:00]

997
00:42:27,799 --> 00:42:29,834
At 6:00 AM.

998
00:42:30,535 --> 00:42:32,137
[Up at the crack of dawn]

999
00:42:32,137 --> 00:42:34,506
He's already up at six?

1000
00:42:34,506 --> 00:42:37,676
[Munching]

1001
00:42:37,676 --> 00:42:39,578
[He's writing something in a notebook...]

1002
00:42:39,578 --> 00:42:43,548
There were things I couldn't ask yesterday.

1003
00:42:43,548 --> 00:42:45,383
How do I bring them up?

1004
00:42:45,383 --> 00:42:47,686
[He got up early
and wrote down a list of questions]

1005
00:42:47,686 --> 00:42:52,491
[Day 2 question notebook]
About asking them for exact measurements...

1006
00:42:52,491 --> 00:42:54,326
It's busy and to just...

1007
00:42:54,326 --> 00:42:56,795
Or if they could write it down.

1008
00:42:56,795 --> 00:42:59,564
The things he was curious about,

1009
00:42:59,564 --> 00:43:01,266
- he organized them out for real.
- I have to phrase it precisely.

1010
00:43:01,266 --> 00:43:03,401
[The sauce is so good, how did you make it?]
So I looked it up.

1011
00:43:03,401 --> 00:43:07,639
After last night's service,
while I was writing down what I'd do tomorrow,

1012
00:43:07,639 --> 00:43:09,241
he came over and asked me how today was.

1013
00:43:09,241 --> 00:43:11,510
Everyone was gathered around, and I...

1014
00:43:11,510 --> 00:43:14,279
How was your first day?

1015
00:43:14,279 --> 00:43:15,813
A little tired.

1016
00:43:15,813 --> 00:43:19,484
- A little tired.
- Because of jet lag.

1017
00:43:19,484 --> 00:43:24,356
Actually, I was a little tired
from the jet lag.

1018
00:43:24,356 --> 00:43:26,791
I'm a little wiped out, but...

1019
00:43:26,791 --> 00:43:29,895
- Even so, I'm happy right now.
- You're happy.

1020
00:43:29,895 --> 00:43:33,765
I'm in an Italian kitchen.

1021
00:43:33,765 --> 00:43:36,134
This is amazing.

1022
00:43:36,134 --> 00:43:38,937
- Thank you, Hee Tae.
- Thank you.

1023
00:43:38,937 --> 00:43:42,340
When I said "I'm happy
to be in an Italian kitchen,"

1024
00:43:42,340 --> 00:43:44,409
they really seemed to love it.

1025
00:43:44,409 --> 00:43:47,491
[Turns out studying really does pay off!]
Studying never fails you.

1026
00:43:48,446 --> 00:43:51,383
[Emotional appeal nailed it]
When you show love for the kitchen...

1027
00:43:51,383 --> 00:43:53,952
- They seem to love expressions like that.
- Right.

1028
00:43:53,952 --> 00:43:57,221
I prepared another heartfelt line for today.

1029
00:43:58,590 --> 00:44:00,993
Everyone, get ready to be moved!

1030
00:44:03,295 --> 00:44:05,597
I want to be a big help.

1031
00:44:05,597 --> 00:44:07,659
I'm sorry I haven't been more helpful.

1032
00:44:07,659 --> 00:44:08,700
[What is that?]

1033
00:44:08,700 --> 00:44:11,937
I'll run around even harder today.

1034
00:44:11,937 --> 00:44:13,838
[Still impressive on a rewatch]

1035
00:44:13,838 --> 00:44:18,718
If it's not rude,
I'll ask more proactively today.

1036
00:44:20,078 --> 00:44:22,581
[Will these heartfelt lines]

1037
00:44:22,581 --> 00:44:23,915
[help him escape rookie status?]

1038
00:44:23,915 --> 00:44:25,650
[Knock knock]

1039
00:44:25,650 --> 00:44:28,653
- Nobody's there.
- The door is always locked.

1040
00:44:28,653 --> 00:44:29,921
[Five minutes before opening AM 08:55]
He went early.

1041
00:44:29,921 --> 00:44:33,357
- There's no need to be that eager.
- Just clock in on time.

1042
00:44:34,593 --> 00:44:36,962
[Staff arriving one by one]
Good morning.

1043
00:44:36,962 --> 00:44:38,662
Good morning.

1044
00:44:39,998 --> 00:44:41,399
[Fresh pasta rival(?) Sorem is also arriving]

1045
00:44:41,399 --> 00:44:43,267
He's here.

1046
00:44:47,439 --> 00:44:49,774
He must be listening to music.

1047
00:44:51,710 --> 00:44:52,744
[Who?]

1048
00:44:52,744 --> 00:44:54,846
The owner, Giancarlo.

1049
00:44:54,846 --> 00:44:55,880
But it's still locked.

1050
00:44:55,880 --> 00:44:57,916
Yes, he's inside with the door locked.

1051
00:44:57,916 --> 00:44:59,551
He's listening to music.

1052
00:44:59,551 --> 00:45:01,453
- Really?
- Oh, he's listening to music?

1053
00:45:01,453 --> 00:45:04,889
He plays music loudly when he gets to work.

1054
00:45:04,889 --> 00:45:07,626
[The owner blasts music on arrival
and opens sharp at 9]

1055
00:45:07,626 --> 00:45:08,860
Hello.

1056
00:45:08,860 --> 00:45:11,663
- Hello.
- Hello.

1057
00:45:11,663 --> 00:45:12,731
[Head Chef No.1 is in!]
Hello.

1058
00:45:12,731 --> 00:45:13,765
Did you get some sleep?

1059
00:45:13,765 --> 00:45:16,167
- Yes, did you sleep well?
- Yes.

1060
00:45:16,167 --> 00:45:17,902
Very well.

1061
00:45:18,703 --> 00:45:20,538
Hello.

1062
00:45:20,538 --> 00:45:22,641
Let's all share these.

1063
00:45:22,641 --> 00:45:24,276
[No.2 brought something in a box]
Oh gosh.

1064
00:45:24,276 --> 00:45:25,877
Happy birthday, Simone.

1065
00:45:25,877 --> 00:45:27,479
Thank you.

1066
00:45:27,479 --> 00:45:28,747
Oh right.

1067
00:45:28,747 --> 00:45:30,415
He said his birthday was today.

1068
00:45:30,415 --> 00:45:32,516
- Simone's birthday.
- Right, Simone's birthday.

1069
00:45:33,151 --> 00:45:34,319
What is it? Bread?

1070
00:45:34,319 --> 00:45:35,787
Dessert.

1071
00:45:35,787 --> 00:45:38,223
[Cannoncini]

1072
00:45:39,003 --> 00:45:41,038
Doesn't Simone look old?

1073
00:45:43,094 --> 00:45:45,163
He looks really good.

1074
00:45:45,163 --> 00:45:47,565
Super stylish.

1075
00:45:50,268 --> 00:45:51,969
[What about me?]
You too.

1076
00:45:54,939 --> 00:45:57,409
- After a day it gets a bit easier.
- Right.

1077
00:45:57,409 --> 00:45:59,544
You're together all day, after all.

1078
00:45:59,544 --> 00:46:01,146
- She's here!
- Hello.

1079
00:46:01,146 --> 00:46:02,847
Hello.

1080
00:46:03,848 --> 00:46:06,717
- Hi, Simo! Happy birthday.
- Thank you.

1081
00:46:09,754 --> 00:46:12,866
[The owner shows up right at 9!]

1082
00:46:12,866 --> 00:46:14,192
- Hello.
- Hello.

1083
00:46:14,192 --> 00:46:16,629
- All right, time to work!
- Hello.

1084
00:46:17,696 --> 00:46:19,064
[Another day begins!]
I love that sound.

1085
00:46:19,064 --> 00:46:20,532
- The owner is so MZ.
- The chime opens the door.

1086
00:46:20,532 --> 00:46:22,466
- Right.
- It's wild.

1087
00:46:24,569 --> 00:46:27,572
I want...

1088
00:46:27,572 --> 00:46:30,141
I want to be a big help.

1089
00:46:30,141 --> 00:46:32,610
Oh, thank you.
Are you talking about my English?

1090
00:46:32,610 --> 00:46:35,280
[No! Your work]
I'll help you.

1091
00:46:35,280 --> 00:46:37,882
[Likability]
Thank you.

1092
00:46:37,882 --> 00:46:39,451
You can help with English too.

1093
00:46:39,451 --> 00:46:42,120
[Using the line he prepped before he forgets!]

1094
00:46:42,120 --> 00:46:43,288
[Bread hat on again today!]

1095
00:46:43,288 --> 00:46:45,490
It feels a bit lighter than yesterday.

1096
00:46:45,490 --> 00:46:47,058
- And the hat.
- After one day.

1097
00:46:47,058 --> 00:46:48,460
- It started suiting you.
- Really?

1098
00:46:48,460 --> 00:46:50,895
He's already adjusting.

1099
00:46:50,895 --> 00:46:53,631
- Hee Tae! Knead the yellow pasta.
- Yes!

1100
00:46:53,631 --> 00:46:55,800
- Me?
- Yes, you.

1101
00:46:57,268 --> 00:46:59,237
[Now grabbing the eggs on his own]
Starting with eggs again.

1102
00:46:59,237 --> 00:47:04,108
The mornings are always gelato,
fresh pasta dough.

1103
00:47:05,043 --> 00:47:07,278
[Adding flour on his own]

1104
00:47:07,278 --> 00:47:09,214
You memorized that in one day?

1105
00:47:09,214 --> 00:47:11,416
- Doing it again, it clicks.
- The body remembers.

1106
00:47:11,416 --> 00:47:14,135
[Day two and he's handling
fresh pasta dough solo!]

1107
00:47:14,135 --> 00:47:17,021
[Day 2]
My real concern is

1108
00:47:17,021 --> 00:47:19,924
how to get into the cooking line.

1109
00:47:19,924 --> 00:47:22,627
What can I do to attach myself
to the main station?

1110
00:47:22,627 --> 00:47:24,796
Is there a way?

1111
00:47:24,796 --> 00:47:26,476
[Rookie zone]
The roles are

1112
00:47:26,476 --> 00:47:29,100
[Senior zone]
so clearly fixed.

1113
00:47:29,801 --> 00:47:31,903
I need to break into the senior zone!

1114
00:47:31,903 --> 00:47:34,672
That's the only thing
on my mind the whole time.

1115
00:47:35,373 --> 00:47:38,509
[Glancing]

1116
00:47:39,210 --> 00:47:41,413
[I need to get into that zone fast...]
He keeps scoping it out.

1117
00:47:41,413 --> 00:47:44,983
[Territory Hee Tae's eyeing]
Everyone wants that. To grab the burner.

1118
00:47:44,983 --> 00:47:46,351
He's really staring.

1119
00:47:46,351 --> 00:47:48,887
He has to get there.

1120
00:47:48,887 --> 00:47:51,322
- I need to dip a toe to cross over.
- Right.

1121
00:47:51,322 --> 00:47:52,957
- If maybe...
- Getting a toe in isn't easy.

1122
00:47:52,957 --> 00:47:55,026
Maybe they'll call me over.

1123
00:47:55,026 --> 00:47:58,096
[A kitchen with no openings]
The puzzle is honestly all filled up right now.

1124
00:47:58,096 --> 00:47:59,831
[Packed tight]
There's no empty piece,

1125
00:47:59,831 --> 00:48:02,933
- so you have to push in.
- True.

1126
00:48:05,036 --> 00:48:07,972
[Hee Tae's strategy]

1127
00:48:07,972 --> 00:48:10,341
[Step 1: Finish my own tasks fast]
Honestly faster.

1128
00:48:10,341 --> 00:48:13,177
Cram all the prep in faster...

1129
00:48:15,713 --> 00:48:17,882
[Gelato prep done quickly!]

1130
00:48:17,882 --> 00:48:19,884
[Senior zone]

1131
00:48:19,884 --> 00:48:21,788
[Sneaking over]

1132
00:48:22,754 --> 00:48:24,289
Where should I put this?

1133
00:48:24,289 --> 00:48:25,757
Put it here.

1134
00:48:25,757 --> 00:48:28,026
Yes.

1135
00:48:28,026 --> 00:48:30,862
[Done already?]

1136
00:48:30,862 --> 00:48:31,963
[Thumbs-up earned]

1137
00:48:31,963 --> 00:48:35,800
You can put it here for now.
While we boil the potatoes.

1138
00:48:35,800 --> 00:48:37,268
Hi Paolo, good morning.

1139
00:48:37,268 --> 00:48:38,703
[Glance]

1140
00:48:38,703 --> 00:48:42,506
[Once you're done early and have a window...]
Get done with enough buffer and step in...

1141
00:48:43,708 --> 00:48:46,110
Head Chef?

1142
00:48:46,110 --> 00:48:47,345
- He worked up the courage.
- Head Chef?

1143
00:48:47,345 --> 00:48:49,147
Head Chef?

1144
00:48:49,147 --> 00:48:50,548
Head Chef?

1145
00:48:50,548 --> 00:48:53,518
- Is there anything I can help with?
- Anything?

1146
00:48:53,518 --> 00:48:55,854
Want to try that?

1147
00:48:55,854 --> 00:48:57,322
- Pigeon?
- Yeah.

1148
00:48:57,322 --> 00:48:58,623
- Pigeon?
- Yeah.

1149
00:48:58,623 --> 00:49:00,592
[Yes, absolutely!]
- Yes? - Okay.

1150
00:49:00,592 --> 00:49:03,127
- Pigeon?
- Pigeon.

1151
00:49:03,127 --> 00:49:04,128
Pigeon prep.

1152
00:49:04,128 --> 00:49:05,997
[Pigeon came to brave Hee Tae]

1153
00:49:05,997 --> 00:49:08,666
[Finally a chance to break
into the senior zone?]

1154
00:49:08,666 --> 00:49:11,803
There was nothing left to do
with the fresh pasta,

1155
00:49:11,803 --> 00:49:14,251
so I asked, "Want to try that?"

1156
00:49:14,251 --> 00:49:16,508
He seems like a careful person,

1157
00:49:16,508 --> 00:49:20,445
so I wanted to see how he'd handle the pigeon.

1158
00:49:20,445 --> 00:49:23,781
[But a new opportunity arrives...]

1159
00:49:23,781 --> 00:49:26,050
- Pigeon?
- Yes.

1160
00:49:26,050 --> 00:49:27,418
Pigeon...

1161
00:49:27,418 --> 00:49:29,220
You haven't touched pigeons in a while, right?

1162
00:49:29,220 --> 00:49:31,055
I hardly ever handle pigeons.

1163
00:49:31,055 --> 00:49:32,790
Hardly ever.

1164
00:49:33,925 --> 00:49:39,031
[Pigeon, not common
even for 27-year veteran Sam Kim]

1165
00:49:39,998 --> 00:49:41,600
This dish...

1166
00:49:41,600 --> 00:49:46,171
Pigeon is one of my favorite meats.

1167
00:49:46,171 --> 00:49:47,806
I thought about how to change it.

1168
00:49:47,806 --> 00:49:50,641
And I wanted some vegetables.

1169
00:49:52,143 --> 00:49:54,212
[Pigeon meatballs]
That looks good.

1170
00:49:54,212 --> 00:49:55,647
That looks great!

1171
00:49:55,647 --> 00:50:00,174
[Pigeon breast and leg meat]

1172
00:50:01,186 --> 00:50:02,554
With vegetables.

1173
00:50:02,554 --> 00:50:04,689
[Pigeon roast with spring vegetables]

1174
00:50:04,689 --> 00:50:09,628
We don't let just anyone handle pigeon.

1175
00:50:09,628 --> 00:50:13,531
It's small and delicate,
so a mistake means losing the whole thing.

1176
00:50:13,531 --> 00:50:16,001
So even if anyone wants to try,

1177
00:50:16,001 --> 00:50:20,338
we can't let them if they're not skilled.

1178
00:50:20,338 --> 00:50:21,373
- Right.
- That's precise work.

1179
00:50:21,373 --> 00:50:22,707
- Since it's small.
- Pigeon has very...

1180
00:50:22,707 --> 00:50:23,808
- Tough work.
- And the meat...

1181
00:50:23,808 --> 00:50:25,110
Tons of waste.

1182
00:50:25,110 --> 00:50:27,679
Right, you could waste valuable ingredients.

1183
00:50:27,679 --> 00:50:29,080
Yes, yes.

1184
00:50:29,080 --> 00:50:30,982
[Giving that to Hee Tae? Can he handle it?]

1185
00:50:30,982 --> 00:50:33,551
[Head Chef's crash course on pigeon prep]
- Cut, and after that... - Okay.

1186
00:50:33,551 --> 00:50:34,953
Okay?

1187
00:50:34,953 --> 00:50:38,356
The grip style varies a little,
even with chicken.

1188
00:50:38,356 --> 00:50:41,226
[Learning Head Chef Gianpietro's prep style]
But this chef has his own style.

1189
00:50:41,226 --> 00:50:44,629
You watch and pick up the style.

1190
00:50:44,629 --> 00:50:45,930
- Okay?
- Yes.

1191
00:50:45,930 --> 00:50:48,199
Thank you, Chef.

1192
00:50:48,199 --> 00:50:50,015
[Smirk!]

1193
00:50:50,879 --> 00:50:52,137
[Out of the fresh pasta zone
and into the senior zone!]

1194
00:50:52,137 --> 00:50:54,673
I think I saw it as an upgrade.

1195
00:50:54,673 --> 00:50:57,409
A different section,
the start of the second door.

1196
00:50:57,409 --> 00:51:00,145
[This won't be easy...]
You felt like they recognized you a bit.

1197
00:51:00,145 --> 00:51:02,047
With the tip of the knife.

1198
00:51:02,047 --> 00:51:04,783
Keep the blade as close
to the bone as possible,

1199
00:51:04,783 --> 00:51:07,519
[Slide]
and cut slowly.

1200
00:51:07,519 --> 00:51:09,554
Slowly slice it.

1201
00:51:09,554 --> 00:51:11,288
[Clean]
The center.

1202
00:51:13,758 --> 00:51:15,660
[Nice?]
Okay.

1203
00:51:15,660 --> 00:51:17,996
You cut close to the bone

1204
00:51:17,996 --> 00:51:20,264
- to make it slice cleanly.
- Yes.

1205
00:51:21,766 --> 00:51:23,990
[Glance]

1206
00:51:28,473 --> 00:51:29,607
[Clean cut]
Okay.

1207
00:51:29,607 --> 00:51:31,976
[Nice]

1208
00:51:31,976 --> 00:51:35,980
[He nailed pigeon prep on the first try?]

1209
00:51:35,980 --> 00:51:37,381
[Nod]

1210
00:51:38,717 --> 00:51:40,117
[Nod]

1211
00:51:41,686 --> 00:51:43,754
[Snip]

1212
00:51:45,790 --> 00:51:48,760
[Look at Hee Tae!]

1213
00:51:48,760 --> 00:51:50,816
[Glance]

1214
00:51:52,297 --> 00:51:56,279
Honestly, working with a knife
to some degree...

1215
00:51:56,279 --> 00:51:58,770
[Way too clean for a beginner]
without practice in your hands,

1216
00:51:58,770 --> 00:52:01,907
you'd look clumsy. But from the look of it...

1217
00:52:03,274 --> 00:52:05,710
- They must've liked it.
- Good job.

1218
00:52:05,710 --> 00:52:08,580
[Even 27-year Chef Sam Kim
wouldn't prep pigeon often...]

1219
00:52:08,580 --> 00:52:10,215
[Cluck]
It's anatomically similar to a chicken!

1220
00:52:10,215 --> 00:52:13,118
Snap the joint, snap, and cut it quick.

1221
00:52:13,118 --> 00:52:15,687
[That's 27 years of experience]
All poultry is pretty much the same.

1222
00:52:15,687 --> 00:52:19,023
Slice it open, snap, open, snap.

1223
00:52:21,292 --> 00:52:22,510
[Nod]

1224
00:52:22,510 --> 00:52:25,196
The Head Chef really likes it!

1225
00:52:25,196 --> 00:52:26,197
[Good!]

1226
00:52:26,197 --> 00:52:30,668
I was nodding because he followed my demo well.

1227
00:52:30,668 --> 00:52:34,205
I meant he did a great job.

1228
00:52:34,205 --> 00:52:37,443
If he'd done it poorly,
my expression would've been very different.

1229
00:52:38,877 --> 00:52:40,745
From what I observed,

1230
00:52:40,745 --> 00:52:45,984
he really understood how to use the knife
when prepping pigeon.

1231
00:52:45,984 --> 00:52:48,620
He seems to have good hands too.

1232
00:52:48,620 --> 00:52:52,157
He preps calmly and well.

1233
00:52:52,157 --> 00:52:56,361
He's not just working,
he's thinking while he works.

1234
00:52:56,361 --> 00:52:57,929
He thinks, "He fits our puzzle."

1235
00:52:57,929 --> 00:53:00,297
That's the vibe.

1236
00:53:01,699 --> 00:53:04,803
[After finishing pigeon prep
in the senior zone]

1237
00:53:04,803 --> 00:53:06,404
[He reads the room
and returns to the rookie zone!]

1238
00:53:06,404 --> 00:53:08,889
- Can I help?
- He's all over the place.

1239
00:53:08,889 --> 00:53:10,761
- Right.
- Looking everywhere.

1240
00:53:10,761 --> 00:53:13,111
I don't want to look idle, so I try not to.

1241
00:53:13,111 --> 00:53:16,014
- He moves so actively.
- Yeah, that's true.

1242
00:53:16,014 --> 00:53:19,559
Yes, press this.

1243
00:53:20,451 --> 00:53:22,487
Chef Gianpi.

1244
00:53:22,487 --> 00:53:25,089
[Head Chef Gianpi watches everything]

1245
00:53:25,089 --> 00:53:27,525
[Hee Tae's perfect!]
- Right. - Yes.

1246
00:53:27,525 --> 00:53:29,127
Perfect!

1247
00:53:29,127 --> 00:53:32,082
[Glance]

1248
00:53:34,299 --> 00:53:35,733
So.

1249
00:53:35,733 --> 00:53:38,336
- Lucrezia!
- Yes.

1250
00:53:38,336 --> 00:53:43,608
You and Hee Tae each make today's staff meal.

1251
00:53:43,608 --> 00:53:44,876
Okay.

1252
00:53:44,876 --> 00:53:50,048
You both make tortelli separately

1253
00:53:50,048 --> 00:53:53,268
and let's see who makes it better.

1254
00:53:53,268 --> 00:53:54,752
Okay.

1255
00:53:54,752 --> 00:53:56,855
Then I'll have to really put in the work.

1256
00:53:56,855 --> 00:54:00,859
I can't get shown up.

1257
00:54:00,859 --> 00:54:04,028
[Hee Tae doesn't know yet, but...]
I didn't catch a word of what they said.

1258
00:54:05,230 --> 00:54:06,931
- Showdown.
- Okay.

1259
00:54:06,931 --> 00:54:08,566
- A comparison?
- A showdown.

1260
00:54:08,566 --> 00:54:10,702
A showdown.

1261
00:54:10,702 --> 00:54:13,938
- Lu's competitive side just kicked in.
- Right?

1262
00:54:13,938 --> 00:54:15,907
He stoked her up.

1263
00:54:15,907 --> 00:54:18,243
But earlier you said something went down.
Is this it?

1264
00:54:18,243 --> 00:54:19,244
- Wait.
- This is real.

1265
00:54:19,244 --> 00:54:21,613
I just remembered this.

1266
00:54:21,613 --> 00:54:22,547
[Shaking head]
What happened?

1267
00:54:22,547 --> 00:54:25,516
- Something's up?
- Let's watch. Don't spoil it.

1268
00:54:25,516 --> 00:54:26,684
Something's up, right?

1269
00:54:26,684 --> 00:54:28,453
[Reveal in a moment]
Don't spoil it.

1270
00:54:28,453 --> 00:54:33,958
You each make 20 tortelli!

1271
00:54:33,958 --> 00:54:36,294
Don't help each other. Do it independently.

1272
00:54:36,294 --> 00:54:37,395
- Okay.
- Okay?

1273
00:54:37,395 --> 00:54:39,163
[What are they talking about?]

1274
00:54:39,163 --> 00:54:40,969
I didn't catch a word of what they said.

1275
00:54:40,969 --> 00:54:42,437
That's why you're like that.

1276
00:54:42,437 --> 00:54:44,535
[Is something going on?]

1277
00:54:44,535 --> 00:54:45,970
[No clue]
- Pasta? - Yeah.

1278
00:54:45,970 --> 00:54:48,539
Does Hee Tae know we're competing, Gianpi?

1279
00:54:49,140 --> 00:54:54,036
We take turns making tortelli

1280
00:54:54,036 --> 00:54:58,349
and have a showdown to see who makes it better.

1281
00:54:58,349 --> 00:55:00,652
- Really?
- Yes.

1282
00:55:00,652 --> 00:55:02,887
His voice even cracked.

1283
00:55:02,887 --> 00:55:04,222
- This is...
- He got that startled.

1284
00:55:04,222 --> 00:55:06,561
- Isn't this kind of forced?
- "Really?"

1285
00:55:06,561 --> 00:55:07,952
How am I going to win?

1286
00:55:07,952 --> 00:55:10,240
[6 years of tortelli vs. 2 days of tortelli]
I've never done it,

1287
00:55:10,240 --> 00:55:12,497
- but against someone who does it every day...
- That's true.

1288
00:55:12,497 --> 00:55:14,799
But Lu looks serious right now.

1289
00:55:14,799 --> 00:55:16,301
- Of course, it's a comparison.
- She can't lose.

1290
00:55:16,301 --> 00:55:18,336
[Lucrezia's pride is on the line too]
Right.

1291
00:55:18,336 --> 00:55:20,337
- Really?
- Yes.

1292
00:55:21,572 --> 00:55:24,483
[A showdown out of nowhere?]

1293
00:55:25,410 --> 00:55:27,244
[Flustered]
No way...

1294
00:55:29,914 --> 00:55:33,151
The reason I suggested this showdown,

1295
00:55:33,151 --> 00:55:36,720
Hee Tae has good hands,
so he was handling tortelli well too.

1296
00:55:37,555 --> 00:55:43,094
So I wanted to see
which of them makes it better.

1297
00:55:43,094 --> 00:55:46,531
I was also curious
if I could tell the difference in shape.

1298
00:55:46,531 --> 00:55:49,212
So without knowing who made which,

1299
00:55:49,212 --> 00:55:51,835
we did a fully blind test.

1300
00:55:52,637 --> 00:55:55,005
- A real showdown.
- A blind test?

1301
00:55:55,005 --> 00:55:57,342
On day two? Whoa, that's huge.

1302
00:55:57,342 --> 00:55:59,911
[Showdown: Cheese & potato tortelli]

1303
00:55:59,911 --> 00:56:03,781
[Each makes their own tortelli]

1304
00:56:03,781 --> 00:56:07,952
Simone, you will boil the pasta later.

1305
00:56:07,952 --> 00:56:13,091
I handled the boiling so the Chef wouldn't
know whose tortelli was whose.

1306
00:56:13,091 --> 00:56:16,995
[Both boiled blind for Head Chef to judge]
I divided Lucrezia's tortelli into one plate

1307
00:56:16,995 --> 00:56:18,863
and Hee Tae's into another plate...

1308
00:56:18,863 --> 00:56:22,070
So nobody knows whose is whose.

1309
00:56:22,070 --> 00:56:26,754
I'll look at the two plates, identify them,

1310
00:56:26,754 --> 00:56:28,606
and pick the better one.

1311
00:56:28,606 --> 00:56:32,343
[Head Chef judges in full blind mode]

1312
00:56:32,343 --> 00:56:34,846
- But the ingredients are the same.
- Right.

1313
00:56:34,846 --> 00:56:37,048
- Will the difference really show?
- Wouldn't they look the same?

1314
00:56:37,048 --> 00:56:40,751
[Can the Head Chef tell them apart?]
But I bet he'll tell right away.

1315
00:56:41,810 --> 00:56:42,894
I'm curious.

1316
00:56:42,894 --> 00:56:46,190
[Whose tortelli will turn out better?]

1317
00:56:46,190 --> 00:56:48,431
[Two rookies' pride is on the line]

1318
00:56:49,227 --> 00:56:52,956
[Fresh pasta blind test]

1319
00:56:53,898 --> 00:56:57,035
[Who wins this showdown?]

1320
00:56:57,035 --> 00:56:58,936
[Starting with Senior Lu!]
What's even happening with Lu?

1321
00:56:58,936 --> 00:57:01,005
Suddenly, it's a cooking show.

1322
00:57:01,005 --> 00:57:03,508
- Lu was just calmly cooking and...
- Suddenly a cooking show.

1323
00:57:03,508 --> 00:57:06,210
I just realized I was coming
for multiple people's jobs back there.

1324
00:57:06,210 --> 00:57:08,011
Right.

1325
00:57:08,713 --> 00:57:11,597
[Senior Lu starts the tortelli calmly]

1326
00:57:12,550 --> 00:57:16,988
[Hovering next to her]

1327
00:57:16,988 --> 00:57:20,792
Look at the hands. The movement is different.

1328
00:57:20,792 --> 00:57:22,126
- He's suddenly chatty.
- Got it.

1329
00:57:22,126 --> 00:57:23,628
- Come on.
- He's suddenly chatty.

1330
00:57:23,628 --> 00:57:24,962
I'll just watch.

1331
00:57:24,962 --> 00:57:26,397
He said he's comparing.

1332
00:57:26,397 --> 00:57:27,932
- He must feel awkward already.
- I get how he feels.

1333
00:57:27,932 --> 00:57:29,767
[A little nervous...]
Everyone can tell.

1334
00:57:29,767 --> 00:57:31,469
[Making potato tortelli]

1335
00:57:31,469 --> 00:57:33,938
I could memorize that method now.

1336
00:57:33,938 --> 00:57:37,008
- It's actually easy to mix up.
- Really?

1337
00:57:37,008 --> 00:57:39,639
[Glance]

1338
00:57:43,208 --> 00:57:48,086
[Did you know Hee Tae was watching?]
Yes, but I thought that was natural.

1339
00:57:48,086 --> 00:57:51,055
Hee Tae's only made tortelli for two days.

1340
00:57:51,055 --> 00:57:56,461
He'd naturally want to confirm
what he remembers is right.

1341
00:57:56,461 --> 00:58:00,364
[Senior Lu stays steady under Hee Tae's gaze]

1342
00:58:00,364 --> 00:58:01,666
You're really good.

1343
00:58:01,666 --> 00:58:04,168
Not really.

1344
00:58:06,345 --> 00:58:09,941
Lu looks kind of tough,

1345
00:58:09,941 --> 00:58:11,509
and she's really good.

1346
00:58:11,509 --> 00:58:13,544
She's done it for a long time,

1347
00:58:13,544 --> 00:58:14,645
so it's quick...

1348
00:58:14,645 --> 00:58:15,813
- Done it for a long time.
- He keeps putting her up.

1349
00:58:15,813 --> 00:58:17,081
- Constantly.
- He emphasizes how long she's done it.

1350
00:58:17,081 --> 00:58:18,616
[You're a 27-year veteran chef...]
He's hyping her up.

1351
00:58:18,616 --> 00:58:20,151
Got a lot to say already.

1352
00:58:20,151 --> 00:58:22,653
- A lot already.
- He's setting the stage.

1353
00:58:22,653 --> 00:58:23,888
When someone's good, you call it.

1354
00:58:23,888 --> 00:58:25,923
She's good, of course.

1355
00:58:25,923 --> 00:58:27,391
She's really good.

1356
00:58:27,391 --> 00:58:31,529
She's done it for a long time, so it's quick...

1357
00:58:31,529 --> 00:58:36,133
Lu is rougher and faster.

1358
00:58:37,902 --> 00:58:39,804
That's good.

1359
00:58:39,804 --> 00:58:41,572
No, come on.

1360
00:58:42,673 --> 00:58:46,043
But honestly, you're really good too!

1361
00:58:46,043 --> 00:58:47,745
- She says he's good.
- That's right!

1362
00:58:47,745 --> 00:58:49,747
They're complimenting each other a lot.

1363
00:58:49,747 --> 00:58:52,143
[They're trading compliments, but...]

1364
00:58:52,984 --> 00:58:56,053
Lu! You're nervous.

1365
00:58:57,021 --> 00:59:02,660
[Tension fills the kitchen]

1366
00:59:02,660 --> 00:59:04,228
She's done a ton.

1367
00:59:04,228 --> 00:59:06,063
[Lucrezia's cheese & potato tortelli done]
She does so many so fast.

1368
00:59:06,063 --> 00:59:07,932
Okay.

1369
00:59:07,932 --> 00:59:09,867
[My turn?]
Okay.

1370
00:59:09,867 --> 00:59:11,068
[First row is Lucrezia]
I'll pass you.

1371
00:59:11,068 --> 00:59:12,479
Yes.

1372
00:59:14,572 --> 00:59:16,272
[Whoosh]
Your turn.

1373
00:59:17,742 --> 00:59:20,873
[All right, my turn?]
All right. Now we'll see...

1374
00:59:22,380 --> 00:59:25,750
[Hee Tae also starts with potato tortelli!]

1375
00:59:25,750 --> 00:59:28,974
[Eyes locked in]

1376
00:59:31,489 --> 00:59:32,990
They're even.

1377
00:59:32,990 --> 00:59:35,326
Way more even than yesterday.

1378
00:59:35,326 --> 00:59:40,164
Yesterday he was piping twice
and stuff like that.

1379
00:59:40,164 --> 00:59:42,333
The entire time,

1380
00:59:42,333 --> 00:59:47,438
I was just thinking
about how to elevate the finish.

1381
00:59:47,438 --> 00:59:50,408
[More care than usual]

1382
00:59:50,408 --> 00:59:53,109
[Back at it!]

1383
00:59:53,911 --> 00:59:57,809
[No.2 keeps watching]

1384
00:59:58,849 --> 01:00:01,445
The Chef isn't allowed to look.

1385
01:00:02,887 --> 01:00:08,426
[Carefully making them
with 27 years on the line...]

1386
01:00:08,426 --> 01:00:10,027
[Hee Tae's tortelli look pretty solid]

1387
01:00:10,027 --> 01:00:12,129
They came out nicely.

1388
01:00:12,129 --> 01:00:15,235
[Plump!]

1389
01:00:15,235 --> 01:00:17,703
I should take the tortelli downstairs.

1390
01:00:18,405 --> 01:00:20,195
[Glancing]

1391
01:00:20,195 --> 01:00:22,167
She's keeping an eye on you.

1392
01:00:24,305 --> 01:00:27,375
I glanced at him,
but I didn't look closely on purpose.

1393
01:00:27,375 --> 01:00:30,355
It was a surprise challenge for me too.

1394
01:00:30,355 --> 01:00:32,135
I saw Hee Tae is good with his hands.

1395
01:00:32,135 --> 01:00:35,605
He learned to make them quickly.

1396
01:00:35,605 --> 01:00:37,445
Personally...

1397
01:00:37,445 --> 01:00:39,515
I was a bit anxious.

1398
01:00:39,515 --> 01:00:41,285
[No.3 Lucrezia, slightly anxious]
Oh, really?

1399
01:00:41,285 --> 01:00:43,495
- Lucrezia is very...
- She's competitive.

1400
01:00:43,495 --> 01:00:45,175
Lucrezia is quite competitive.

1401
01:00:45,175 --> 01:00:49,635
She listens closely to feedback on staff meals.

1402
01:00:49,635 --> 01:00:52,705
Even if I say it's delicious,
if she's not satisfied with it,

1403
01:00:52,705 --> 01:00:54,465
- she gets really...
- Oh, really?

1404
01:00:54,465 --> 01:00:57,185
She's very serious about cooking.

1405
01:00:57,185 --> 01:00:59,683
- Wait!
- Yes, yes.

1406
01:01:00,545 --> 01:01:02,545
I know, I know.

1407
01:01:03,415 --> 01:01:06,195
[Lu's Tortelli waiting to be boiled]

1408
01:01:06,195 --> 01:01:10,695
[Lucrezia's Tortelli / Hee Tae's Tortelli]

1409
01:01:10,695 --> 01:01:13,855
[Yeah, this should do!]

1410
01:01:13,855 --> 01:01:18,005
[Hee Tae's Potato Tortelli]

1411
01:01:18,005 --> 01:01:22,423
[Putting the Potato Tortelli in first]

1412
01:01:22,423 --> 01:01:25,935
We have to hurry now!

1413
01:01:27,815 --> 01:01:30,495
Did you... did you finish the potato tortelli?

1414
01:01:30,495 --> 01:01:33,285
Did you... did you finish the potato tortelli?

1415
01:01:33,285 --> 01:01:34,465
Oh!

1416
01:01:34,465 --> 01:01:36,871
Oh, no...

1417
01:01:36,871 --> 01:01:40,167
Hee Tae made the potato tortelli square.

1418
01:01:40,167 --> 01:01:41,455
Oh!

1419
01:01:41,455 --> 01:01:43,887
[Not again!]
Did you do it the wrong way again?

1420
01:01:44,945 --> 01:01:47,344
Did you do it the wrong way again?

1421
01:01:48,625 --> 01:01:51,765
No, I know how to do it!
I know the potato one is pinched.

1422
01:01:51,765 --> 01:01:53,815
I must have been nervous...

1423
01:01:53,815 --> 01:01:55,365
Oh, man.

1424
01:01:55,365 --> 01:01:57,555
You were on "Chef & My Fridge,"
and you're nervous?

1425
01:01:57,555 --> 01:01:59,905
[I'm upset]
Competition... My pride is a bit hurt.

1426
01:01:59,905 --> 01:02:02,725
[I don't know why I did that]
Oh, really...

1427
01:02:02,725 --> 01:02:05,191
[Potato Tortelli is finished with a side pinch]

1428
01:02:05,191 --> 01:02:08,103
[Senior chef Lu's perfect finish]

1429
01:02:08,103 --> 01:02:10,023
[But Hee Tae]

1430
01:02:10,023 --> 01:02:13,075
[Again! Square Potato Tortelli]

1431
01:02:13,715 --> 01:02:16,565
[He made the wrong shape so well]
The potato one...

1432
01:02:16,565 --> 01:02:19,155
[Aware of his mistake]
I made it in the elevator shape.

1433
01:02:19,845 --> 01:02:21,525
[The main chef saw it]
Gianpietro saw it.

1434
01:02:21,525 --> 01:02:23,825
Hee Tae! No.

1435
01:02:23,825 --> 01:02:25,525
It can't be helped.

1436
01:02:25,525 --> 01:02:29,012
We'll be able to tell whose
Potato Tortelli is whose.

1437
01:02:30,325 --> 01:02:32,805
[Humming]
Wait, she said that? I had no idea.

1438
01:02:32,805 --> 01:02:34,577
[Lu's already confident]
Since he already made a mistake.

1439
01:02:34,577 --> 01:02:36,361
- That's so funny.
- Right from the start.

1440
01:02:36,361 --> 01:02:37,975
[I can't believe she said that]
Oh, well.

1441
01:02:37,975 --> 01:02:41,935
More than anything, I just didn't want
Hee Tae to get his feelings hurt.

1442
01:02:41,935 --> 01:02:44,011
[Can't hide her smile]
He'd take it too seriously,

1443
01:02:44,011 --> 01:02:45,098
"Oh no, I messed up."

1444
01:02:45,098 --> 01:02:47,285
We felt really bad for him.

1445
01:02:47,285 --> 01:02:49,125
[Does this mean the result is obvious?]

1446
01:02:49,125 --> 01:02:51,285
Of course!

1447
01:02:51,285 --> 01:02:52,705
[I'm doomed]
It's a win by default.

1448
01:02:52,705 --> 01:02:54,785
Yeah, a win by default.

1449
01:02:54,785 --> 01:02:58,055
[If this happened during service]

1450
01:02:58,055 --> 01:03:02,575
[It's a major mistake that could've
served the wrong dish to a customer]

1451
01:03:02,575 --> 01:03:06,464
[Yesterday, because of this]

1452
01:03:08,375 --> 01:03:10,165
[Discarded!]
- I'm sorry. - Oh, dear.

1453
01:03:10,165 --> 01:03:11,615
It has to be thrown out.

1454
01:03:11,615 --> 01:03:12,915
- Oh, dear.
<i>- It's okay.</i>

1455
01:03:12,915 --> 01:03:15,635
[The boss even consoled him]
"It's okay."

1456
01:03:15,635 --> 01:03:17,635
"It's okay."

1457
01:03:18,305 --> 01:03:21,395
[To think I made the same mistake again]

1458
01:03:22,355 --> 01:03:24,545
[What's different is her smile?]
Go and take a walk.

1459
01:03:24,545 --> 01:03:25,745
She suddenly brightened up.

1460
01:03:25,745 --> 01:03:27,572
As you can see.

1461
01:03:28,246 --> 01:03:29,555
[Such contrasting expressions]

1462
01:03:29,555 --> 01:03:31,075
He must've been so embarrassed then.

1463
01:03:31,075 --> 01:03:32,165
Oh, man...

1464
01:03:32,165 --> 01:03:34,504
I was so embarrassed...

1465
01:03:35,395 --> 01:03:40,165
[Will the match end in vain like this?]

1466
01:03:41,655 --> 01:03:43,295
[Hmm]

1467
01:03:43,295 --> 01:03:45,879
Hee Tae was supposed to make potato tortelli...

1468
01:03:45,879 --> 01:03:48,355
But he made them square.

1469
01:03:48,355 --> 01:03:49,795
Now everyone knows who made them.

1470
01:03:49,795 --> 01:03:51,575
The word is out now.

1471
01:03:51,575 --> 01:03:53,615
Everyone over there is talking about it!

1472
01:03:53,615 --> 01:03:57,055
- Redo one serving of potato tortelli!
- One serving? Okay.

1473
01:03:57,055 --> 01:03:58,888
[Awkward]
So I did it again.

1474
01:03:58,888 --> 01:04:01,211
[Main Chef gives another chance]
- You did it again? - Yes.

1475
01:04:01,211 --> 01:04:03,155
It happens.

1476
01:04:03,155 --> 01:04:04,785
Mistakes can happen anytime.

1477
01:04:04,785 --> 01:04:06,975
Even we make mistakes.

1478
01:04:06,975 --> 01:04:09,815
It's common.

1479
01:04:09,815 --> 01:04:12,535
[No more mistakes!]

1480
01:04:13,235 --> 01:04:16,615
[Pinching both ends properly this time]
Now, make it round.

1481
01:04:16,615 --> 01:04:19,975
[Cutting meticulously!]

1482
01:04:20,727 --> 01:04:24,495
[Checking again so the filling doesn't leak]

1483
01:04:24,495 --> 01:04:27,225
[Potato tortelli back on track]
It came out nicely.

1484
01:04:27,935 --> 01:04:30,835
You have to be humiliated a bit to...

1485
01:04:30,835 --> 01:04:32,435
snap out of it.

1486
01:04:32,435 --> 01:04:37,555
[Hee Tae's cheese & potato tortelli and]

1487
01:04:37,555 --> 01:04:42,455
[Lu's tortelli are boiling at the same time]

1488
01:04:42,455 --> 01:04:45,735
[While they're being served on the same plate]

1489
01:04:45,735 --> 01:04:48,007
[Main Chef on standby]
We won't tell the chef yet.

1490
01:04:48,007 --> 01:04:49,869
They're being very thorough.

1491
01:04:49,869 --> 01:04:52,135
[Results about to be revealed]
It's a blind test.

1492
01:04:52,135 --> 01:04:54,375
- Lu?
- Yes.

1493
01:04:54,375 --> 01:04:55,875
Who...

1494
01:04:55,875 --> 01:04:58,245
Who made what? I don't know.

1495
01:04:58,245 --> 01:05:02,945
I don't know. Simone plated them,
so only he knows.

1496
01:05:03,745 --> 01:05:06,295
[Let's see]
Can't you tell just by looking?

1497
01:05:06,295 --> 01:05:08,513
They look quite similar.

1498
01:05:09,775 --> 01:05:13,425
[Pretty close]
They look very similar.

1499
01:05:13,425 --> 01:05:17,535
[But they are clearly different tortelli
made by two different people!]

1500
01:05:17,535 --> 01:05:20,175
[What's the evaluation criteria
for this match?]

1501
01:05:20,175 --> 01:05:22,995
Actually, the taste...

1502
01:05:22,995 --> 01:05:25,125
wasn't the main factor.

1503
01:05:25,125 --> 01:05:26,805
Because the filling was the same.

1504
01:05:26,805 --> 01:05:31,075
The key point was
how the tortelli was wrapped and shaped.

1505
01:05:31,075 --> 01:05:36,682
The difference in skill shows
in how the pasta is closed.

1506
01:05:37,735 --> 01:05:40,995
[Don't be nervous]

1507
01:05:43,399 --> 01:05:46,645
[The moment of decision]

1508
01:05:48,295 --> 01:05:51,285
[Can the chef tell whose tortelli is whose?]
I think he'll know right away.

1509
01:05:51,285 --> 01:05:53,486
Let's see.

1510
01:05:53,486 --> 01:05:57,943
[Who made the better tortelli shape!]
Let's see which one is Hee Tae's.

1511
01:05:57,943 --> 01:06:00,175
- Gianpietro.
- One Petrov.

1512
01:06:00,175 --> 01:06:01,975
[They deliver it to the main chef]
One.

1513
01:06:01,975 --> 01:06:03,585
Thank you.

1514
01:06:06,545 --> 01:06:10,208
[Nervous juniors]

1515
01:06:10,945 --> 01:06:12,835
You have to guess.

1516
01:06:13,655 --> 01:06:16,515
[He looks at No. 3 Lucrezia's tortelli]

1517
01:06:16,515 --> 01:06:18,625
This is Lu's.

1518
01:06:18,625 --> 01:06:21,185
And this is Hee Tae's.

1519
01:06:21,185 --> 01:06:23,187
This is Lu's.

1520
01:06:23,187 --> 01:06:24,675
And this is Hee Tae's.

1521
01:06:24,675 --> 01:06:26,935
[Tells their tortelli apart at a glance]
He got it right away?

1522
01:06:26,935 --> 01:06:28,429
He got it right away.

1523
01:06:28,429 --> 01:06:29,815
- He got it right away.
- Right.

1524
01:06:29,815 --> 01:06:31,295
- As expected.
- As expected.

1525
01:06:31,295 --> 01:06:32,375
He already figured it out.

1526
01:06:32,375 --> 01:06:33,695
This is Lucrezia's,

1527
01:06:33,695 --> 01:06:36,545
and this is Hee Tae's.

1528
01:06:36,545 --> 01:06:38,935
They look the same to me.

1529
01:06:38,935 --> 01:06:40,195
He can tell just by looking...

1530
01:06:40,195 --> 01:06:43,075
[Bitter]

1531
01:06:43,075 --> 01:06:44,385
Hee Tae's.

1532
01:06:44,385 --> 01:06:46,460
[Flustered]

1533
01:06:46,460 --> 01:06:49,540
Great job, Hee Tae.

1534
01:06:50,275 --> 01:06:53,175
[The atmosphere is a bit...]

1535
01:06:53,175 --> 01:06:54,335
[Good job, kitchen junior!]

1536
01:06:54,335 --> 01:06:57,155
[Is everyone comforting Hee Tae?]

1537
01:06:57,155 --> 01:06:59,525
[Yes... Yes, sir]

1538
01:06:59,525 --> 01:07:01,975
[The match is already over]

1539
01:07:01,975 --> 01:07:03,335
The match is already over...

1540
01:07:03,335 --> 01:07:04,885
What?

1541
01:07:04,885 --> 01:07:06,335
The match is over.

1542
01:07:06,335 --> 01:07:08,565
- Is that how it works?
- Good job.

1543
01:07:08,565 --> 01:07:10,029
It's okay.

1544
01:07:10,029 --> 01:07:12,375
[When the boss's comfort needs a translator]
It's all okay.

1545
01:07:12,375 --> 01:07:14,245
It's all okay.

1546
01:07:14,245 --> 01:07:16,644
[Teasing until the end]
It's all okay.

1547
01:07:17,715 --> 01:07:21,385
[It was so easy to tell]
Good job, good job.

1548
01:07:21,385 --> 01:07:23,034
She's the one who always makes it.

1549
01:07:23,034 --> 01:07:26,245
[Is the senior's wall that high?]

1550
01:07:26,245 --> 01:07:28,958
[Is my tortelli that ugly?]
So what was the difference?

1551
01:07:30,915 --> 01:07:35,295
It was a match between Seoul and Naples!

1552
01:07:35,295 --> 01:07:37,315
- It was a match.
- Seoul and Naples.

1553
01:07:37,315 --> 01:07:40,135
You bet the pride of Seoul on this?

1554
01:07:40,135 --> 01:07:43,495
As a Seoulite, I'm a bit...

1555
01:07:43,495 --> 01:07:45,575
My pride is hurt.

1556
01:07:46,275 --> 01:07:47,815
So who won?

1557
01:07:47,815 --> 01:07:51,034
You can see the difference in the tortelli.

1558
01:07:51,034 --> 01:07:52,565
[So who is the winner of this match?]

1559
01:07:52,565 --> 01:07:53,685
You mean the tortelli?

1560
01:07:53,685 --> 01:07:55,765
I recognized it immediately.

1561
01:07:55,765 --> 01:07:58,455
I recognized it immediately!

1562
01:07:58,455 --> 01:08:01,025
[Did Hee Tae's tortelli look bad?]

1563
01:08:01,025 --> 01:08:03,505
No, no! Rather than that...

1564
01:08:03,505 --> 01:08:06,545
Absurdly enough, it looked prettier.

1565
01:08:06,545 --> 01:08:09,045
Huh? What?

1566
01:08:09,045 --> 01:08:10,785
Huh? What?

1567
01:08:10,785 --> 01:08:13,796
[My tortelli was prettier?]
- He said it was prettier! - Really?

1568
01:08:14,565 --> 01:08:18,655
[Hee Tae Reaction Cam]
When wrapping the tortelli filling,

1569
01:08:18,655 --> 01:08:22,195
it was obvious who made which.

1570
01:08:22,195 --> 01:08:24,885
Unlike Lucrezia, Hee Tae's...

1571
01:08:24,885 --> 01:08:28,035
It's absurd, but it was more accurate.

1572
01:08:28,035 --> 01:08:31,135
The potato tortelli was perfectly shaped.

1573
01:08:31,135 --> 01:08:32,535
It's your first time hearing this?

1574
01:08:32,535 --> 01:08:34,565
Yes, it's my first time.

1575
01:08:34,565 --> 01:08:36,035
[Is that true?]

1576
01:08:36,035 --> 01:08:39,205
How you close the tortelli is important.

1577
01:08:39,205 --> 01:08:41,715
[He fixed the shape many times]
It was tightened very well.

1578
01:08:41,715 --> 01:08:43,765
The shape was really beautiful.

1579
01:08:43,765 --> 01:08:45,345
[Sudden change of attitude]

1580
01:08:45,345 --> 01:08:48,975
You must pull the dough as tight
as possible to wrap the filling like Hee Tae.

1581
01:08:48,975 --> 01:08:52,071
That way, when the tortelli is cooked,

1582
01:08:52,071 --> 01:08:55,575
it puffs up and looks much fuller.

1583
01:08:55,575 --> 01:08:57,045
The tortelli...

1584
01:08:57,045 --> 01:08:59,735
I don't like it when it collapses
after being boiled.

1585
01:08:59,735 --> 01:09:01,015
I tried to make them like this.

1586
01:09:01,015 --> 01:09:03,075
I pressed them tight to make them stand up,

1587
01:09:03,075 --> 01:09:05,025
trying to prevent them from collapsing.

1588
01:09:05,025 --> 01:09:08,495
[Pressed firmly to make them chewier!]
That's the style I prefer.

1589
01:09:09,475 --> 01:09:11,445
If you don't pull the dough tight enough,

1590
01:09:11,445 --> 01:09:13,815
it'll go flat when placed on the plate.

1591
01:09:13,815 --> 01:09:16,595
Oh, so it goes flat.

1592
01:09:16,595 --> 01:09:20,178
[Hee Tae's tortelli, pressed once more]
It will puff up more like this.

1593
01:09:21,650 --> 01:09:23,348
[Lucrezia's vs. Hee Tae's potato tortelli]

1594
01:09:23,348 --> 01:09:26,645
[Hard to tell the difference from above]

1595
01:09:26,645 --> 01:09:29,095
[Pasta that isn't sealed well gets soggy
from the moisture]

1596
01:09:29,095 --> 01:09:30,625
Oh, you're right.

1597
01:09:30,625 --> 01:09:32,485
Wow, they're so different.

1598
01:09:32,485 --> 01:09:35,025
[The more it puffs, the chewier it is!]

1599
01:09:35,025 --> 01:09:37,315
If made like Hee Tae's, it puffs up more.

1600
01:09:37,315 --> 01:09:39,063
Hee Tae understood this point.

1601
01:09:39,063 --> 01:09:42,031
Hee Tae's tortelli were shaped so well

1602
01:09:42,031 --> 01:09:44,175
- that I felt they were better.
- That's a good thing!

1603
01:09:44,175 --> 01:09:46,215
- Exactly.
- It was a compliment.

1604
01:09:46,215 --> 01:09:47,975
[Winner: Hee Tae wins the evaluation!]

1605
01:09:47,975 --> 01:09:50,175
Oh, wow. He's going that far?

1606
01:09:50,175 --> 01:09:52,855
- Is this okay?
- He's being that honest?

1607
01:09:52,855 --> 01:09:55,277
Man, this is an unexpected loss for Lu.

1608
01:09:55,277 --> 01:09:56,565
When she sees this broadcast...

1609
01:09:56,565 --> 01:09:57,905
Lu is probably a bit...

1610
01:09:57,905 --> 01:10:00,077
She went silent.

1611
01:10:01,205 --> 01:10:04,515
[But actually]
Lu is still there, but...

1612
01:10:04,515 --> 01:10:06,595
[The one who really went silent was Hee Tae]
- Cheese and potato. - No.

1613
01:10:06,595 --> 01:10:09,285
Both cheese and potatoes.

1614
01:10:09,285 --> 01:10:12,625
[Italian language limit exceeded]
- It's the pinching. - The pinching.

1615
01:10:12,625 --> 01:10:14,065
[Who won?]
Never eaten with this kind of pinching.

1616
01:10:14,065 --> 01:10:17,535
He's disappointed, not knowing the truth.

1617
01:10:17,535 --> 01:10:21,175
Mine are a bit more pressed down.

1618
01:10:21,175 --> 01:10:24,759
[Even Lu accepts the result]

1619
01:10:24,759 --> 01:10:27,555
[The owner takes a bite too]

1620
01:10:27,555 --> 01:10:29,446
It's delicious!

1621
01:10:32,065 --> 01:10:34,175
[A gesture of approval!]

1622
01:10:35,825 --> 01:10:40,455
[Praying since he doesn't know
what's happening]

1623
01:10:42,935 --> 01:10:45,125
My reputation is already gone.

1624
01:10:45,125 --> 01:10:49,831
Not that it was great before!

1625
01:10:49,831 --> 01:10:53,096
[Everyone praises Hee Tae, but he has no idea]
You can only do better.

1626
01:10:54,455 --> 01:10:56,305
He doesn't know.

1627
01:10:56,305 --> 01:10:58,625
He just thinks his stood out in a bad way.

1628
01:10:58,625 --> 01:11:00,967
- That's all he's thinking right now.
- Right, right.

1629
01:11:00,967 --> 01:11:03,155
You're seeing the evaluation now

1630
01:11:03,155 --> 01:11:04,764
through this video for the first time.

1631
01:11:04,764 --> 01:11:06,053
How do you feel?

1632
01:11:06,053 --> 01:11:07,543
I feel great.

1633
01:11:07,543 --> 01:11:09,047
Because actually...

1634
01:11:09,047 --> 01:11:11,335
At the time, the chef told me,

1635
01:11:11,335 --> 01:11:12,545
"Hey, you did better."

1636
01:11:12,545 --> 01:11:13,831
"You won," he said.

1637
01:11:13,831 --> 01:11:14,919
He said that compliment...

1638
01:11:14,919 --> 01:11:17,352
- just to encourage me...
- To comfort you.

1639
01:11:17,352 --> 01:11:19,455
I thought that's what he meant.

1640
01:11:19,455 --> 01:11:21,475
- I think he really meant it.
- It's true.

1641
01:11:21,475 --> 01:11:24,295
- I'm even more surprised seeing this now.
- Of course.

1642
01:11:24,295 --> 01:11:26,631
[Current time 12:00 PM]
Hello.

1643
01:11:26,631 --> 01:11:28,743
[Lunch service begins]
Now, the customers...

1644
01:11:28,743 --> 01:11:29,975
It's time to open.

1645
01:11:29,975 --> 01:11:33,191
[Customers swarm in as they open]
This restaurant is really hard to book.

1646
01:11:33,191 --> 01:11:36,135
[It's starting]

1647
01:11:36,135 --> 01:11:39,927
[Packed with people eager to enjoy the food]

1648
01:11:39,927 --> 01:11:41,015
Okay!

1649
01:11:41,015 --> 01:11:43,215
Let's go!

1650
01:11:43,215 --> 01:11:46,149
Don't slow down!

1651
01:11:46,951 --> 01:11:50,951
[Lunch service begins
with the staff in tension]

1652
01:11:50,951 --> 01:11:53,895
[Where is Hee Tae?]

1653
01:11:53,895 --> 01:11:55,445
[Agile]
Now...

1654
01:11:55,445 --> 01:11:59,719
[Hee Tae stands at the fresh pasta station]

1655
01:11:59,719 --> 01:12:03,025
[Day 2, what's expected of the junior Hee Tae?]

1656
01:12:03,025 --> 01:12:06,005
What he needs to do now is actually...

1657
01:12:06,005 --> 01:12:08,663
just speed up at the fresh pasta station.

1658
01:12:08,663 --> 01:12:12,167
What we wanted from Hee Tae today...

1659
01:12:12,167 --> 01:12:16,065
was to handle the pasta prep 100% on his own.

1660
01:12:16,065 --> 01:12:19,815
Hee Tae is doing the work accurately,

1661
01:12:19,815 --> 01:12:24,039
so he just needs to speed up with confidence.

1662
01:12:24,039 --> 01:12:26,439
[Hee Tae is in charge of fresh pasta]
On my second day...

1663
01:12:26,439 --> 01:12:28,119
So he's completely taken over.

1664
01:12:28,119 --> 01:12:30,375
He's officially in charge of this section.

1665
01:12:30,375 --> 01:12:33,510
In charge of pasta on day 2?

1666
01:12:34,583 --> 01:12:38,601
[Expectations rise after the duel with Lu]
Wow, it's a big challenge to trust him.

1667
01:12:40,606 --> 01:12:44,096
I'm expecting Hee Tae to go a step further.

1668
01:12:45,905 --> 01:12:48,823
I had no idea all this was happening...

1669
01:12:48,823 --> 01:12:50,327
I was just working.

1670
01:12:50,327 --> 01:12:52,655
You had no idea they were saying this.

1671
01:12:53,511 --> 01:12:55,127
[Hee Tae's solo stage, built on trust]

1672
01:12:55,127 --> 01:12:58,089
[But he has no idea]

1673
01:12:58,803 --> 01:13:00,329
I really want to do well.

1674
01:13:00,329 --> 01:13:02,335
[If he does well, can he move to the stove?]

1675
01:13:02,335 --> 01:13:04,035
[The orders begin]
Order: salami and pie.

1676
01:13:04,035 --> 01:13:05,271
[Order 1]
Then ham,

1677
01:13:05,271 --> 01:13:07,751
[And Hee Tae is in charge of Cheese Tortelli]
rabbit, salad.

1678
01:13:07,751 --> 01:13:09,527
[Order 2]
[Listen to the order]

1679
01:13:09,527 --> 01:13:13,106
[Hee Tae handles tortelli and tagliatelle]
Polenta and gorgonzola, then tagliatella.

1680
01:13:13,106 --> 01:13:15,063
[Translating into English]
Sorem was next to me.

1681
01:13:15,063 --> 01:13:17,031
He kept telling me what I couldn't hear.

1682
01:13:17,031 --> 01:13:18,551
Like, how many of each need to go in.

1683
01:13:18,551 --> 01:13:20,151
He'd summarize it for me once more.

1684
01:13:20,151 --> 01:13:22,665
Ah, because he's good at English.

1685
01:13:22,665 --> 01:13:24,647
[Grateful for Sorem]
Sorem is playing a huge role.

1686
01:13:24,647 --> 01:13:25,831
He helped me out so much.

1687
01:13:25,831 --> 01:13:27,319
[But]
Order, animella and egg.

1688
01:13:27,319 --> 01:13:28,823
Then two cheese tortelli.

1689
01:13:28,823 --> 01:13:30,295
Wow, look at all these orders.

1690
01:13:30,295 --> 01:13:33,218
[Orders keep coming]
[The pasta Hee Tae must make right away is...]

1691
01:13:33,218 --> 01:13:34,729
[Total of five dishes]

1692
01:13:34,729 --> 01:13:36,823
Ah, that moment was really tough.

1693
01:13:36,823 --> 01:13:38,785
I wondered, "Can I handle this alone?"

1694
01:13:38,785 --> 01:13:42,915
[Starting with cheese tortelli]
That must've been so stressful.

1695
01:13:42,915 --> 01:13:46,639
The thing about lunch is, no appetizers,
so the pasta goes out right away.

1696
01:13:46,639 --> 01:13:48,135
- Right.
- So the orders just pile up.

1697
01:13:48,135 --> 01:13:49,783
If the pasta doesn't go out...

1698
01:13:49,783 --> 01:13:55,319
[Hee Tae's tasks:
Four cheese tortelli and two duck tagliatelle]

1699
01:13:55,319 --> 01:13:59,447
[Cheese tortelli is the pasta
Hee Tae has made the most]

1700
01:13:59,447 --> 01:14:03,568
[He even did well in the blind test
a moment ago]

1701
01:14:03,568 --> 01:14:04,851
[Starting two rows at once!]

1702
01:14:04,851 --> 01:14:08,167
- He's completely used to it now.
- Totally.

1703
01:14:08,167 --> 01:14:10,405
He's really focused now.

1704
01:14:10,405 --> 01:14:13,047
[Trying to fill them quickly]

1705
01:14:13,831 --> 01:14:15,795
[Struggling]

1706
01:14:15,795 --> 01:14:18,203
If the filling is too cold,
it doesn't squeeze out well.

1707
01:14:18,203 --> 01:14:20,727
It's not coming out...

1708
01:14:20,727 --> 01:14:22,565
Next order is two cheese tortelli,

1709
01:14:22,565 --> 01:14:26,327
[Another order comes in!]
fried pie as bread for one, one tagliatella.

1710
01:14:26,327 --> 01:14:29,605
Wow, he's basically rapping the orders.

1711
01:14:29,605 --> 01:14:33,351
[Orders 1, 2, 3 in progress, and Order 4 added]
That must be so overwhelming.

1712
01:14:33,351 --> 01:14:36,439
[A flood of orders]
Oh no, it's an emergency.

1713
01:14:36,439 --> 01:14:39,863
[He just started folding
2 portions of Cheese Tortelli]

1714
01:14:39,863 --> 01:14:42,823
It looks like a famous handmade dumpling shop.

1715
01:14:42,823 --> 01:14:46,618
You know those elders at the market stalls.

1716
01:14:46,618 --> 01:14:48,039
That's exactly what it looks like.

1717
01:14:48,039 --> 01:14:51,495
Actually, at this point,
I started to feel a bit dazed.

1718
01:14:51,495 --> 01:14:53,159
Like, "Why am I here?"

1719
01:14:53,159 --> 01:14:56,306
That kind of moment finally came.

1720
01:14:58,583 --> 01:15:01,831
[Undercover or not, he's in fresh pasta hell]

1721
01:15:01,831 --> 01:15:03,239
Is the cheese tortelli ready?

1722
01:15:03,239 --> 01:15:05,319
Or do I need to make it?

1723
01:15:05,319 --> 01:15:07,351
He might have finished it all.

1724
01:15:07,351 --> 01:15:11,031
I'm sure about the cheese tortelli.
I saw him making it.

1725
01:15:11,031 --> 01:15:13,623
[Senior Sorem comes to check
on the junior, Hee Tae]

1726
01:15:14,551 --> 01:15:16,247
[Glance]
Next time...

1727
01:15:16,247 --> 01:15:19,527
- Sprinkle more flour on the table.
- Yes, sir.

1728
01:15:19,527 --> 01:15:21,642
[Critiqued on the flour while so busy]
Yes.

1729
01:15:28,759 --> 01:15:32,164
[The biggest drawback of meticulous Hee Tae]

1730
01:15:32,164 --> 01:15:33,639
[Sorem's speed vs. Hee Tae's speed]

1731
01:15:33,639 --> 01:15:35,031
[Fast!]

1732
01:15:35,031 --> 01:15:36,711
[Significantly slower]
Speed...

1733
01:15:36,711 --> 01:15:38,439
He makes them pretty, but...

1734
01:15:38,439 --> 01:15:40,887
Ah, the speed is a bit...

1735
01:15:40,887 --> 01:15:43,767
Oh, there must be a huge backlog of orders.

1736
01:15:43,767 --> 01:15:46,023
[What to do?]
- It's too slow. - Yes.

1737
01:15:46,023 --> 01:15:49,525
[Distressing even now]
Almost ten pasta orders came in just now.

1738
01:15:49,525 --> 01:15:52,103
[Rushing]
Fried bread and two cheese tortelli.

1739
01:15:52,103 --> 01:15:54,876
[All Hee Tae's work]
I need one duck tagliatelle.

1740
01:15:55,703 --> 01:15:59,125
[Hee Tae is still making cheese tortelli]
It's a real emergency.

1741
01:15:59,125 --> 01:16:01,735
I was getting nervous.

1742
01:16:02,647 --> 01:16:05,575
There's no time. It has to go out fast.

1743
01:16:06,434 --> 01:16:07,541
[Checking]

1744
01:16:07,541 --> 01:16:08,711
- Everyone's waiting.
- Right.

1745
01:16:08,711 --> 01:16:10,327
They're waiting for me...

1746
01:16:10,327 --> 01:16:12,119
This is really...

1747
01:16:12,119 --> 01:16:14,465
Because of me...

1748
01:16:14,465 --> 01:16:16,679
Pasta should go out first,
but it's not coming out.

1749
01:16:16,679 --> 01:16:17,975
Right.

1750
01:16:17,975 --> 01:16:20,405
- Try to reduce waste if possible.
- Yes.

1751
01:16:20,405 --> 01:16:21,479
Reduce the gaps.

1752
01:16:21,479 --> 01:16:23,703
He keeps critiquing me.

1753
01:16:23,703 --> 01:16:26,775
- Right.
- It needs to go out fast.

1754
01:16:26,775 --> 01:16:30,823
[Critique #2, wide gaps wasting dough]

1755
01:16:30,823 --> 01:16:32,663
He's wasting a lot.

1756
01:16:32,663 --> 01:16:34,119
With those gaps in between...

1757
01:16:34,119 --> 01:16:36,615
Is he going to fry those and sell them?

1758
01:16:36,615 --> 01:16:38,135
Do they sell those separately?

1759
01:16:38,135 --> 01:16:39,479
By frying the bits in between?

1760
01:16:39,479 --> 01:16:42,850
[The Waste King of Parma]
At that rate, the dough...

1761
01:16:42,850 --> 01:16:44,475
would be enough for one serving.

1762
01:16:44,475 --> 01:16:46,595
[Focus and let's do this fast!]

1763
01:16:46,595 --> 01:16:49,639
[Cut them to finish two cheese tortelli]
- All that dough left over. - Right.

1764
01:16:49,639 --> 01:16:52,441
Looks like there's enough for one serving.

1765
01:16:53,751 --> 01:16:57,239
[Cuts one and organizes]

1766
01:16:57,239 --> 01:16:59,398
[Critique #3, you can cut them all first]
First...

1767
01:16:59,398 --> 01:17:01,351
- You can cut them all before moving.
- Yes.

1768
01:17:01,351 --> 01:17:04,195
You're wasting time.

1769
01:17:06,071 --> 01:17:08,695
[Immediate correction]

1770
01:17:08,695 --> 01:17:10,935
[Critique #4, this shape is bad]
Not this.

1771
01:17:10,935 --> 01:17:13,415
- These two as well!
- They look fine though.

1772
01:17:13,415 --> 01:17:14,519
Not this.

1773
01:17:14,519 --> 01:17:17,943
Even in this rush, he's rejecting
the ones that aren't pretty.

1774
01:17:17,943 --> 01:17:19,590
Ah, Sorem is really...

1775
01:17:19,590 --> 01:17:21,079
He's very by-the-book.

1776
01:17:21,079 --> 01:17:23,447
He's a bit of a stickler.

1777
01:17:23,447 --> 01:17:26,551
[Constant critiques on every detail]
He gets flustered when rushed.

1778
01:17:26,551 --> 01:17:29,047
There's that too.

1779
01:17:29,047 --> 01:17:32,375
But since he kept telling me
to do this and that,

1780
01:17:32,375 --> 01:17:35,603
it felt like the results were getting worse.

1781
01:17:37,701 --> 01:17:39,697
I wasn't happy with the shapes either.

1782
01:17:39,697 --> 01:17:42,055
I was more concerned
because I couldn't afford to mess up.

1783
01:17:42,055 --> 01:17:43,831
It's not easy.

1784
01:17:43,831 --> 01:17:44,855
[Is it almost done?]

1785
01:17:44,855 --> 01:17:47,290
- That must be a lot of pressure.
- Yeah.

1786
01:17:48,439 --> 01:17:50,471
[The main chef steps in!]
Look.

1787
01:17:50,471 --> 01:17:52,839
The head chef is doing it himself.

1788
01:17:52,839 --> 01:17:54,135
[Is there another problem?]
What's up?

1789
01:17:54,135 --> 01:17:56,755
That must be really stressful.

1790
01:17:56,755 --> 01:17:58,199
When you cut it,

1791
01:17:58,199 --> 01:18:00,311
- use your other hand.
- Yes.

1792
01:18:00,311 --> 01:18:01,588
[Quick and clean]

1793
01:18:01,588 --> 01:18:03,478
[Main chef shows a cleaner, faster method]
Yes.

1794
01:18:03,478 --> 01:18:04,711
- Like this.
- Yes.

1795
01:18:04,711 --> 01:18:06,999
- And you keep it clean.
- Yes.

1796
01:18:06,999 --> 01:18:10,119
[Intimidated]
Then this.

1797
01:18:10,119 --> 01:18:13,943
[The main chef wants him to hurry up]
Thank you.

1798
01:18:13,943 --> 01:18:17,383
[After the 5th critique from the main chef]

1799
01:18:17,383 --> 01:18:21,111
[Cheese tortelli 4 (in progress),
duck tagliatelle 2, torta bread 1]

1800
01:18:21,111 --> 01:18:25,483
[Orders are still piling up like a mountain]

1801
01:18:26,407 --> 01:18:28,375
[Critique #6]
Be careful. This one isn't closed.

1802
01:18:28,375 --> 01:18:30,935
Oh, right. It'll burst if it's like that.

1803
01:18:30,935 --> 01:18:32,983
- This isn't closed.
- Yes.

1804
01:18:32,983 --> 01:18:36,215
- Yes. I'll double-check them.
- Okay.

1805
01:18:36,215 --> 01:18:37,863
You must be having a mental breakdown.

1806
01:18:37,863 --> 01:18:39,623
Time is flying, but the orders...

1807
01:18:39,623 --> 01:18:41,191
Those need to go out.

1808
01:18:41,191 --> 01:18:43,367
He must be so anxious.

1809
01:18:43,367 --> 01:18:46,311
[Stressful to watch]
- I'm nervous just watching. - I know.

1810
01:18:48,135 --> 01:18:50,495
[Hee Tae's orders:
Two cheese tortelli, two cheese tortelli]

1811
01:18:50,495 --> 01:18:53,913
[Two duck tagliatelle, one torta bread]

1812
01:18:53,913 --> 01:18:55,815
[Critiques]
[1. Sprinkle flour 2. Wasting dough]

1813
01:18:55,815 --> 01:18:57,879
[3. Wasting time 4. Shape of the pasta]

1814
01:18:57,879 --> 01:19:00,967
[5. Speed 6. Completeness]

1815
01:19:00,967 --> 01:19:03,175
[Meanwhile]

1816
01:19:04,743 --> 01:19:08,551
[Other main dishes are being made]
- I'm curious about this. - So many orders.

1817
01:19:08,551 --> 01:19:11,209
[Serving to the tables]
Table four.

1818
01:19:12,263 --> 01:19:14,279
[Boil the cheese tortelli]
Cheese tortelli.

1819
01:19:14,279 --> 01:19:16,807
Right now the guests...

1820
01:19:16,807 --> 01:19:19,543
- They have no idea this is happening.
- They don't care.

1821
01:19:19,543 --> 01:19:21,671
[Hee Tae's orders: two cheese tortelli]

1822
01:19:21,671 --> 01:19:24,775
- Time must have flown by.
- It certainly did.

1823
01:19:24,775 --> 01:19:27,510
- Send down the cheese tortelli.
- Yes.

1824
01:19:28,743 --> 01:19:31,095
[Making them one by one]

1825
01:19:31,095 --> 01:19:33,847
[Busy boiling them]

1826
01:19:35,582 --> 01:19:37,981
[Hee Tae is busy making the next pasta]

1827
01:19:37,981 --> 01:19:41,079
He's struggling to keep up.

1828
01:19:41,079 --> 01:19:43,495
Next order is salami, torta bread,

1829
01:19:43,495 --> 01:19:45,207
[Orders keep coming in]
compote, gorgonzola,

1830
01:19:45,207 --> 01:19:49,847
[Duck tagliatelle added]
then tagliatelle and gnocchi.

1831
01:19:49,847 --> 01:19:52,103
[Hee Tae's orders: three duck tagliatelle]

1832
01:19:52,103 --> 01:19:53,767
It was so hectic.

1833
01:19:53,767 --> 01:19:56,453
- There were just too many orders.
- Right.

1834
01:19:58,471 --> 01:20:01,799
Two more torta bread for Table 7.

1835
01:20:01,799 --> 01:20:02,935
Yes!

1836
01:20:02,935 --> 01:20:06,359
[Hee Tae's orders: three torta bread]
- More fried bread, please. - Yes!

1837
01:20:06,359 --> 01:20:08,679
[An energetic response]
Yes!

1838
01:20:08,679 --> 01:20:12,839
[To Hee Tae, 'Torta Bread' is]

1839
01:20:13,719 --> 01:20:16,455
[Yesterday, 1st day of undercover work]

1840
01:20:16,455 --> 01:20:18,147
[Hee Tae learned how to make torta bread]

1841
01:20:18,147 --> 01:20:20,225
- Hee Tae.
- Yes!

1842
01:20:20,225 --> 01:20:23,205
- Perfect.
- Bravo.

1843
01:20:23,205 --> 01:20:25,175
- Perfect.
- Bravo.

1844
01:20:25,175 --> 01:20:26,245
Bravo.

1845
01:20:26,245 --> 01:20:29,849
[Torta Bread he was praised for on day one]
- You got a lot of praise for it. - Thank you.

1846
01:20:30,460 --> 01:20:33,185
[But there's much less time than yesterday]
This is a piece of cake.

1847
01:20:33,185 --> 01:20:34,965
I've done it so many times.

1848
01:20:34,965 --> 01:20:36,467
[Confidently rolling out the dough]

1849
01:20:36,467 --> 01:20:39,737
[Hee Tae is still making cheese tortelli]
This should be a piece of cake by now.

1850
01:20:39,737 --> 01:20:43,505
[He just needs to cut it into squares]

1851
01:20:45,285 --> 01:20:46,565
[Wait!]

1852
01:20:46,565 --> 01:20:47,715
[What happened?]
What?

1853
01:20:47,715 --> 01:20:49,925
- Why?
- Are you okay?

1854
01:20:50,785 --> 01:20:53,075
[Why did he stop cutting?]

1855
01:20:53,075 --> 01:20:54,305
I'm okay.

1856
01:20:54,305 --> 01:20:56,465
[Actually, this is the right size]
- Right. - Long.

1857
01:20:56,465 --> 01:20:58,545
- It's short.
- If it's like this, wait.

1858
01:20:58,545 --> 01:20:59,825
[He cut the intervals too wide]

1859
01:20:59,825 --> 01:21:02,127
- It's too wide.
- You need to cut it into three.

1860
01:21:02,127 --> 01:21:04,777
- That's the right portion size.
- To get the right number of pieces.

1861
01:21:04,777 --> 01:21:06,862
- If you cut it in half like that...
- Right, right.

1862
01:21:06,862 --> 01:21:09,135
- I had to trim both sides again.
- You'll waste more on both sides.

1863
01:21:09,135 --> 01:21:10,695
[More waste!]
Oh, you're wasting a lot.

1864
01:21:10,695 --> 01:21:12,515
He's very nervous.

1865
01:21:12,515 --> 01:21:16,145
- No, that's...
- He says he's a farmer, but he wastes wheat.

1866
01:21:16,145 --> 01:21:19,935
I have to handle
7 to 8 different menu items alone.

1867
01:21:19,935 --> 01:21:21,330
And they're all different.

1868
01:21:21,330 --> 01:21:23,859
[The poor farmer was cornered]
You really have to memorize them well.

1869
01:21:23,859 --> 01:21:25,555
True, but this is...

1870
01:21:25,555 --> 01:21:26,965
It's quite confusing.

1871
01:21:26,965 --> 01:21:28,392
[Oops]

1872
01:21:29,215 --> 01:21:31,055
- Are you okay?
- I'm okay.

1873
01:21:31,055 --> 01:21:32,805
- What should you do?
- I have to fold it again.

1874
01:21:32,805 --> 01:21:35,375
You have to redo it.

1875
01:21:35,375 --> 01:21:38,435
[Sorem steps in to fix it]
Oh, but he's improvising right away.

1876
01:21:38,435 --> 01:21:40,455
He's fixing it immediately.

1877
01:21:40,455 --> 01:21:41,795
Do you throw away the scraps?

1878
01:21:41,795 --> 01:21:43,095
No, we knead them back together.

1879
01:21:43,095 --> 01:21:45,208
You can reuse them.

1880
01:21:48,515 --> 01:21:50,465
Thank you.

1881
01:21:52,115 --> 01:21:56,065
[He even messes up the bread
he was praised for]

1882
01:21:56,065 --> 01:21:58,876
[Trying to cut the rest of the dough quickly]

1883
01:22:02,175 --> 01:22:04,735
This one is a bit small, so be careful.

1884
01:22:04,735 --> 01:22:07,375
This one is a bit small, so be careful.

1885
01:22:07,375 --> 01:22:10,259
[A hell of constant criticism]
Be careful.

1886
01:22:10,259 --> 01:22:12,511
[A clear difference in size]
Right.

1887
01:22:12,511 --> 01:22:15,843
Don't make them smaller than this.

1888
01:22:15,843 --> 01:22:17,136
- Okay?
- Yes.

1889
01:22:17,136 --> 01:22:22,335
[Another and another criticism!]

1890
01:22:22,335 --> 01:22:24,385
In a way, it makes me think,

1891
01:22:24,385 --> 01:22:27,095
"Is there something wrong with me?"

1892
01:22:27,095 --> 01:22:28,575
[Failing the seniors' expectations]

1893
01:22:28,575 --> 01:22:30,590
[Dejected]

1894
01:22:30,590 --> 01:22:32,625
I think you should measure
it against your finger.

1895
01:22:32,625 --> 01:22:34,644
If it's somewhat similar, they let it pass.

1896
01:22:34,644 --> 01:22:36,245
- If there's a big difference...
- Right.

1897
01:22:36,245 --> 01:22:38,545
All those guys say they're so good,

1898
01:22:38,545 --> 01:22:40,545
but when I saw them when it was busy,

1899
01:22:40,545 --> 01:22:42,217
there wasn't much of a difference.

1900
01:22:42,217 --> 01:22:44,225
- What?
- You have a lot of pent-up feelings.

1901
01:22:44,225 --> 01:22:46,275
- Suddenly, about the other chefs...
- He's bitter.

1902
01:22:46,275 --> 01:22:48,865
- Why are you dissing them?
- Why do you have so much resentment?

1903
01:22:48,865 --> 01:22:50,066
- They're doing fine.
- Honestly...

1904
01:22:50,066 --> 01:22:52,135
Why bring up the other chefs
who are doing well?

1905
01:22:52,135 --> 01:22:53,525
I thought they'd be exceptional.

1906
01:22:53,525 --> 01:22:55,557
But they're not much different from mine.

1907
01:22:55,557 --> 01:22:56,915
I didn't know you were so bitter.

1908
01:22:56,915 --> 01:23:00,135
[The "Kitchen Saint" suddenly vents his sorrow]
Oh, Hee Tae...

1909
01:23:00,135 --> 01:23:03,185
[Dejectedly picking up the right-sized dough]
He's so discouraged.

1910
01:23:03,825 --> 01:23:08,994
[Only the right-sized bread dough
is being fried]

1911
01:23:13,475 --> 01:23:17,135
[No. 2 Simone checks the fried bread]

1912
01:23:17,135 --> 01:23:19,655
Later, you two...

1913
01:23:19,655 --> 01:23:21,125
Yes?

1914
01:23:21,985 --> 01:23:24,495
What's going on?

1915
01:23:24,495 --> 01:23:26,705
[What is it?]
Is something wrong?

1916
01:23:28,245 --> 01:23:32,885
Ask Hee Tae to show you
how to make the torta bread.

1917
01:23:32,885 --> 01:23:34,485
- A compliment!
- Wait a minute.

1918
01:23:34,485 --> 01:23:36,855
- Okay.
- Tell them to ask you?

1919
01:23:36,855 --> 01:23:38,465
[Okay]

1920
01:23:38,465 --> 01:23:39,925
Huh?

1921
01:23:39,925 --> 01:23:41,455
- High praise.
- Wait a minute.

1922
01:23:41,455 --> 01:23:43,475
- High praise.
- Tell them to ask you?

1923
01:23:43,475 --> 01:23:45,205
Wait, the chef just...

1924
01:23:45,205 --> 01:23:47,585
He was just complaining, but then Simone...

1925
01:23:47,585 --> 01:23:49,795
- They're saying nice things.
- Seriously.

1926
01:23:49,795 --> 01:23:52,295
- That's too much.
- Such a good friend.

1927
01:23:52,295 --> 01:23:54,755
- Those guys...
- To such good friends...

1928
01:23:54,755 --> 01:23:57,940
In that situation, I hated everyone.

1929
01:23:59,535 --> 01:24:00,855
He's giving so much praise.

1930
01:24:00,855 --> 01:24:04,945
He's full of compliments.

1931
01:24:04,945 --> 01:24:07,345
Oh, it's pretty.

1932
01:24:07,345 --> 01:24:10,093
[Hee Tae's torta bread praised again]
That compliment is kind of funny.

1933
01:24:10,093 --> 01:24:12,705
It's a backhanded compliment.

1934
01:24:12,705 --> 01:24:15,185
[But he's too busy working to hear it]

1935
01:24:15,185 --> 01:24:18,507
If you'd heard that, you'd be less upset.

1936
01:24:18,507 --> 01:24:22,176
- I'm sure I would've if I'd heard it.
- Exactly. But you couldn't hear it.

1937
01:24:22,176 --> 01:24:23,434
- For now...
- Not at all.

1938
01:24:23,434 --> 01:24:27,665
Since I didn't understand 90% of the talk...

1939
01:24:27,665 --> 01:24:29,125
I was just...

1940
01:24:29,125 --> 01:24:33,555
[I was just a pasta machine]
I just did my best at the task given to me.

1941
01:24:33,555 --> 01:24:34,815
Hee Tae.

1942
01:24:34,815 --> 01:24:36,160
Yes.

1943
01:24:37,191 --> 01:24:38,815
[Checking the pasta Hee Tae made again]

1944
01:24:38,815 --> 01:24:41,825
Checking it one more time.

1945
01:24:41,825 --> 01:24:44,575
[Worry]

1946
01:24:45,955 --> 01:24:48,495
Good! It's even better now!

1947
01:24:48,495 --> 01:24:51,125
[Another compliment!]
He said it's even better.

1948
01:24:51,125 --> 01:24:54,145
- Wow, you didn't understand any of this?
- I had no idea.

1949
01:24:54,145 --> 01:24:56,565
You must have had no idea what he was saying.

1950
01:24:56,565 --> 01:24:58,995
The shape is pretty.

1951
01:25:00,565 --> 01:25:02,805
[Another missed compliment]

1952
01:25:02,805 --> 01:25:05,054
It's a compliment, though.

1953
01:25:05,715 --> 01:25:08,455
[Cutting]

1954
01:25:08,455 --> 01:25:12,015
[Squeezing]

1955
01:25:12,015 --> 01:25:14,845
[Pressing]

1956
01:25:14,845 --> 01:25:17,535
[Hee Tae is in his own pasta hell]
- Orders are piling up. - I know.

1957
01:25:17,535 --> 01:25:19,935
Counting the numbers in my head.

1958
01:25:19,935 --> 01:25:21,575
[Grabbing a tray in a hurry]

1959
01:25:21,575 --> 01:25:24,755
- This happens in just two days.
- Whoa, you scared me.

1960
01:25:24,755 --> 01:25:26,565
[Completely logged out]
You look so frazzled.

1961
01:25:26,565 --> 01:25:27,905
I'm totally out of it.

1962
01:25:27,905 --> 01:25:29,575
You're just so focused on the work.

1963
01:25:29,575 --> 01:25:33,587
If your life is feeling a bit weary
or difficult,

1964
01:25:33,587 --> 01:25:37,825
I think going to Parma and working here
would be a good idea.

1965
01:25:37,825 --> 01:25:41,492
[Manual labor clears your mind]
Your mind will be completely cleared.

1966
01:25:42,385 --> 01:25:47,112
[All the piled-up lunch orders are finished]

1967
01:25:49,475 --> 01:25:54,055
[Hee Tae's pasta, made with blood, sweat,
and tears, is finally served]

1968
01:25:54,055 --> 01:25:56,565
[Yum]

1969
01:25:56,565 --> 01:25:58,785
[Eyebrow twitch?]

1970
01:25:58,785 --> 01:26:02,060
It's a divine touch.

1971
01:26:03,200 --> 01:26:06,195
- A divine touch.
- Hands of a god.

1972
01:26:07,985 --> 01:26:11,205
[It's delicious]

1973
01:26:12,165 --> 01:26:15,852
[Fried torta bread]
It's very plump.

1974
01:26:21,105 --> 01:26:22,697
If even the elderly can eat it well,

1975
01:26:22,697 --> 01:26:25,935
[Nod, nod]
it means it's soft and delicious.

1976
01:26:25,935 --> 01:26:28,710
[It's a fantastic dish]

1977
01:26:30,995 --> 01:26:32,896
It looks delicious.

1978
01:26:34,625 --> 01:26:37,765
[Proven by the empty plates]

1979
01:26:37,765 --> 01:26:40,558
They really licked the plates clean.

1980
01:26:41,650 --> 01:26:43,593
Gulping down some sparkling water.

1981
01:26:43,593 --> 01:26:46,978
[Hee Tae finally quenches his thirst]

1982
01:26:49,905 --> 01:26:53,075
[Good job, everyone]

1983
01:26:53,075 --> 01:26:55,747
[Suddenly making a Korean-style finger heart]

1984
01:26:55,747 --> 01:26:58,630
He learned something else.

1985
01:27:00,043 --> 01:27:01,695
Did you teach him that?

1986
01:27:01,695 --> 01:27:03,028
No, I didn't even teach him.

1987
01:27:03,028 --> 01:27:04,735
- They just know it.
- Is this Korean-made?

1988
01:27:04,735 --> 01:27:06,965
[How did he know?]
Yes.

1989
01:27:06,965 --> 01:27:11,175
[Studying Korean expressions after "Idiot"]
- They all study a lot. - It's a heart.

1990
01:27:11,175 --> 01:27:14,935
[Taking a breather in a friendly atmosphere
with finger hearts]

1991
01:27:14,935 --> 01:27:18,115
[Will lunch end without any more hell?]

1992
01:27:19,145 --> 01:27:21,595
[Sunny, not Jung Ji Sun, in Chengdu, China]
In Chengdu, China,

1993
01:27:21,595 --> 01:27:23,035
what kind of changes

1994
01:27:23,035 --> 01:27:27,055
[Day 2 as a kitchen junior]
will Chef Jung Ji Sun show us?

1995
01:27:27,885 --> 01:27:32,175
[Current time 1:30 PM]

1996
01:27:33,195 --> 01:27:35,843
[As lunch service]

1997
01:27:35,843 --> 01:27:38,703
[is coming to an end]

1998
01:27:40,045 --> 01:27:42,695
[The rush of orders is finally over]

1999
01:27:42,695 --> 01:27:45,255
[Sneaking around]

2000
01:27:46,213 --> 01:27:51,194
- Walking with your hands behind your back?
- I know. I didn't have time to walk like that.

2001
01:27:51,895 --> 01:27:52,975
Hey, you two.

2002
01:27:52,975 --> 01:27:54,695
As soon as the other person appears,

2003
01:27:54,695 --> 01:27:58,994
they're busy criticizing each other.

2004
01:28:00,425 --> 01:28:02,599
[Turn]

2005
01:28:03,335 --> 01:28:06,665
Is it break time now?

2006
01:28:06,665 --> 01:28:10,825
No, we have to eat.

2007
01:28:10,825 --> 01:28:15,383
[It's time for the staff meal]

2008
01:28:16,555 --> 01:28:19,210
[Sunny suddenly looks for someone]

2009
01:28:21,835 --> 01:28:24,665
[Does she have something to say
to the head of the wok station?]

2010
01:28:24,665 --> 01:28:27,415
Can I practice my wok skills later?

2011
01:28:27,415 --> 01:28:29,675
- Of course.
- Oh, wok practice.

2012
01:28:29,675 --> 01:28:32,495
[The reason Sunny wants to grab a wok...]
- Eat first. - Okay.

2013
01:28:32,495 --> 01:28:35,995
[Sunny tried the wok on her first day
as an undercover commis chef]

2014
01:28:35,995 --> 01:28:37,645
[But wait?]

2015
01:28:37,645 --> 01:28:43,065
[The local wok that stumped
the 24-year Chinese food veteran]

2016
01:28:43,065 --> 01:28:45,645
It's not that I'm bad at it.

2017
01:28:45,645 --> 01:28:48,170
The wok just wouldn't move at all.

2018
01:28:49,369 --> 01:28:52,206
It's too big.
I can't even lift it with one hand.

2019
01:28:52,206 --> 01:28:55,575
[Biggest worry is wok-handling]

2020
01:28:55,575 --> 01:29:00,525
[She must master the wok
to move to the next level]

2021
01:29:00,525 --> 01:29:02,505
- After we eat.
- After we eat?

2022
01:29:02,505 --> 01:29:05,515
- Ask the chef at the wok station to teach you!
- The one with the glasses?

2023
01:29:05,515 --> 01:29:07,095
Yes, that's right.

2024
01:29:07,095 --> 01:29:08,495
The one with the glasses.

2025
01:29:08,495 --> 01:29:09,835
Eat first.

2026
01:29:09,835 --> 01:29:12,395
He's on duty, so...

2027
01:29:12,395 --> 01:29:14,765
you can get some salt and practice together.

2028
01:29:14,765 --> 01:29:16,461
Okay.

2029
01:29:16,461 --> 01:29:18,555
[Sunny achieves her goal of practicing]
He's so kind.

2030
01:29:18,555 --> 01:29:19,625
This is great.

2031
01:29:19,625 --> 01:29:21,375
I know.

2032
01:29:21,375 --> 01:29:23,455
You don't seem stressed at all.

2033
01:29:23,455 --> 01:29:25,835
[Worrying]

2034
01:29:25,835 --> 01:29:27,885
You don't look stressed, but were you?

2035
01:29:27,885 --> 01:29:30,105
- I was very stressed.
- You were?

2036
01:29:30,105 --> 01:29:33,545
[He can forget stress in just one second]
Get stressed, then forget it. Repeat.

2037
01:29:33,545 --> 01:29:35,935
[The staff begins their lunch]

2038
01:29:35,935 --> 01:29:38,149
They all gather to eat.

2039
01:29:38,149 --> 01:29:40,015
[What's for lunch today?]
That looks delicious.

2040
01:29:40,015 --> 01:29:42,495
Everything looks so good.

2041
01:29:42,495 --> 01:29:44,365
This is braised winter melon.

2042
01:29:44,365 --> 01:29:46,255
- Winter melon?
- Winter melon?

2043
01:29:46,679 --> 01:29:55,172
[This large vegetable is the winter melon]
It's like a mix of pumpkin and radish.

2044
01:29:55,648 --> 01:30:00,178
[A common ingredient in Chinese home cooking]

2045
01:30:00,178 --> 01:30:05,758
[In Chengdu, it's often braised or in soup]

2046
01:30:05,758 --> 01:30:10,118
[Braised in its own juices]

2047
01:30:11,838 --> 01:30:15,108
[Braised Winter Melon]
Oh, that looks tasty.

2048
01:30:15,108 --> 01:30:18,068
[Pork with Houttuynia Cordata]

2049
01:30:18,068 --> 01:30:20,128
That looks delicious just by looking at it.

2050
01:30:20,128 --> 01:30:21,878
[Egg Soup]

2051
01:30:21,878 --> 01:30:23,823
Looks so good.

2052
01:30:25,561 --> 01:30:29,038
[Everyone is eating comfortably]

2053
01:30:29,038 --> 01:30:30,610
[Peeking]

2054
01:30:31,958 --> 01:30:34,178
Why?

2055
01:30:34,178 --> 01:30:37,028
[Huh?]
She's looking for something.

2056
01:30:38,718 --> 01:30:41,668
[She finds the Senior Chef
with glasses who has finished his meal]

2057
01:30:42,352 --> 01:30:43,668
[Sunny follows him immediately]

2058
01:30:43,668 --> 01:30:45,698
- I'm done eating.
- Why? Why?

2059
01:30:45,698 --> 01:30:48,418
[Practicing with the Senior Chef]
To practice?

2060
01:30:48,418 --> 01:30:50,658
You have to get up as soon as the seniors do.

2061
01:30:50,658 --> 01:30:53,906
That way, you can go over and try it out.

2062
01:30:53,906 --> 01:30:57,698
[The Senior Chef with glasses remains on duty
at the Wok station]

2063
01:30:57,698 --> 01:30:59,298
[Peeking]

2064
01:30:59,298 --> 01:31:01,074
Okay.

2065
01:31:02,228 --> 01:31:06,258
[Heading straight for today's wok teacher]

2066
01:31:06,258 --> 01:31:08,358
[Appearing suddenly]

2067
01:31:08,358 --> 01:31:10,108
Hello.

2068
01:31:11,218 --> 01:31:12,948
Hello.

2069
01:31:13,668 --> 01:31:17,538
Please help me practice.

2070
01:31:17,538 --> 01:31:20,548
- You mean using this wok?
- Yes, yes.

2071
01:31:21,298 --> 01:31:24,801
[Who is Sunny's wok teacher today?]
I tried it yesterday, but it was so heavy.

2072
01:31:26,489 --> 01:31:32,379
[The chef who guards
the end of the Wok station]

2073
01:31:33,142 --> 01:31:35,938
[From steady-selling stir-fried vegetables]

2074
01:31:35,938 --> 01:31:38,687
[To dishes with rich, thick broths]

2075
01:31:38,687 --> 01:31:40,313
That looks delicious.

2076
01:31:40,313 --> 01:31:43,148
[The chef in charge of all banquet dishes]

2077
01:31:43,148 --> 01:31:45,798
[Wok station No.6 Guo Li Hong]
He's the junior at the Wok station.

2078
01:31:45,798 --> 01:31:48,258
- Oh, the junior?
- Yes, the Wok station junior.

2079
01:31:48,258 --> 01:31:52,238
[The No.6 Senior Chef
is Sunny's wok teacher today]

2080
01:31:52,238 --> 01:31:55,168
[And]

2081
01:31:55,168 --> 01:31:57,498
[At the new move of the junior, Sunny]

2082
01:31:57,498 --> 01:32:00,158
- They keep watching.
- They come to watch.

2083
01:32:00,158 --> 01:32:02,388
Are you working through your lunch break?

2084
01:32:02,388 --> 01:32:04,336
I need to practice.

2085
01:32:04,336 --> 01:32:06,118
- She's so passionate.
- She's practicing.

2086
01:32:06,118 --> 01:32:09,320
[Senior Liu amazed by Sunny's break practice]
Opportunities like this are precious.

2087
01:32:10,688 --> 01:32:14,658
[Today, practicing with peppers instead of salt]

2088
01:32:14,658 --> 01:32:17,108
Put the ladle down first.

2089
01:32:17,108 --> 01:32:19,886
Spread it out like this.

2090
01:32:19,886 --> 01:32:21,662
Fold it in half.

2091
01:32:21,662 --> 01:32:23,487
He taught me everything
from the very beginning.

2092
01:32:23,487 --> 01:32:25,238
- Make it a bit longer.
- He's so kind.

2093
01:32:25,238 --> 01:32:26,338
Flip it over.

2094
01:32:26,338 --> 01:32:28,118
- Like this.
- That's right.

2095
01:32:28,118 --> 01:32:31,138
Do it like this, then grab it.

2096
01:32:31,138 --> 01:32:32,868
Hold it here.

2097
01:32:32,868 --> 01:32:34,738
- Hold it like this.
- Hold it...

2098
01:32:34,738 --> 01:32:37,488
Hold it...

2099
01:32:37,488 --> 01:32:40,788
Sunny, pull with your left hand.

2100
01:32:40,788 --> 01:32:42,898
And push with the ladle.

2101
01:32:42,898 --> 01:32:46,628
[Heave-ho, heave-ho]

2102
01:32:46,628 --> 01:32:50,738
[Hearing this rattling sound]
Wow, this is really hard.

2103
01:32:50,738 --> 01:32:55,185
[Flashback to yesterday's first attempt]

2104
01:32:55,185 --> 01:32:59,198
[The salt didn't even budge]

2105
01:32:59,198 --> 01:33:01,408
This won't do.

2106
01:33:01,408 --> 01:33:04,768
[Humiliation for the 24-year veteran]
It's too hard.

2107
01:33:04,768 --> 01:33:06,351
[Starting with the same rattling as yesterday]

2108
01:33:06,351 --> 01:33:07,975
But if you can't handle the wok,

2109
01:33:07,975 --> 01:33:09,882
you won't even get a chance at the main stove.

2110
01:33:09,882 --> 01:33:12,438
You can't do anything
if you can't even do this.

2111
01:33:12,438 --> 01:33:16,022
Like this.

2112
01:33:16,022 --> 01:33:20,498
[Senior helps Sunny find the rhythm]
Basically, you need a sense of rhythm.

2113
01:33:20,498 --> 01:33:22,258
[Sunny follows the rhythm of the wok]

2114
01:33:22,258 --> 01:33:23,398
[Heave-ho]
Like this.

2115
01:33:23,398 --> 01:33:25,132
Yes.

2116
01:33:26,358 --> 01:33:28,118
- Did I do it?
- Yes, that's it.

2117
01:33:28,118 --> 01:33:29,798
[Good job, Sunny!]
That's the feeling.

2118
01:33:29,798 --> 01:33:32,478
That's the feeling. Okay, okay.

2119
01:33:32,478 --> 01:33:35,846
[The chilies start to flip in the wok]

2120
01:33:35,846 --> 01:33:38,918
It feels completely different from yesterday.

2121
01:33:38,918 --> 01:33:41,328
- Yesterday was salt, so it was heavy.
- Is it different?

2122
01:33:41,328 --> 01:33:44,979
- It's definitely easier with the chilies.
- You're right.

2123
01:33:44,979 --> 01:33:46,195
Right, salt is much heavier.

2124
01:33:46,195 --> 01:33:49,195
- Exactly.
- Salt also sticks if there's any moisture.

2125
01:33:50,768 --> 01:33:56,310
[Wok work is easier with light chilies]

2126
01:33:56,310 --> 01:33:58,438
It's much easier.

2127
01:33:58,438 --> 01:34:01,376
It's much lighter, and it flips well.

2128
01:34:01,376 --> 01:34:04,536
He set me up to practice without the heat.

2129
01:34:05,478 --> 01:34:07,478
You found a good teacher.

2130
01:34:07,478 --> 01:34:09,728
He's a good senior.

2131
01:34:09,728 --> 01:34:13,318
[Sunny gains momentum after getting it down]
She's keeping it going now.

2132
01:34:14,148 --> 01:34:15,598
You're a very fast learner.

2133
01:34:15,598 --> 01:34:17,678
- Really?
- Yes.

2134
01:34:17,678 --> 01:34:19,748
[A spoonful of compliments added]

2135
01:34:19,748 --> 01:34:22,141
Push slowly. Slowly.

2136
01:34:22,141 --> 01:34:25,730
Try pushing and pulling! Push and pull!

2137
01:34:26,418 --> 01:34:29,388
Is there no way to hold it like this?

2138
01:34:29,388 --> 01:34:31,058
[Sunny wants to grip it lower]
Ah, I see.

2139
01:34:31,058 --> 01:34:32,338
This is more comfortable for me.

2140
01:34:32,338 --> 01:34:34,148
That's more comfortable for you?

2141
01:34:34,148 --> 01:34:35,652
But usually, we hold it like this.

2142
01:34:35,652 --> 01:34:38,098
It's easier to lift the wok this way.

2143
01:34:38,098 --> 01:34:41,583
If you hold it your way, it's hard to lift.

2144
01:34:41,583 --> 01:34:44,468
- Lifting it with one hand is really hard.
- Because you have to lift it.

2145
01:34:44,468 --> 01:34:48,118
[The double-handle wok uses different muscles]
You have to lift it with one hand.

2146
01:34:48,798 --> 01:34:50,918
But my wrist hurts.

2147
01:34:50,918 --> 01:34:53,168
It'll hurt for a few years.

2148
01:34:53,168 --> 01:34:54,840
It'll hurt for a few years?

2149
01:34:54,840 --> 01:34:58,475
- Isn't that just hurting forever?
- A few years? This is intense.

2150
01:34:58,475 --> 01:35:01,478
- It's normal.
- It's like Shaolin Temple.

2151
01:35:01,478 --> 01:35:03,939
He says it won't hurt once I'm used to it.

2152
01:35:03,939 --> 01:35:05,398
- The pain is very normal.
- It's normal?

2153
01:35:05,398 --> 01:35:08,718
It'll hurt for a while,
but it'll stop after some time.

2154
01:35:08,718 --> 01:35:11,728
[A 24-year veteran junior gets advice
on calluses from a 6-year senior]

2155
01:35:11,728 --> 01:35:14,786
- I should work out for this.
- Exactly.

2156
01:35:15,588 --> 01:35:17,438
[While Sunny is getting used to the wok]

2157
01:35:17,438 --> 01:35:18,934
[Peek]

2158
01:35:18,934 --> 01:35:20,566
Grandma is here.

2159
01:35:21,268 --> 01:35:25,403
[Grandma approaches Sunny as she practices]
She must be proud to see this.

2160
01:35:28,933 --> 01:35:31,158
Did you tell her to practice?

2161
01:35:31,158 --> 01:35:35,514
She's really good. Sunny, Show her!

2162
01:35:36,333 --> 01:35:37,425
[Yes, sir!]

2163
01:35:37,425 --> 01:35:40,638
[A chance to make up
for yesterday's clunkiness!]

2164
01:35:40,638 --> 01:35:42,418
[Immediate performance]

2165
01:35:42,418 --> 01:35:44,288
Here she goes, here she goes!

2166
01:35:44,288 --> 01:35:46,958
Look at her go.

2167
01:35:46,958 --> 01:35:49,568
She's truly the queen of Chinese cuisine.

2168
01:35:51,138 --> 01:35:53,908
See? She can use the wok now.

2169
01:35:53,908 --> 01:35:56,918
[Nod]

2170
01:35:56,918 --> 01:36:00,308
[Shy and covered in sweat]
Was it okay?

2171
01:36:00,308 --> 01:36:03,488
You're good.

2172
01:36:03,488 --> 01:36:06,038
- The senior chef looks very happy too.
- Yeah.

2173
01:36:06,038 --> 01:36:07,668
Since he's the one who taught her.

2174
01:36:07,668 --> 01:36:11,241
[The student surpasses the master]
Seeing her do exactly as taught...

2175
01:36:11,241 --> 01:36:13,038
- must feel good.
- Like this?

2176
01:36:13,038 --> 01:36:16,142
You're a bit clumsy, but you're doing great.

2177
01:36:17,538 --> 01:36:21,458
[Sunny is pumped after the senior's praise]

2178
01:36:21,458 --> 01:36:25,008
[A key figure approaches Sunny]

2179
01:36:25,008 --> 01:36:27,603
[The male manager appears]
Is he the male manager?

2180
01:36:29,598 --> 01:36:31,378
[Staring intently]

2181
01:36:31,378 --> 01:36:34,228
[He's here!]

2182
01:36:34,228 --> 01:36:35,958
[Glance]

2183
01:36:35,958 --> 01:36:38,078
You're a fast learner.

2184
01:36:38,078 --> 01:36:41,113
She's picking it up so fast. Really fast.

2185
01:36:42,198 --> 01:36:45,875
[Watching the kitchen junior's wok skills]

2186
01:36:45,875 --> 01:36:47,286
Like this?

2187
01:36:47,286 --> 01:36:50,015
[Continuing to practice as before]

2188
01:36:53,188 --> 01:36:54,958
That's it, that's it.

2189
01:36:56,688 --> 01:36:59,998
She's strong because she was a boxer.

2190
01:36:59,998 --> 01:37:03,298
Because she was a boxer.

2191
01:37:03,298 --> 01:37:06,758
[The cover story is perfect]
He says I'm strong.

2192
01:37:06,758 --> 01:37:10,418
[Surprised]

2193
01:37:10,418 --> 01:37:12,688
She's improved a lot.

2194
01:37:12,688 --> 01:37:14,948
She's got the basic form down.

2195
01:37:14,948 --> 01:37:16,838
While handling the wok,

2196
01:37:16,838 --> 01:37:20,118
she can now toss the ingredients.

2197
01:37:20,758 --> 01:37:25,058
[Manager shocked by half-day progress]
This isn't easy.

2198
01:37:25,058 --> 01:37:27,958
[Incredible adaptability of a veteran]

2199
01:37:27,958 --> 01:37:29,348
[Staring]

2200
01:37:29,348 --> 01:37:31,971
Do you want to try stir-frying a dish?

2201
01:37:31,971 --> 01:37:33,918
- What should I stir-fry?
- He wants you to actually stir-fry one?

2202
01:37:33,918 --> 01:37:35,423
- Vegetable. You can do that.
- Okay.

2203
01:37:35,423 --> 01:37:37,638
Already? Hold on.

2204
01:37:37,638 --> 01:37:40,199
I was quite excited then.
Because he suddenly told me to stir-fry.

2205
01:37:40,199 --> 01:37:41,918
You look so cheerful.

2206
01:37:41,918 --> 01:37:44,528
He told me to stir-fry vegetables.

2207
01:37:44,528 --> 01:37:48,646
Oh, wow!

2208
01:37:48,646 --> 01:37:50,150
[Lifting it up]
Isn't it hot?

2209
01:37:50,150 --> 01:37:51,908
It's okay. It's okay.

2210
01:37:51,908 --> 01:37:55,241
[Exciting practice makes her forget the heat]

2211
01:37:55,978 --> 01:37:57,988
Do you want to try it?

2212
01:37:57,988 --> 01:38:00,418
I'll try it after you show me first.

2213
01:38:00,418 --> 01:38:03,938
I'll try it after you show me first.

2214
01:38:03,938 --> 01:38:08,038
[Adding seasonal vegetables]

2215
01:38:08,038 --> 01:38:10,898
[The key is to push the ladle and pull the wok]

2216
01:38:10,898 --> 01:38:12,038
[Give it a try]

2217
01:38:12,038 --> 01:38:14,688
[Quickly stepping up]

2218
01:38:14,688 --> 01:38:16,308
[Tossing the wok]

2219
01:38:16,308 --> 01:38:18,948
- Is this right?
- That's right. That's it.

2220
01:38:18,948 --> 01:38:20,738
[Slow but steady tossing of the vegetables]

2221
01:38:20,738 --> 01:38:22,288
Oh, it's working properly.

2222
01:38:22,288 --> 01:38:24,813
[The senior turns up the heat for Sunny]
Now, faster.

2223
01:38:26,628 --> 01:38:28,481
[Intense heat that makes it hard to open eyes]

2224
01:38:31,008 --> 01:38:33,568
[Intense wok work]
Oh, her skills are showing now.

2225
01:38:33,568 --> 01:38:34,927
Your skills are showing now.

2226
01:38:34,927 --> 01:38:37,508
[Did Ji Sun forget she's undercover?]
Hey, you're undercover...

2227
01:38:37,508 --> 01:38:39,298
I told you to go easy on it.

2228
01:38:39,298 --> 01:38:41,318
They're clapping.

2229
01:38:41,318 --> 01:38:42,883
[Enthusiastic applause]

2230
01:38:43,878 --> 01:38:46,118
It's really, really good.

2231
01:38:46,118 --> 01:38:48,746
[Sunny finding her groove]
He's as happy as if he did it himself.

2232
01:38:48,746 --> 01:38:51,608
- Our senior with glasses is so happy.
- It's really nice to see.

2233
01:38:51,608 --> 01:38:54,297
[The 24-year veteran junior, thanks to our
senior with glasses, found her groove again]

2234
01:38:54,297 --> 01:38:55,999
Now that I know how to hold it.

2235
01:38:55,999 --> 01:38:57,968
It's just like holding it with one hand.

2236
01:38:57,968 --> 01:39:00,076
It's the same.

2237
01:39:03,051 --> 01:39:05,441
She has mastered the salt toss now too.

2238
01:39:05,441 --> 01:39:08,751
Oh, she's working so hard.

2239
01:39:08,751 --> 01:39:12,367
[While the 24-year veteran junior practices]
He's such a helpful senior, Mr. Glasses.

2240
01:39:14,251 --> 01:39:17,070
[Break time ends,
5 minutes to assembly, 4:25 PM]

2241
01:39:18,001 --> 01:39:21,971
[Staff gather for the evening assembly]
Okay, it's time for the assembly.

2242
01:39:21,971 --> 01:39:24,891
[Sunny joins after her wok practice]

2243
01:39:24,891 --> 01:39:28,278
[About 40 employees gather in one place]

2244
01:39:28,278 --> 01:39:29,551
[Evening assembly begins]
Is everyone here?

2245
01:39:29,551 --> 01:39:31,601
- Good afternoon.
- Good afternoon.

2246
01:39:31,601 --> 01:39:33,811
[Starting roll call immediately]
Fu Jie Zhi, Zhang Chi.

2247
01:39:33,811 --> 01:39:36,141
- Wang Ming Zhi, Chen Bo.
- Yes.

2248
01:39:36,141 --> 01:39:39,691
[Names are called one by one]
Zheng Qian Mao. Liu Guan Zheng.

2249
01:39:39,691 --> 01:39:42,451
[Absent this morning, nervous now]
He's not here, right?

2250
01:39:43,491 --> 01:39:44,971
- Liu Fu Yong.
- Yes.

2251
01:39:44,971 --> 01:39:46,701
Sunny.

2252
01:39:46,701 --> 01:39:48,649
- Sunny.
- Yes.

2253
01:39:49,311 --> 01:39:51,521
[Satisfied shrug]

2254
01:39:51,521 --> 01:39:55,908
I hope you can all help each other
while you work,

2255
01:39:55,908 --> 01:39:58,291
and I hope we can communicate a lot.

2256
01:39:58,291 --> 01:40:00,611
[As the announcements wrap up]
Let's all communicate more.

2257
01:40:00,611 --> 01:40:04,961
Sunny! How was the wok practice today?

2258
01:40:04,961 --> 01:40:06,721
[Shy]
- It was good. - Good.

2259
01:40:07,331 --> 01:40:08,781
- It was good.
- Good.

2260
01:40:08,781 --> 01:40:11,501
[The senior's praise boosts the junior's spirits]
Her senior is speaking up for her.

2261
01:40:11,501 --> 01:40:13,201
Wow, her senior is...

2262
01:40:13,201 --> 01:40:14,851
He's saying he's the one who trained her.

2263
01:40:14,851 --> 01:40:17,441
"I'm the one who trained Sunny today."

2264
01:40:17,441 --> 01:40:23,400
If you're not busy tonight,
it'd be good to practice more.

2265
01:40:23,400 --> 01:40:25,771
[Oh]

2266
01:40:25,771 --> 01:40:27,821
So that during tomorrow's service,

2267
01:40:27,821 --> 01:40:30,061
you can handle the stir-fry dishes.

2268
01:40:30,061 --> 01:40:33,043
So that you can handle
the stir-fry dishes tomorrow.

2269
01:40:33,043 --> 01:40:35,891
[As you might move to the Wok station soon]
Already?

2270
01:40:35,891 --> 01:40:37,521
I got goosebumps at that moment.

2271
01:40:37,521 --> 01:40:39,291
- Really?
- Yes.

2272
01:40:39,291 --> 01:40:42,321
[The possibility of moving to the
Wok station has opened up]

2273
01:40:42,321 --> 01:40:44,811
It's the same for everyone else.

2274
01:40:44,811 --> 01:40:46,541
If you want to learn and become a chef,

2275
01:40:46,541 --> 01:40:50,671
you must take the time to practice a lot.

2276
01:40:50,671 --> 01:40:54,864
Don't just settle for your current position.

2277
01:40:54,864 --> 01:40:56,881
[A bold move after seeing her steady practice]
Isn't that a bit too fast?

2278
01:40:56,881 --> 01:40:59,171
- It is.
- Seriously.

2279
01:40:59,171 --> 01:41:00,911
[Ending the assembly with a slogan]

2280
01:41:00,911 --> 01:41:02,431
Be elegant as a person.

2281
01:41:02,431 --> 01:41:03,841
Work properly.

2282
01:41:03,841 --> 01:41:05,131
With the best service,

2283
01:41:05,131 --> 01:41:07,525
we put the customer first!

2284
01:41:08,701 --> 01:41:11,531
[Sunny has mixed feelings
about the unexpected news]

2285
01:41:11,531 --> 01:41:13,545
Wow.

2286
01:41:16,291 --> 01:41:18,701
Wait, he's the senior right above her.

2287
01:41:18,701 --> 01:41:20,301
- He doesn't look happy right now.
- Xu Jian Kai.

2288
01:41:20,301 --> 01:41:22,011
She was originally under him.

2289
01:41:22,011 --> 01:41:24,731
But now she's suddenly moving up
to the Wok station.

2290
01:41:24,731 --> 01:41:27,445
[The MZ senior is gloomy]
He looks like he's about to cry.

2291
01:41:29,121 --> 01:41:33,569
[The Prep station crew takes their places
for the evening service]

2292
01:41:33,569 --> 01:41:35,531
[Sunny and No. 3 Xu Jian Kai return]
What's wrong?

2293
01:41:35,531 --> 01:41:38,115
It seems to have gotten awkward.

2294
01:41:39,491 --> 01:41:41,771
[Glance]

2295
01:41:42,611 --> 01:41:45,371
Oh, Xu Jian Kai must feel uncomfortable now.

2296
01:41:45,371 --> 01:41:47,771
[The Prep station is quiet]
He's right in front of her.

2297
01:41:47,771 --> 01:41:50,401
He must feel a bit uncomfortable now.

2298
01:41:51,955 --> 01:41:53,426
Did you get some rest?

2299
01:41:53,426 --> 01:41:55,953
[Sunny breaks the silence]
Did you get some rest? Did you sleep?

2300
01:41:55,953 --> 01:41:57,645
Yes, I went home and slept.

2301
01:41:57,645 --> 01:42:00,141
[The MZ senior avoids eye contact?]
He won't look at her.

2302
01:42:00,141 --> 01:42:02,931
- You didn't take a nap at lunch?
- No.

2303
01:42:02,931 --> 01:42:05,021
Will you be okay for the evening shift
without a nap?

2304
01:42:05,021 --> 01:42:06,351
Why didn't you sleep?

2305
01:42:06,351 --> 01:42:09,026
- I came back and...
- Why practice with the wok

2306
01:42:09,026 --> 01:42:10,651
instead of sleeping?

2307
01:42:10,651 --> 01:42:13,491
She was practicing with the wok
during the break.

2308
01:42:13,491 --> 01:42:14,701
I saw her.

2309
01:42:14,701 --> 01:42:19,597
I asked her why she didn't go home.

2310
01:42:20,431 --> 01:42:23,091
She said this opportunity is precious.

2311
01:42:23,091 --> 01:42:24,851
- He remembers.
- "This is precious to me."

2312
01:42:24,851 --> 01:42:26,591
Wow, he actually remembers that.

2313
01:42:26,591 --> 01:42:28,771
Se even cheered "Wow" earlier.

2314
01:42:28,771 --> 01:42:31,569
Right, she practiced with the wok
during the break.

2315
01:42:32,351 --> 01:42:36,046
She's actually getting quite good.

2316
01:42:37,371 --> 01:42:41,551
[Everyone acknowledges Sunny's effort
even if they don't say it]

2317
01:42:41,551 --> 01:42:44,001
Should I ask Sunny to slice the sirloin?

2318
01:42:44,001 --> 01:42:45,261
What do you think?

2319
01:42:45,261 --> 01:42:47,260
Sure, you should teach her.

2320
01:42:47,260 --> 01:42:49,121
- Slicing meat?
- We're going to dice the meat.

2321
01:42:49,121 --> 01:42:50,621
- Rou ding?
- Yes.

2322
01:42:50,621 --> 01:42:53,451
Ding means to cut into squares.

2323
01:42:53,451 --> 01:42:54,971
[Ding is Dicing]
- Ding? - Yes.

2324
01:42:54,971 --> 01:42:56,883
Ding is a square.

2325
01:42:56,883 --> 01:42:58,173
Should I dice all of it?

2326
01:42:58,173 --> 01:43:01,224
That's right. Just dice everything.

2327
01:43:04,141 --> 01:43:08,211
[If she can endure this awkwardness]

2328
01:43:08,211 --> 01:43:11,311
[She can soon move to the Wok station]

2329
01:43:12,161 --> 01:43:15,231
I'll show you the standard size.

2330
01:43:15,231 --> 01:43:18,571
[The example given by No. 3]
- Like this? - Yes.

2331
01:43:18,571 --> 01:43:21,894
[After the slicing lesson,
they prepare for the evening service]

2332
01:43:23,973 --> 01:43:27,091
[Glance]

2333
01:43:27,091 --> 01:43:31,531
To be honest, earlier at the meeting,
when the male manager

2334
01:43:31,531 --> 01:43:34,291
said something about me going to
the Wok station tomorrow...

2335
01:43:34,291 --> 01:43:36,321
I felt like I had to walk on eggshells.

2336
01:43:36,321 --> 01:43:37,421
[Of course you would]
Right.

2337
01:43:37,421 --> 01:43:41,478
- I felt self-conscious around the prep crew.
- I bet.

2338
01:43:42,658 --> 01:43:46,489
[Silence still hangs over the prep station]
It's definitely awkward right now.

2339
01:43:47,251 --> 01:43:51,651
[She finishes a whole container
while slicing in silence]

2340
01:43:51,651 --> 01:43:52,751
[Glance]

2341
01:43:52,751 --> 01:43:55,821
[Glance]

2342
01:43:55,821 --> 01:43:57,598
I'm finished.

2343
01:43:58,351 --> 01:43:59,901
What should I slice next?

2344
01:43:59,901 --> 01:44:01,981
If you're done with that, do the frogs.

2345
01:44:01,981 --> 01:44:03,261
Frogs?

2346
01:44:03,261 --> 01:44:05,731
- Frogs? Okay.
- Again?

2347
01:44:05,731 --> 01:44:08,171
- Okay.
- Frogs again?

2348
01:44:08,811 --> 01:44:12,204
[Now she preps frogs with a smile]

2349
01:44:12,991 --> 01:44:15,601
[Getting into position]

2350
01:44:16,371 --> 01:44:20,211
[Maybe this will be the last time
I chop a frog!]

2351
01:44:21,491 --> 01:44:25,559
[While she nonchalantly slices frogs]

2352
01:44:26,491 --> 01:44:29,121
[The banquet hall's final boss
approaches Sunny]

2353
01:44:29,711 --> 01:44:33,651
[Is she doing well?]

2354
01:44:33,651 --> 01:44:36,751
- The grandmother is always smiling.
- I know.

2355
01:44:37,411 --> 01:44:40,054
Sunny seems to be a very fast learner,
don't you think?

2356
01:44:41,421 --> 01:44:43,611
She seems to have strong hands.

2357
01:44:43,611 --> 01:44:46,427
I could see her strength
when she was using the wok earlier.

2358
01:44:47,071 --> 01:44:49,041
[Ugh]
Of course.

2359
01:44:50,941 --> 01:44:54,051
She's really strong.

2360
01:44:54,051 --> 01:44:56,834
One punch from her would knock a frog out.

2361
01:44:57,551 --> 01:44:59,378
Look at her hands.

2362
01:44:59,378 --> 01:45:01,451
Indeed.

2363
01:45:01,451 --> 01:45:03,171
Look at those hands.

2364
01:45:03,171 --> 01:45:05,283
[The fists of a boxer?]
She's a boxer, after all.

2365
01:45:05,283 --> 01:45:07,021
A real boxer.

2366
01:45:07,021 --> 01:45:09,027
One punch, three frogs.

2367
01:45:09,027 --> 01:45:10,131
Seriously.

2368
01:45:10,131 --> 01:45:12,561
[One punch, three Sung Juns?]

2369
01:45:12,561 --> 01:45:14,031
[Dinner guests arrive]

2370
01:45:14,031 --> 01:45:16,400
Oh, the guests are coming in now.

2371
01:45:17,539 --> 01:45:20,118
[The large banquet hall fills up with guests]

2372
01:45:20,991 --> 01:45:23,981
[Which means orders are pouring in]

2373
01:45:23,981 --> 01:45:25,923
It's starting.

2374
01:45:25,923 --> 01:45:27,281
We have orders for five tables.

2375
01:45:27,281 --> 01:45:29,741
Start cooking for five tables.

2376
01:45:29,741 --> 01:45:32,221
[Orders start coming in]

2377
01:45:32,221 --> 01:45:34,113
Sunny!

2378
01:45:34,861 --> 01:45:36,061
Sunny!

2379
01:45:36,061 --> 01:45:38,730
- Come assist over here.
- Yes, sir.

2380
01:45:39,406 --> 01:45:41,171
[Sunny takes her place at the Wok station]

2381
01:45:41,171 --> 01:45:43,638
[Swish?]

2382
01:45:45,424 --> 01:45:47,845
- Kuaizi.
- Chopsticks.

2383
01:45:48,509 --> 01:45:50,131
She needs to have them ready.

2384
01:45:50,131 --> 01:45:51,747
[Finding chopsticks]
- I need them. - Because she has to...

2385
01:45:51,747 --> 01:45:54,031
She has to do the plating.

2386
01:45:54,031 --> 01:45:57,311
[She grabbed the chopsticks herself]

2387
01:45:58,520 --> 01:46:00,862
He got them for me on day one,
but not this afternoon.

2388
01:46:00,862 --> 01:46:03,340
Oh, you're right.

2389
01:46:05,981 --> 01:46:09,507
[Handing them over nonchalantly]
Okay.

2390
01:46:13,083 --> 01:46:15,091
[Disappointed]
If he doesn't, I'll have to do it myself.

2391
01:46:15,091 --> 01:46:16,541
If he doesn't look out for me...

2392
01:46:16,541 --> 01:46:18,691
- Were you a bit hurt by that?
- Yes.

2393
01:46:18,691 --> 01:46:19,713
Oh, well...

2394
01:46:19,713 --> 01:46:22,628
- That was the only thing he did for me.
- You get disappointed quite often.

2395
01:46:22,628 --> 01:46:23,871
Right.

2396
01:46:23,871 --> 01:46:25,771
He should've at least told me where they are.

2397
01:46:25,771 --> 01:46:27,611
Right.

2398
01:46:27,611 --> 01:46:31,491
[The manager approaches to check Sunny's order]

2399
01:46:31,491 --> 01:46:33,281
Please prepare this after you're done.

2400
01:46:33,281 --> 01:46:35,395
An order for fried corn with duck egg yolk.

2401
01:46:35,395 --> 01:46:37,023
Two of them.

2402
01:46:37,023 --> 01:46:39,841
[Fried corn with duck egg yolk learned earlier]
Fried corn with duck egg yolk.

2403
01:46:39,841 --> 01:46:43,121
[Sunny goes to prepare it without hesitation]

2404
01:46:43,121 --> 01:46:46,301
[Starting calmly with the canned corn as learned]

2405
01:46:46,301 --> 01:46:47,603
Okay, canned corn.

2406
01:46:47,603 --> 01:46:49,261
Open it.

2407
01:46:49,261 --> 01:46:52,081
[Followed by the custard powder]
Coat it with custard powder.

2408
01:46:52,081 --> 01:46:56,467
[Mixing it well so it doesn't clump]

2409
01:46:56,467 --> 01:46:59,939
[Ready to fry the corn with duck egg yolk!]

2410
01:46:59,939 --> 01:47:02,854
[Setting the right plates for the dish]

2411
01:47:03,866 --> 01:47:06,171
[Setting the parsley as well]

2412
01:47:06,171 --> 01:47:07,871
Parsley.

2413
01:47:07,871 --> 01:47:09,951
[Glance]

2414
01:47:10,861 --> 01:47:12,831
[A thumbs up as expected!]

2415
01:47:12,831 --> 01:47:16,291
[Sunny is good!]
In every kitchen, the thumbs up is universal.

2416
01:47:16,291 --> 01:47:17,391
- A thumbs up.
- Like this.

2417
01:47:17,391 --> 01:47:20,947
- That's how they communicate.
- This is the compliment. We don't use words.

2418
01:47:20,947 --> 01:47:25,101
[Sunny works fast and
even observes the cooking]

2419
01:47:25,101 --> 01:47:28,545
[Frying the corn Sunny coated in powder]

2420
01:47:35,747 --> 01:47:37,871
[Staring intently]

2421
01:47:37,871 --> 01:47:40,961
This won't do.

2422
01:47:40,961 --> 01:47:43,131
This won't do. You have to coat it again.

2423
01:47:43,131 --> 01:47:46,171
The powder? Why?

2424
01:47:46,171 --> 01:47:48,356
No, it's okay.

2425
01:47:48,356 --> 01:47:50,960
[Xu Jian Kai redoes it after being scolded]
Do it again.

2426
01:47:51,841 --> 01:47:54,891
- Redo it? Redo it again?
- Redo it.

2427
01:47:54,891 --> 01:47:56,321
Is there a problem?

2428
01:47:56,321 --> 01:47:58,731
There's not enough powder on the corn.

2429
01:47:58,731 --> 01:48:02,275
- It wasn't coated enough.
- You have to go and teach Sunny again.

2430
01:48:02,275 --> 01:48:04,221
[Sunny made a mistake?]
Sunny coated it, right?

2431
01:48:04,221 --> 01:48:06,983
- Sunny was the one who coated it.
- No, this...

2432
01:48:06,983 --> 01:48:08,184
[An unexpected mistake]

2433
01:48:08,184 --> 01:48:09,418
[Will she make it to the Wok station?]

2434
01:48:09,418 --> 01:48:10,926
The powder all fell off.

2435
01:48:10,926 --> 01:48:12,861
It doesn't look good enough to serve!

2436
01:48:12,861 --> 01:48:14,830
All sorts of thoughts crossed my mind.

2437
01:48:14,830 --> 01:48:17,243
It was the first time I felt I'd hit a limit.

2438
01:48:17,243 --> 01:48:19,099
[It's already day two!]
You pinch.

2439
01:48:19,975 --> 01:48:21,851
[But mistakes keep happening today]
Is there something wrong with me?

2440
01:48:21,851 --> 01:48:24,407
This is too salty!

2441
01:48:24,407 --> 01:48:26,342
[Confidence is fading]
In a restaurant...

2442
01:48:26,342 --> 01:48:28,911
[Will the undercover chefs give up?]
I'm starting to have deep thoughts.

2443
01:48:28,911 --> 01:48:33,455
The biggest chance to appeal to the chef
comes when you make the staff meal.

2444
01:48:33,455 --> 01:48:37,850
Can I cook a dish for you?

2445
01:48:37,850 --> 01:48:39,994
[To make up for his mistakes so far]
I need to stand out more.

2446
01:48:39,994 --> 01:48:41,991
[Top Chef mode on?]
I feel like I really need to do well.

2447
01:48:41,991 --> 01:48:44,833
[No longer hiding her skills]
I have a bit of a competitive streak.

2448
01:48:44,833 --> 01:48:46,295
[Seniors are confused]

2449
01:48:46,295 --> 01:48:49,098
In the kitchen, it's all about skill.

2450
01:48:49,098 --> 01:48:51,000
There's no way my food would taste bad.

2451
01:48:51,000 --> 01:48:53,369
[Capturing the seniors' taste buds]
What's more important is the local flavor.

2452
01:48:53,369 --> 01:48:55,623
[A brutal critique that puts chefs on edge]

2453
01:48:56,138 --> 01:48:57,973
[An incident at the Chengdu restaurant?]

2454
01:48:58,701 --> 01:49:00,710
[Massive portions]

2455
